text:
This place is at one of the locales in the Tyler Print Institute building at Robertson Quay. At first is a bit confusing, the name suggests a market, and they do sell a few (overpriced) fruits and vegetables, but it can also appear as a bakery, cafe, restaurant, takeaway or souvenir store. They seem to have a bit of everything.

As a restaurant they have few tables outside where they serve an interesting menu. Ambitious might be the proper word to describe it. They have common dishes, mostly Western, but made with a slight, almost imperceptible, twist, mainly done by adding a touch of a different flavour, which lifts the plate. For example, the sweet potato fries come with a well-balanced curry mayonnaise. More importantly, the food I've had there a couple of times is done with care and precision. Prices seem rather high, but portions are on the generous side, so I think they're fair (it's Robertson Quay anyway). Burgers are big and delicious, and pasta is served in more than enough amounts. Mainstream beers are expensive at 10++ for a miserable half pint, but they have good craft beers at the same price for a bottle. Coffee is not bad, but nothing to rave about. Cakes are tasty, worth trying. An important thing is they make an effort in offering more local products rather than imports, maybe they could make that more explicit.

Inside the shop, there are three tables that serve as a cafe, and there's a shelf that showcases souvenirs of the interesting kind, I'm talking about Singlish "dictionaries" and Teochew recipe books instead of Merlion keychains. While these quirky souvenirs are quickly becoming mainstream, they also sell books by Math Paper Press, which are truly good local gifts.

SPRMKT has a little bit of many different things and, sometimes, it's not quite clear what to expect. It is, after all, a place to have a nice dining experience and find some amusing local products. It is worth a try, the food is better than it would seem.

Mid 30's international traveler walking around town with camera gear, hungry and thirsty. 
Went to Level 33
Took Private Elevator
Receptionist didn't acknowledge me at all. 
Went to the balcony myself. 
No table so I stood in a clear section to look at the view. 
First thing waiter said to me when he saw me is "No Tripod" to take photos. 
I ask for a menu.
Menu never came. 
I left with my camera, my tripod and my American Express.
Went to a food center in China Town
Pigged out
Went back to the hotel. 
Writing a review. 
GREAT VIEW from the balcony tho. 
Make sure you dress up.
Don't bring your camera gear and act all touristy. LOL
It is a fancy place, but unfortunately too fancy for me...

text:
I was recommended to this place by a friend. We got lost on our first visit, cause we didn't really have much time as 'nature called.' But anyway, just a tip, if you're driving, turn into the parking lot of block 128 and immediately turn right after wards. Just follow the road and the shop is just tucked away at the corner.

I have tried many ice cream shops all over the world and I have to say that Creamier is up there on my list. You can just feel that the ice cream was very finely made. It was very smooth and, true to its name, very creamy. I think it is slightly too sweet but it was not overwhelming. The flavors were also quite creative. I had the salted gula Melaka and earl grey lavender. Both were just absolutely wonderful.

I had the ice cream with waffle and it was well made too. It was too crispy for me tbh, but I can understand that most people will like it. I'm just one of those oddballs who prefer his waffles without any crispiness to it. If you're like me, let the ice cream sog down the waffles first, let it absorb those delicious goodies before devouring it.

I can't wait to go back to Singapore and try the other flavors from Creamier.
Too crowded, too loud. It takes more time to find a place to sit and to wait for the order than to eat. Nice for once for tourists.
Probably could be considered a high end food court. Nice variety, from local to seafood to Western/European  selections. Slightly pricey but its still good value.

I'm with Timothy S - what could have been a really wonderful first impression (a wall showcasing bags of hard-to-find speciality coffee they've served? This is going to be damn good!) was quickly squashed not by the delicious smell of freshly pulled espresso, but by a rather shocking pungent smell that engulfed the entire downstairs area. I have no doubt whatever they were cooking up was delicious, but I wasn't ready to smack head first into an olfactory brick wall when all I really wanted was a long black and a place to relax for a bit.

Once I found the back staircase leading to an upstairs seating section (and that there was a fast, free internet connection showing up on my list) I was set. And the coffee was delicious.

This place makes me so freaking happy. Every time I'm even remotely near Tanjong Pagar (so maybe all of Singapore) I think to myself, ohemgee I could get a bagel.

'The Lox' comes with pickled beets that are freakishly pink and delicious. Other innovative sandwiches are also great. 

Tbh these bagel sandwiches get a little messy and filling, but it's Singapore and if you're looking for bagels, it's really only here or Sacha and Son's in my book. (But plz let me know if you find anything else!!!!!)

Yours truly,
A New York Bagel Freak

I like that it's 2 stories and I like that it's just lots of rows of a few stalls so it's easy to explore and it never gets too suffocating. I had the Char Teow and it was good but a bit too greasy for my taste.

text:
Walked by this place by chance and saw this new restaurant at Ngee Ann City. At first thought the name was d'gold cafe, but I'm closer inspection the 'l'  is actually a coffee bean. 

The place wasn't too crowded, about 60% filled. But noticed a celebrity seated near the bar with his family. On display are many mugs signed with well wishes from other celebrities, so maybe I the cafe is owned by a celebrity?

Was given 2 menus by the waiter. 1 is a food menu and the other a drinks menu. This is quite common, but the drinks menu is like 5 times thicker than the food menu. Haa... Although I always order the same old ice tea or ice latte, I decided to check out the drinks menu anyway. The selection of teas is really... Wah...  Also don't know how to describe. You come once a week for the rest of the year, and you probably would not have tried all the teas yet. Anyway, the boring person that I am, I tried the old English iced tea,and it was pretty delicious. Definitely not BOH or lipton brand..  

Back to food, I ordered the pork cheek whilst my wife ordered the Crispy salmon. Both were fantastic. Portion abit small but it leaves just enough room in your stomach for dessert. Which is probably the goal because when a pair of girls came and sat beside us, they were already chittering away about the cheesecake. One of them sat down, looked at the cake display and exclaimed "what? Only 2 cakes left? That's it, Im not going to order a main, I'm just eating cake.". She meant it too. They didn't order anything else, just the last 2 slices of cheesecake. 

I can't say much for the cake, I didn't get to try it. But from where I was sitting it looked pretty good. Nothing fancy about it. Just a classic, tall, moist cheesecake. 

All in all, full marks from every aspect. The service staff are friendly, prompt and attentive. They don't charge for water. Food is good and served in a timely manner and at the same time. Comfortable and stylish ambience. And perhaps some chance to score a look at some celebrities. 

To summarise, pretentious food without the hefty price tag.

text:
Singapore limited edition tea: Calamansi (best served cold)

I've been to almost all of the Lupicia tea shops (except Taiwan, Australia, and a few stores in Japan). This one in Singapore is inside the Great City Mall! It's a bit small compared to the Paris and Honolulu ones! But the staff was really helpful and friendly as always! I sampled the Calamansi tea since it's the only one you can get at the Singapore Lupicia! It was like drinking hot lime tea! lol! The staff recommended serving it cold like an iced tea! I bought a tin of the Calamansi and a box of the Fan Dance (Chinese New Year edition) all for about $29USD!

If you're into finding exclusive Lupicia teas, I also recommend visiting the Isetan Drymarket on Scotts Road. The store is a bit hidden on the Sports Level. But they have exclusive Lupicia teas (Spice Garden, Durian Green, Miss Vanda, Royal Bandung) made just for Isetan Singapore!!! A neat find! :)

Food was good - service was super slow. We came for lunch and there was only 2 staffs. 1 we multi-tasking as the cook. Not a place I would recommend if you only have 1 hour for lunch. Otherwise, worth the try!

text:
Amoy St is a great place to grab lunch if you work nearby in the CBD. It is a two storey food center that has every kind of local food you can imagine. Most of the stalls are good. 

My favorite are the ones on the first level. There is a fruit juice stall with a really nice aunty that has many different kinds of fruit juice combinations. The vegetarian stalls on the first floor are also pretty good. My favorite place though is the chee chong fun uncle. $1.20 for a plate of really good and fresh chee chong fun. This place opens as early as 6:30am. 

Most stalls close pretty early though and are not open on the weekends.

text: Solid four starts. Went early on a Saturday and two of us racked up a nearly $40 brunch. That was the only downside of the trip. Food was good,  coffee was better, great music, nice staff, cool ambiance. I will definitely go back. Loved it. Not sure if we caught a one-off experience but it wasn't too crowded which was a plus.

Fantastic coffee and decent breakfast noms, but it's pricey and the service can be a bit plodding. I love the atmosphere of the place and its story, but I'm not sure it's worth nearly SGD 50 for two people to have brunch.

A+ for flat whites, though!

text:
Maybe I came on a wrong day... A lot of the stalls were closed during my late afternoon visit.

I found the set up a little confusing as one have to go around corners to get to certain areas and the alley ways are narrow with barely enough space to walk around.

I won't make a special trip just to come here for food but if you are in the area, not a bad place to just come and chill. At least one can get a ice cold beer from The Good Beer Company to go with all these street food!

text:
A little too pricey for regular consumption and smack in the middle of yuppie central but the desserts here are really worth the trip.

We had the guanaja chocolate souffle and the After 8 (mint and chocolate) souffle, plus pure origin Venezuela hot chocolate and ginger lemonade to wash it down.

1. Guanaja souffle: Luxuriously dark and full-bodied chocolate flavour throughout, but at the same time extraordinarily light and fluffy. Loved it. Wasn't too sweet, and came with a small jug of vanilla sauce that wasn't that sugary either and complemented it very well. 
There was also raspberry sorbet on the side. I thought that was too sweet but my companion liked the pairing. It's not sweeter than the average fruit sorbet, so ymmv with this one.

2. After 8 souffle: Came with a small plastic dropper that had mint liqueur inside, and a jug of decadent thick dark chocolate sauce. We didn't know whether the souffle was flavoured, and our server told us to squeeze the dropper, so our mint ended up all concentrated in one spot.
The souffle turned out to be plain, more like a stage for the chocolate + mint. If we'd known this, we probably would have spread out the mint a bit more! The chocolate sauce was so good I ate it on its own and then felt like a pig. 

3. Venezuela hot chocolate: Was really good. The thickness was creamy and satisfying, not one of those watery versions you get elsewhere. Flavour was also strong and even. 

4. Ginger lemonade: This had actual ginger slices in the lemonade, though the ginger taste wasn't extremely strong. Refreshing after all that chocolate.

text: Fortunately, there are quite a few places in Singapore to grab a decent cup of coffee, and while I didn't actually end up having a coffee here, it is still one of those places where coffee is basically available at any time of the day. Actually, I just stopped here for a cup of tea, and it wasn't all that bad either, and neither was the price. In fact before I knew it, the tea was in front of me and I was merrily enjoying it. Oh, and it's also open twenty-four hours, which basically means you can also come here first thing in the morning and expect it to be open.

text:
This is the nicest Hawker center in singapore. It's newly renovated, so it better be, but I was surprised just how clean and bright it was. The signage is also very consistent and nice. Because it's so beautiful, it's very crowded, especially with tourists and foreigner business workers.

The food is not that exceptional, but there's a huge variety all in one place, so you're guaranteed to find something you like. We got satay (which is on the street side), basil chicken, pork on noodles and char keay teow. Everything was tasty, but I definitely have favorite places to go for many of these dishes. We also got yummy sugar cane juice. Yum!

Seating can be difficult, especially if you have a large group, so you have to hawk dive for tables sometimes. This is definitely a very Singaporean experience that everyone should experience!

I have been working out of office for two days straight now to get some quiet time to plan and reflect. Yahava is one top of my list forcomfortable place to sit and do some  work while sipping great coffee. No other coffee place can beat them for the taste and price. Try anything on the list- I'm pretty sure that it will be great. They also supply beans to several others places so you can even buy some of the beans back home. 

The food/dessert offerings are alright. However, with Awfully Chocolate, Ice Cream Chef, and the hawker centre a stone throw away, I would prefer to just order coffee here. 

Since It's not easy to come here, the place doesn't get too crowded on most days. They don't offer free wifi or charging point (that I know of), so come with a fully charged laptop. Alternatively, just sit back, sip on the great coffee and read a book.

text:
Yummy bak chor mee! 

I've also had the laksa here which is decent but the star here is the Bak Chor Mee. The dry version is chocked full of porky flavor goodness. Plenty of ingredients between the the minced pork, sliced pork, pork balls, and braised mushrooms combined with the slightly vinegary sauce. The noodles have a nice bite-back texture and the soup to wash it all down is pretty flavorful too. 

As a bonus, they're open super late so you can fulfill your bak chor mee cravings even at odd hours.

text:
Located in the first basement level at MBS, close to the SW entrance, down the first escalator. This hosts a variety of cuisines, all at reasonable prices.

I opted for the Italian Seafood Marinara ($7.80) which was a decent-sized portion of pasta with squid, mussels and prawns in a delicious tomato sauce. Overall, very good value for money at a place that you would expect mains to be in the $10+ price range. However, the mussels were terrible - rubbery, overcooked and probably not fresh.

Props for the cute paging system, and the other options available. If you are in the MBS area, this is worth checking out.

text: Newly opened Gastronomia outlet at the B1 central fountain location in Raffles City mall. Good menu with some great choices, stylish design, friendly service. Demand for seating seems higher than what is available. Some of the floor space is under utilized, looks like a couple more tables can be easily fitted in.

text: Yet another favorite haunt for my caffeine addiction. The coffee is full bodied and yet not too sweet. Coupled that with thick toast or Hebi Hiam Toast, its simply heaven for me. This place is generally crowded during working week but for weekend, I find it relaxing. There is indoors and outdoor seating compared to its usually small outfit in other malls. The outdoor is sheltered and has a high roof so you won't really feel the heat badly. So if you feel like a breather, head outdoors. But for me.. I still prefer the aircon la.

text:
Apart from the other reviews, this small burger bar also does quiches and quick bites to go, which they will heat up for you. 
The mushroom quiche I got tasted good, but it was a little small and I scoffed it down quickly.
I came here on a Friday afternoon around 4pm so it was really empty. Staff were a little bit lacklustre in their service attitude, but otherwise the place looked quite appealing and I wouldn't mind dropping by for a full meal if I'm ever around the area.

text: Their roasted milk tea is thick but can still taste the tea! Order 0% sugar for a more healthier choice! Oh their pearls are chewy and sometimes better than goong cha's (IMO)

This space is incredibly quirky and I feel like they need better pub.
A Malaysian brand 'theme' restaurant, walking it is a series of unexpected surprises.

When you first step in the space looks almost like a kids playpark, step further into the dining area and the first thing that caught my eye was an entire corner decked out as a bridal studio! Gowns, mannequins, flowers, and cutesy stuffed toys... After I sat down I then realised there was also a live band setting up!

The decor feels like a combination of a maid-cafe, garden themed restaurant, and bridal studio! Apparently it's also a wedding hall. I hope so, since they don't look like they do very well on walk-ins for the cafe part of the space.

I was just meeting a friend so I can't comment on the food, but service was polite, and the space was just so charming!

Really hope to come back in the future! :)

OH AND THERE'S FREE WIFI! :D

Although close to Robertson Quay and it's abundance of restaurants, UE Square has been pretty much a barren wasteland.  So when I heard about this new restaurant with the interesting name I thought I'd try it.
Ostensibly it's a salad place.  Which sounded good to me.  The problem was in the execution of, well, pretty much everything.  It took about fifteen minutes to get our drinks served, and another 15 to get our salads.  This despite the fact that there were only a few diners there.   The salads consisted of wilted lettuce that looked like it had gone bad a few days ago.  Veggies that were either past their peak or poorly chosen.   And flavorlessly cooked beef and chicken.   It seems the owners put too much effort into being hip hipster hippies and not enough into learning how to choose ingredients and cook them properly.
To sum it up: Bad, slow service.  Terrible food.   

With so many great places to eat nearby, coming here is a foolhardy mistake.
Cross it off your list.  This is one place that needs to be economically Darwined out of existence.

text: Great plain and almond  croissants, come heated and crispy.  Also, the beef and Arugula, and the cheese, mushrooms and Arugula croissants and a good size and very filling.  Café Latte is smooth and well made.  Overall food and drink quality is high, and the revamped setting and menu is very good, it is a strong competition to Prego at the Fairmont for a quick breakfast and lunch.  They've done away with the silly squirting fountain, and using the space for another coffee/dining place.

My schedule during my trip to Singapore so I was rarely around to try out the different stalls during breakfast and lunch hours (which was when most stalls were open).

Though I did manage to try two stalls:

-A Noodle Story: I think it was overhyped honestly. It was like a dry ramen? Maybe I just didn't really get to enjoy the dish because I had mixed the chili into my noodles not realizing how spicy it would be..but at least the pork belly is flavorful!

-Char Kway Teow: one man operation. The old uncle cooks, collects your payment, handles deliveries on his own (when I visited during the evening). It was a super saucy dish with lots of oysters too! Not to mention how can 3 sgd be beat?

This is a large hawker center in the Chinatown area.    So many choices.

I got a nice Lychee Juice.   People around me were going crazy for Seafood noodle soup.   The Hainanese Chicken Rice is very popular with many stall offering the dish.   

Most food can be had for less than US$5.   Some as low as $2.5-3, depending on what you want and how much food you want to it.   Usually very busy.

text:
Mmm.. the cakes here are delicious. There is very limited seating, about 3-4 tables so we had to get our cake to go. We did manage to find seating elsewhere in the mall.
This is what we had - rare cheese cake. Wow, this was so thick and rich. You won't regret it.
We also had the strawberry shortcake. The sponge was light and fluffy, with layers of sweet strawberry in between. This was topped off with delicious cream.
If you get both, I would recommend eating the strawberry short cake first, because the rare cheese cake will overpower the strawberry shortcake and you won't be able to taste it as much.

text:
I have to give major props to this ice cream shop. Competition for ice cream is fierce in the Upper Thomson area, with 4 or 5 ice cream/waffle shops all within a 5 minutes walk from each other. However, this place stands out so nicely because its 100% vegan, and they don't use processed/refined sugar, only a small amount unrefined cane sugar in their waffles and cane juice in their ice cream. I asked :) 

Even their waffles are vegan, using no eggs or cows milk, and yet it was still delicious. I had 2 scoops of ice cream and a waffle, and by the end of finishing everything, I wasn't like super full or bloated, but I was definitely satisfied. Less guilt, and totally satisfied. That's a pretty good feeling coming out of an ice cream shop. 

The service is also THE NICEST I have come across in Singapore, shocking to say since this is an ice cream shop. All smiles and super sweet. 

They also serve free flow alkaline water with a high ph. I don't know any other ice cream shop, let alone restaurant that serves free flow alkaline water. Do you?!

text:
Came here with the Singapore Yelp Brunch Club and while I loved meeting fellow yelpers, W39 was well, ehhhh. 

It's 2.5 stars (but not quite 3) in my opinion. 

Let's just say, the concept is good but the execution just well, kinda sucked, for lack of a better word.

Food: I got the Hearty Breakfast, and wasn't the least impressed (especially because I was at Arbite the weekend before, and they, they do a mean hearty breakfast - but more on that in another review!) the portions in general just seemed small all around (except for the local options) which would be fine if it tasted amazing but everything just seemed subpar. I also tried bites of the Mee Siam and the Ham & Cheese Panini. The Ham & Cheese Panini definitely tasted kind of like something I could've done myself, however, the Mee Siam was probably the best thing there in my opinion. It was hearty, with a nice sweet flavor to it. I enjoyed that the most. We also got the Honey Lemon Ice Tea which tasted like someone spilled half the jar of honey into. Did they?! 

Ambience: Like I said, great concept, horrible execution. They try to be "cute" with the cute nautical theme and selling old candies we grew up with but it just seems kind of copied. The seating inside is limited and pretty cramped and the service was alright. 

All in all, we left happy to have met everyone but not so happy with the food. Not horrible but really nothing special.

text: Have been coming here to do my work since I was in college and I am surprised that till this day, it is still significantly less crowded than all the other coffee joints in the Orchard area. What I like about this place is that  it is always relatively quiet so you can concentrate on doing your work or having a chat with your friends. There is free wi-fi that can get a little slow but is still much stabler compared to the nonsense you get with wireless@sg. Expect their usual selection of teas, coffees, cakes and dishes -basic enough to satisfy your hunger/thirst woes but I must add that most of the cakes are little too dry for my liking.

text:
I almost always come here only for one thing - their tarts (sliced, whole minis), some of the bests I've had around.

First discovered their tarts and pastries from the tiny neighbourhood store at Tanglin Halt - Fredo Galaxy some years ago, so when Drips opened up at Tiong Bahru (near me), I was thrilled. It's located a little away from the "main attraction" streets where 40 Hands, Books Actually, Tiong Bahru Bakery, Orange Thimble are... so it's usually less crowded, a good thing if you're just looking for somewhere to sit down without having to queue or jostle with others.

Drips dons a modern, white-tiled, high ceiling decor, a nice space to chill but honestly, not one that I dine-in frequently. I do swing by often enough to get their tarts to-go for friends' home parties, picnics, birthdays and such, but that's about it. Looking pass the pastries display to the menu on the wall, you'll find there isn't much else that excites - a tiny selection of sandwiches, coffees and tea-bag teas, mostly somewhat overpriced.

I will still highly recommend Drips for their tarts and cakes, but for a tea time outing that's a little less damaging to your pocket, here's what I usually do: have your pick and splurge on one of their delicate bakes, pack it up in a box... then hop on over to Tiong Bahru Food Centre, order a local soul-warming cup of Teh (milk tea), find a nice big table and dig it. Bliss - economical version ;)

text:
Hipster cafe, great for Instagram-ready fusion--style brunches, as well as cosy date nights. I went there on a Saturday night after 8pm and there was plenty of seats. You order at the main counter, serve yourself water and cutlery, and they bring your food to you. 

We had the mentaiko salmon pasta, the salmon pho and the salted egg mochi w ice cream. For the price, portions of the mains aren't particularly large, but maybe the restaurant's strategy is to leave room for dessert! 

The mentaiko salmon pasta was done perfectly. Al dente pasta, al dente salmon and creamy mentaiko. Mmm mmm mmm! The salmon pho, is a completely different dish. The broth and noodles are delicate, but the salmon was a tad overdone. Otherwise, it's a really nice dish. The salted egg mochi was ah-mazing! I dont know if any other restaurants do it, but it's definitley a heart stopper. They also give 3 mochis, so be prepared to fight if sharing between an even number of people!

text:
While we were disappointed with the Gudetama themed cafe experience, we still wanted to give it another shot and tried Kumoya, which was a pop up themed cafe. We came here when they were featuring Pusheen. 

We only got iced drinks here. But, let me tell you, they were overpriced and bland drinks. Too much ice in both of our latte and frappe drinks. Same pattern like Gudetama cafe - you come here only for the pics. And just like Gudetama Cafe, the customer service was awful. They didn't even tell us that my iced latte needed sugar, and didn't direct me to where the sugar was. If you love Pusheen, though, and you come in time to see Pusheen, this spot is definitely picture worthy. I wished I could've taken a Pusheen stuffed animal home with me, but they're like $45 each. Anyway, you should just come here once to get the Pusheen experience.

I work in RCT and in the evening, there are not many options left. So I go there quite often. Decent sandwiches and soups. 
Sandwiches: I like the brie one, the beef pastrami. For the soups: mushroom and tomato & bell pepper are great. Moroccan carrots - stay away, (it tastes like baby food so if you force yourself to eat it, you will immediately feel like you are a 3 year old, being force fed vegetables you dont like :) )
Good place but slow.... too slow service. Their bred is decent when toasted but the one that's free on the side is actually very chewy... not a fan.

text:
Authentic bakery in Chinatown! 

Food/Drink: the coconut egg tart was something else! We've never had one before and this is just one of the many places around Singapore to get it. A perk is you can get a box full of a dozen pretty easily. 

Price: only 2.20 SGD for one egg tart. 

Atmosphere: We came in in the middle of the day when it was very hot, there was a seating area where you could enjoy your treats that was air conditioned and it was a perfect break from the sweltering heat in chinatown.

Tips: They sell a variety of baked goods other than egg tarts!

text:
A very nice cafe along a stretch of Jalan Besar more known for its motorcycle accessory shops. Opens till late on Fridays and Saturdays, so you can pop over here for a sit and rest after bustling your way through Little India and Mustafa Shopping Centre.

They describe their offerings as "not overly fussy" and "served with warmth" and that's quite an apt description. The baked foods look good with none of that "look at me I'm an exquisite dessert" nonsense and there's quite a wide variety of product on offer. 

While I haven't tried most of the food on the menu, I can tell you that the Salted Caramel Nutella Tart is a sweet-tooth-satisfying crunch, the Chicken Ham & Egg Toast Cup is a unexpectedly comforting chomp, and the Muddy Mud Cake is probably the best chocolate cake I've had in a cafe. Served warm, the Muddy Mud Cake is a delicious gobble that is just moist enough and the right amount of dense that makes for a toothsome chomp that isn't pound-cake heavy nor fleetingly airy.

The Lemonade Jar is a nice refreshing sip but disappointingly, the lemonade doesn't get served in the jar. It's poured out into the large glass with ice instead, which is a perfectly acceptable way to enjoy lemonade. But the jars just look so inviting in the counter.  Anyway, there is also a range of coffees and teas and the usual suspects on the drink menu. 

Butter Studio isn't very large, but it's a cosy, comforting space. You can chill solo or come with your friends for a quiet chat, or for some board or card games that you can find for free use at the corner of the cafe. They host crafty workshops and performances every once in a while too.

3.5 stars. Easy brunch / lunch spot with several branches in the city. Had the crab pasta which was surprisingly delicious (didn't expect a good pasta from a brunch place) - right balance of spicy and savory with a generous amount of crab.

A good spot for meeting up with friends. Vegetarian-friendly.

This cafe is located at the ground floor of heartland mall in Kovan just outside the cold storage. It is of open concept like those modern cafes and kiosks in malls. The menu has a number of food to choose from and i think the cuisine they serve there has a mix of Chinese, western and malay.
I think their food are valued for money and really quite tasty, and also they give pretty big portions of each dish. My friend had ordered the fish and chips and the fish was huge, it came along with chunky fries too, nicely fried. I had one of their aglio olio and the side dishes that came along with it were plentiful i was surprised for the price i was paying.

The boss and staff there were very friendly and they really did their best to provide good service to customers. I would definitely recommend people to dine here as it is a really casual cafe and good service plus food, must try.

text:
The Bao Makers took over the colourful Windowsill Pies shop that moved to Upper Thomson. Instead of keeping the similar type of decoration, the Bao Makers stripped everything to white. From the outside the café stood out quite well due to the colour.
 
On the inside, they also kept the minimalistic industrial look with the cemented walls and wooden furnitures, perfect for hipsters to hangout.
 
We visited the Bao Makers on the last day of our holiday when we were quite full from our previous dinner, but at the back of my mind I always remembered my conversation with Em that I'd go and try the bao at this place. So without further contemplation I dragged hubby in and ordered two baos, the chili crab and Korean bulgogi pork.
 
I like both but the succulent and spicy chili crab definitely delivered more flavour especially with the crispy golden bao. I really like the idea of infusing the local dish into the bao, something that I never seen before at other places. The filling for both baos were sufficient.
 
Since Hubby was craving for dessert he also ordered a pretty serving of lemon meringue sundae. The meringue came as the topping in the shape of rose, the rest of the ingredients were lemon sponge, lemon curd and vanilla ice cream with almond slices. It was delicious but a bit awkward to be called a sundae except if you break the meringue and the sponge cake, then mix the whole thing together with the ice cream. 
 
We had a good time at the Bao Makers and we hope they will be a one stop shop for bao and able to come up with a lot of different fillings next time we go to Singapore.

A quiet location under a block of HDB flats in bukit merah. The staff are friendly. Free wifi is nice. The food is pretty good and reasonably priced

Salmon eggs Benedict $12.90
The eggs weren't very runny but the avocado serving was generous and the toast was pretty good! Loved the salmon

Meaty Mac and cheese $14.80
A Tad dry imho but still a good bowl of Mac n cheese

Will be back!!!!

text:
3.5 
I would give them a 4 but they legit pissed me off.  I ordered a slice of the Beyonce Lemonade cake (yeah I did). It came with a pretty peach buttercream rose on top, I finished half of it and asked them to box it up.  It was delicious. I have had better.  The lemon filling they use was on point but the cake left something to be desired. I think they use a butter cake recipe that lacks complexity (aka well balanced flavor). Anyways, I was planning on having it for breakfast with my morning coffee.  I like to start my day off by looking at something pretty and there was a very pretty buttercream rose on top of my slice when I handed it to them to box it up.  In the morning... I open up my little box and the rose was gone!!!! They took it off my slice before boxing it up!! 

WHY?!?! WHY WOULD THEY DO THAT?!?!?!
They literally ruined my morning.

text:
Situated right at the entrance with beautiful people sitting and eating, there must be something special about this place! 

I wanna look beautiful too and boy, I wanna look cool. 

Luckily there's space and they're opened till 10pm. 

It's expensive wanting to sit here and look cool.. I gave the coffee a miss because I'm not shelling out 9 bucks for coffee I'm unsure of. 

The food is good.. Expensive but...you are paying for location to be seen. 
And it isn't that bad.. The food I mean. 

Had the papardalle pasta ($24)with slow roasted beef cheeks, stewed in a ragout style and little kales and mushrooms. 

The atmosphere is seen to be seen and somebody needs to tell them they need to equalize their music.. Too dang sharp to hang out there now :( 

They offer lots of variety in snacks and coffee. Would I come back? Nah.. Not really. To hang out with friends yeah I could.

Let me make it clear, I am only taking off one star because of the price, as other people mentioned, of the bowls and drinks. As everyone says, the quality is there, but for lunch, it may be too pricey for an every day occasion. 

HOWEVER, I did want to review something that most people don't think of when they think of Grain Traders: THE BAGEL SANDWICHES. Only $10 and you get: a bagel, a protein, a spread, a veggie, and something extra. I always get their plain bagels toasted (they only have 2 types of bagels unfortunately), with jalapeno cream cheese, cured salmon, avocado, and spinach. ALL THAT FOR JUST $10! Great deal! The only sad part is that breakfast is only available 8am-10:30am. Booooo. I want bagels for dinner!

text:
The place was good for conversation as it is not too crowded. The place was like 40% full and we came in around 2.30pm. Service was ok. Server came over twice to get the order. She was nice and efficient. 
Food came quickly. 
All the sandwiches came in sourdough bread and all were too greasy for our liking. Seems like it was buttered and thrown on to the hot plate. 
The meat on the club sandwiches was chunky and moist. The egg was over cooked but was ok. The vege was ok. 
Breakfast dish was normal. The sausage was good with coarse meat, not those overly processed meat. 
Overall service was ok. 
Mostly less stars due to greasy bread.

text:
This is my favourite regular food center in Singapore. Despite its smaller size, it has more great stalls than Maxwell or Lau Pa Sat.

Favourites are:

"Cafe B" run by Chef Boris -- Singapore's best $4.50 pastas done properly al dente and generously sized. Aisle two. 

Chicken rice on aisle three with photo of Lee Kuan Yew visiting. $2.5/3.5/4.5 prices. One of the best Chicken rices in CBD.

Costa Rican food "Mamacita" on aisle four. Good CR style burritos.

Opened by the BreadTalk group, Bread Society is set to be a posher version of the usual breadtalk chain store. While their offerings do look impressive, incorporating european influences with japanese flavours, getting a good bun here is sort of like a lucky draw. While they have interesting flavours, texture of their bread and buns are rather inconsistent. 

I would recommend their chocolate croissants as those are the only products from bread society that has not failed to disappoint time and time again. Their blueberry bread is not bad too but once again, I've had good and bad experiences with it. Their cakes did not impress on the 3 accounts, so if you are looking for quality cakes, go elsewhere.

text:
This is such a cute space, I was torn between keeping it a secret or sharing it for fear it will get crowded over time . But good food must share :) just opened for 3 months as of July 2018, the sourdough open face toasts are simple yet so tasty but so clean after you eat it. I love the banana peanut butter with honey and coconut and the avocado egg toast! Coffee was great, service was incredible and did I mention the smoothie bowls also taste amazing. Nice ambience and chill crowd tucked away on a quiet street. I'll come back for more :) love this place

Ps: There is also a little space selling socially sustainable/ responsible crafts and a nail place tucked in the corner.

They have recently revamped this street with with a glass canopy which covers the entire street, This structure protects hungry foodies from the elements, making a Singapore food crawl all the more enjoyable. Just like any hawkers center, you can move from stall to stall and sample all sorts of munchies and small meals to customize your own little repast. 

I stepped up to a chicken and rice stand, for what was something like my billionth serving of Singapore's signature dish. I enhanced this selection with a nice selection of satay from a nearby hawker stall. Squid and chicken satay? Why yes, I don't mind if I do. Smith Street also has clean seating on the side of the street, and they seem to do a nice job of cleaning up the tables as soon as someone leaves.

However, as good as Smith Street is, it can get a bit sticky for it is outside after all, and unlike a hawker stand, searching for a toilet can be a bit problematic. Still, besides a cornucopia munching to be had, Smith Street is also lined with a number of souvenir shops and specialty items; purchase some Chinese herbs for some old school healing. All and all, Smith Street is a nice change from a typical hawker center.

text:
I cherry picked my pastries based on visual-appeal. I swept sweet bakes like Vanilla & Raisin Swirl $3.50 & Orange Brioche off the shelve, and the former wins slightly but with low marks. The Danish presented in burnt rims, has a notable buttery flavor but not rich enough to remember. The sweet glaze blend gently with the flaky pastry partnering some scattered candies raisins. I wasn't really impressed with the taste, just mediocre.

The Orange Brioche $5.00, was weaker in taste. It didn't sing any buttery tune like other artisanal brioche, no signs of flakiness and rather dry in its texture. There was a small helping of citrus scented custard piped in the middle of the dough, mildly sweet. The orange fruit slice hindered my chewing - simply aesthetically pleasing on the the sweet bread.

The Madeleine $2.00/pc, was a decent piece. Not exceedingly sweet with a soft interior. I'd prefer it to be served warm like db Moderne Bistro so that I could taste the rich buttery structure in its comforting warmth. This one was left in the open, atop the pastry glass cabinet, side-by-side the Financiers. Obviously, it has been overpriced.

The Kumara & Bleu Tart $6.00/pc, champ the fleet in my whole selection when its rivals failed to compete well. The soft and crumbly tart shell adapted quite well to the sweet orange-pigmented kumara cubes gelled together in a pool of coagulated cheese - buttery rich and very delightful. Noticeable flavor is seen coming from the flaky tart, less from the filling.

The battle field continues to be less interesting when the limping Roast Chicken Sandwich $11.50, hit the ground. The fillet slices were dry and fibrous, no traces of flavor until my taste buds met up with the sweet onion chutney above the fresh lettuce. The hard-like-rock baguette made things worst, it was a total shame!

When I thought nothing will be praised, I was charmed by the healthier fare, $8.50 - Quinoa & Lentil Salads. The power grains are executed in perfection along with a mixture of soft lentil which is often undercooked. Carefully seasoned with the right amount of tang lending from the balsamic reduction and some sweet hints from the fresh apple slices, the rehydrated dried cranberry fruits, the heap of rocket greens woke my taste buds with a striking saltiness from the accompanying shaven Parmesan. Just as the episode starts to climax, I felt a cold gush of water came splashing down - the 2 sesame rolls that served alongside was rockier & rubbery than the earlier baguette! What's happening to the breads here? I let out a heavy sigh!

text: If you're after a substantial American style breakfast or brunch Clinton Street Baking Co is a decent option. The servings are massive, just like in The States, but the prices reflect the portion size. They have a lot of the classics here; pancakes, eggs on toast, a big breakfast etc. I thought they might have more baked goods on offer in the display cabinet given the business name, but there were just a few scones and muffins. I opted for the smoked salmon scrambled eggs and was not disappointed.

text:
I'm not sure why I didn't wander into this restaurant sooner since it's so close. Paleo? They sure make it easy to follow the lifestyle. Their menu features salads and meats with veggie sides in addition to the typical bakery delights. Good luck avoiding the breads and pasteries...they look delicious! 

So far, I've had the beetroot, pumpkin and feta salad (skip the feta for the Paleo folks), and it was awesome. Very fresh. I've also sampled their omelet with peppers, mushrooms and ham, which was also good. My favorite so far is their peri peri chicken ($22) because it couldn't be more Paleo with seasoned, grilled chicken breasts and veggies. Don't love too much spice? They put most of the sauce on the side. 

In the Killiney Road area and looking for something healthy? This would be my first recommendation. I'd go here daily if it was a bit less expensive!

text:
Lau Pa Sat was my first ever Hawker Centre and it made a lasting impression. 

This review is based on my pre-COVID experience so I'm unsure what it is like now considering Hawker Centres are so communal. 

When visiting Singapore, I wanted to experience the liveliness of a Hawker Centre and this did not disappoint. There are so many food stands specializing in certain dishes so you know whatever you end up choosing, it will be good. I ordered the duck and one stand and my fiancé ordered Pad Thai at another. Both were good but the Pad Thai was honestly THE BEST Pad Thai I have ever had and still crave it to this day. 

The prices are incredibly cheap and it makes your vacation money stretch. 

Singapore is hot and because Hawker Centres are busy and full of people on their lunch breaks, it gets even warmer. However, there are fans blowing which helps a little. 

If you find an empty seat without tissues on the table, grab that seat! People claim their seats by putting a packet of tissues on the table. It was so amazing to watch this ritual because here in the U.S, not only would someone take that seat, they'd also take the tissues. It was beautiful to see how trustworthy people were with leaving their claimed seats to grab food and how honest the other customers were by not grabbing the claimed seats. 

Overall, this was a wonderful experience and anyone visiting Singapore should come to this specific Hawker Centre. Why this one? Because the Pad Thai is worth the  long flight. Definitely try it!

text:
Quaint little coffee shop based in one of the oldest public housing estates in Singapore. A little nondescript, but unmistakably hip decor - newish designer touches mixed in with just enough vintage Singaporean coffee shop furniture to feel homey without being pretentious. A good mix of residents, young and old, make this less of a hip hangout and more of a local coffee spot. 

Ostensibly a re-do of an existing traditional local coffee roaster, this place does a selection of espresso and pourover brews (v60 and kalita), as well as some cold brew. Single origin beans from the usual places - Kenya, Brazil, etc. Had me a Nicaragua pourover - tasted a tad over roasted but still a well executed brew. Prices are very reasonable too - $5.50 for a pourover that would cost me $7 in a hipper joint. $15.50 for a 250g bag of whole beans, compared to $18-$20 elsewhere. 

Some dessert in the fridge - cakes and chocolate, plus what appears to be flavoured sodas. Didn't try 'em but good to know they have some sweets in case you're a bit famished. 

Definitely a decent and cosy venue for a quick cuppa, and a quiet place for a brief respite from the day's exertions. Will be back.
I thought the coffee and desserts were average at best. Parking around the area isnt the easiest to find too.

This swish little restaurant, tucked away in the Dempsey Hill area is a nice spot for something a tad upmarket. 

For dinner and during the week, I'm sure it's pumping with work catch ups, dates and small groups working their way through the menu.

We came here on a Sunday afternoon and it was very quiet, just one other table in the venue (also Australians, seems to be popular with expats) and a limited brunch menu. 

On weekends, the menu is limited to brunch tartines (open sandwich) and a couple of specials only. We opted for the lobster tartine - definitely as fancy as it sounds. One big slab of bread covered in delicious lobster and toasted gruyere. We also opted for the special, which was truffled chicken. Also delicious and delicately portioned. 

The food is expensive, but the ingredients are high quality too. I did scoff at the $20+ 'Melbourne tartine' of smashed avocado on toast, but then again they charge about $18 for fancy versions of that at home too. 

The service was very attentive (almost too much given how few people were there) and it was a relaxing and quiet break after a full week of living on hawker centre food.

text:
Visited this quaint little coffee shop in East Singapore for the first time today- on a Friday afternoon. It was relatively empty when I arrived & quickly filled up to a nice bustle. 

Knee-deep in my quest for Singapore's best chai latte, I opted for their iced chai latte. It was notably sweeter than the other cups I've tried, but no where near too sweet. In fact, the sweetness coupled with the spiciness of the ..spices was quite the experience for my tastebuds. Definitely a safe beverage choice at Dutch Colony Coffee. 

I'd give 4 stars- the coffee shop is rather out of the way & they do close early. (especially on weekdays)

text:
Tucked between boutiques along the citylink connector, this little Rive Gauche outlet (comprising one refrigerated case and two small tables) is easy to miss. 

Their signature Guanaja ($7/slice) is a cake that one can never get enough of. The light sponge, punctuated by layers of mousse is sandwiched between a shiny layer of rich dark chocolate ganache on top, and a crispy hazelnut base made of cornflake crumbs below. The flavor is well-balanced; though rich, the cake remains pleasantly light in terms of texture, which leaves one craving more down to the last bite. 

Due to the low human traffic here, they have many promotions worth capitalizing on: 
1. Tea set ($6): one slice of cake and tea/coffee. Top up 50 cents for a latte. 
2. Daily promo: All slices of cakes for $5 (not too sure if this is still available)

In conclusion, though Rive Gauche can be found in many places, this branch has a quiet charm that'll definitely bring me back!

text:
Ya Kun Kaya Toast is an extremely popular chain specializing in all things, Toast! 

This fast food joint is known for its iconic breakfast set- - Kaya Toast and Kopi. 

After a quick scan of the menu, we opted for their Kaya Toast set which came with a hot Kopi (subbed for an iced Kopi) and Rendang Chicken. 

KAYA TOAST 
While the Kaya jam itself was decent, the thin overly-toasted breads were dry and unpleasant. Sure, it's made extra crispy to be eaten with the runny egg (which I am not keen on) however, a meal should be pleasing as a combo as well as on its own. Needless to say, this was unpalatable. 

RENDANG CHICKEN
The concept of stuffing this aromatic and spicy chicken into a pocket of toasted bread was genius and a convenient way to eat this dish however, the flavor of the chicken was not tasty. The curry flavor was subpar making this an underwhelming meal. 

KOPI
It leaned more towards a deep bitterness flavor lacking the perfect blend of the sweetened condensed milk. 

While the history of this place is captivating, the food is unimpressive. 

Not a place I'd recommend for a genuine and delicious breakfast spot.

text: I guess you pay for ambience and the rents for restaurants in this part of the Quay?! Good food, but very pricey :)

I was frankly pretty disappointed with the visit. The ambience and layout are really fun and the place looks like it ought to be great. Sadly, the food was only so-so. 
We went for Sunday brunch and between everyone at the table sampled quite a few items on the menu. I had the Ultimate Beef Yard burger and my wife had the Big Breakfast. My burger was slightly undercooked and VERY greasy and the fries (which I had heard good things about) were dry and overcooked. The breakfast items were rather bland as well. Prices (as mentioned in other reviews) are not cheap and frankly very inflated for the quality. 
The place is fun to visit and I suspect that's what you pay for. It is family friendly but very, very noisy for lunch on a Sunday - don't expect any intimate conversation. 
I think this is a low 3 star rating due only to the quirky fun atmosphere but I would not return for the food.

text:
Somehow this is one of the very few original outdoor open air eating locations that survived Singapore's redevelopment. Yes, it has been upgraded since times of old but it has remained a great place to check out a vast mixture of true Singaporean cuisine.

There are two distinct areas of Lau Pa Sat Festival Market. There is the interior where you will find tons of food vendors offering various types and interpretations of food and then there is the outdoor space where you will encounter a lot of food hackers calling you over to their stand.  The interior space does protect you from the elements to a certain degree but the outdoor food stalls are definitely the place to eat at night. 

Overall, this is a great place to check out the various interpretations of true Singaporean cuisine and to truly experience Singaporean culture. One of the great things I find about Lau Pa Sat is that though, sure you are going to encounter a certain number of tourists, it is not overrun by them like say the outdoor dining space of Chinatown.

Overall, fun place to eat.

$12 for a decent selection of 2 bottled beers... what's not to love? I had Stella Artois while my friend had Coronas. It was a pretty cool evening so we seated right outside on the pavement next to what is now a walking street, so it's pretty great for people watching.

Had the Chicken Cordon Bleu, surprisingly big portion with 2 sides (I chose mashed potato and pasta salad)  and fairly decent tasting as well. My friend adores the tictactoe fries (waffle fries really) which are pretty crispy.

Decent spot it you're looking for an affordable night out!

text:
Been here two times already! Both visits for desserts :)
I really love the pudding here. My favourite ones are the milk pudding (which comes with caramel sauce) and coffee pudding (comes with creamer). Not something you can easily find, and it's really smooth and wobbly. I was a little disappointed with the cake though. Tried the special called 'Rose Chiffon', the colour was nice, had a cream cheese frosting, but it tasted a tad too normal. And of course, the slice of chiffon cake cost a tad too much. 

Anyway my friend ate a main course on the second visit and said it was bad. The pork was too dry! I guess I'll still stick to my desserts.

text: I was a little skeptical at first because it kind of sounded gimmicky, but we had such a good experience here. The food was absolutely delicious. My friends got breakfast food that they really enjoyed (side note: I'm pretty sure they put truffle oil in their eggs, so just keep that in mind in case you don't like truffle), while I got pasta with chicken and pesto. I was a little dismayed that they put lemon in it, as I personally do not like lemon at all, but it was still very good. The sauce was so creamy, and the plating was beautiful, as it was for the other meals. We also had a piece of chocolate cake that was amazing - it was rich, decadent, and moist. I split the cake with a friend, which was definitely a good idea because the food is quite filling here. One of my friends ordered Mr Lich's Flaming Brew, which was an alcoholic drink that they light on fire by sprinkling what I think was cinnamon onto it. It was definitely a cool sight, though I'm not sure how it tasted. I'm not really one to go all out with themes like this, but my friends convinced me to wear the robes they had for each of the houses in Harry Potter, and it ended up being a fun touch. Overall had a great time and would definitely recommend for a weekend brunch spot.

text:
We came here for late breakfast/brunch.
We got a table inside. We really like the atmosphere. The apple crumble waffles were excellent. Smashed avocado with poach egg and cheese melt all good.

Live band music with both English and Chinese songs.
We didn't need to make a reservation on a Friday night so kudos to that. Do check out their Fb page for opening days as certain days may be booked for events or so.

Overall the location of the place is excellent at Bugis+ and they have a smoking area outside as well.

Typically you get tapas bites and 1 for 1 offers, great for big groups and intimate gathering for beers! Had their luncheon meat fries and they were fried beautifully with a serving of nancho cheese chips.

They have dart machines in the bar as well so dart fanatics, dart your night away.

For fellow Yelpers and Yelp Elites, do write a review and get a free luncheon meat fries on ur next visit. Do check with the staff on this promotion!

I advise getting there before 6 for a view at the railing. The fries are tasty and the beer sampler is a good value. Still haven't actually had dinner there, but the food looks good!

text:
Would not recommend.

I walked by Flee Away and decided to pop in for a coffee because it looked quite cute... It's decorated head to toe with toys and airplanes with a somewhat vintage vibe. A very kid friendly appearance, but I appreciated the quirkiness nonetheless. Excited by the ambiance, I approached the counter to order my coffee. The woman working was exceptionally rude throughout our entire interaction. I decided to get my order as take away because of her attitude I did not want to linger there any longer. Upon leaving I thanked her and said "have a nice day" to which her response was "yes, okay" without even looking up at me. I was baffled by how such an adorable place could house such a grumpy woman that acted as if my coffee order was greatly inconveniencing her... and the coffee wasn't even any good!

Restaurant out of the way. Serving too small. Overpriced with this kind of quality. Plate was cold. Egg Benedict was so so.

text:
New coffee shop in Asia Square and a much needed addition as I can't say Jewel, OTC, or Starbucks really float my boat. Service is extremely friendly and the owners go out of their way to have a conversation about the coffee. Named after the "optimal temperature" of coffee (according to??) but I would beg to differ given I prefer my coffee piping hot. Currently have an introductory offer for $2 lattes which is quite the steal despite the smaller cup. From discussion with the owner I have tried their Mexican blend which has more of a chocolatey, berry taste (and is my preferred taste) and then when this sold out, also their other blend (name escapes me) which had a citrusy bright taste. I think they should label their beans so you know which one to request. Double shots are the norm apparently so that gets a thumbs up in my book. They have some baked items, which look like half-sized muffin (somewhere between a mini and a standard sized muffin) and they look pretty unappealing (especially compared to the sweet treats available at the neighbouring Artisan Boulangerie Company) and I would strongly suggest they try and up the ante in the bakery department!
There is also a tapas bar as part of 63 celcius. While I would go back to the coffee shop, I would give the tapas bar a miss and this is what has brought my review down... $18++ for a glass of wine that could barely be considered a "glass"... even with the free flow tapas from 4-7pm this was a rip off (and  "flowing" is not a word I would use to describe the frequency of the tapas being distributed). All in all, give the coffee a try, and hopefully the tapas side lifts it game because it faces pretty stiff competition from Cook & Brew, The Exchange, The Bank, Marche and Extra Virgin Pizza.

I used to go to Paul, when I lived in Dubai and occasionally craved a boulangerie (the other options were terrible). It was okay, there.

Here, it's also okay. But not as good as it can be. I suppose when things get this commercialized, you lose the charm and personality that you once had. There's not that much to shout about.

text:
Fight off the touters as you enter the satay-arena and make a beeline for Satay 6-7 

Good value to be had in the combo 6 x prawn/10 x chicken/10 x beef satay @ $S24 and washed down with a jug of Tiger draft beer @ $S19

If still hungry  go the spicy fried rice @ $s4 or Banana Murtabak @ $S8

They serve pretty decent coffee and I liked the idea of coffee beans choices. They actually exceeded my expectation with their coffee and cakes selections, definitely better than many gimmicky cafe out there! 

Definitely a good hangout place because the cafe is spacious and I like their quirky furniture too.

Great management. Had a small issue with the food that was served. Very promptly they took it away, send a manager who handled it with pure professionalism that normal you don't find in Singapore. Great afternoon at the beach, and much thanks to the Coastes team!

I love Ya Kun everywhere else. But we ordered set A at 4.10pm and they told us we'd have to wait 10 mins for the eggs. We got our toast at 4.15pm. But we only got our eggs at 4.35pm. Our drinks and toast are no longer hot. Only writing this because this is the second time this has happened at this branch.

text:
Location is amazing for this place. If you live in Robertson Quay /River Valle area, no doubt you have been clamoring for a nice place to get some good clean healthy food. Salads that make you think, hmm I guess salads are not bad after all. You may have been going home after working in the CBD area and thinking to yourself, "What I would do for a place similar to Grain Traders, or just something else other than the bar food that surrounds the area....well wait no longer true believer because "Eat Me" is here to save us all. The cafe is conveniently located in UE square, in the area where the Kopitiam used to be, and boy am I glad that this was the place to take the space over. Eat Me's tag line is "Lettuce satisfy you" (hehe) and the they do not disappoint. Once you stop giggling at some of the creative names on the menu (like "Posh Spice" and "Big Miss Steak" and finally get your food, your palates are treated to plethora of euphoric sensations. Best of all, you finish the food and you are actually full and you also do not get dragged down or feel heavy. Perfect for after working out. 
I've been here twice now and have tried the Daffy Duck and Big Miss steak, I'm definitely coming to try everything.
The place also served breakfast! I have yet to try but they look yummy.
Oh and they have also just started putting cold press juices on the menu. I had the "coconut, green apple, spinach and cucumber" juice...and yes it tastes even better than it sounds! 
Can't wait to come back to this place!

text:
The baked goods and sandwiches are top quality. Coffee is too, but they only have medium roast beans. This is Asia and they like it medium. I preferred dark roast, and I would rate this bakery a 4-star.

The teh tarik is one of the best that I have had. And the first that I have seen with latte art. This would be an awesome beverage if they make the tea a bit stronger.

I came here a couple months back with a friend and boy do they really need to improve on service. Seating done by a list is not extremely effective if you have a maitre'd who is easily pushed around. Granted it was a Saturday afternoon and from what I've heard (they're always packed), I felt that it should have been made clear that there was a waiting list for seating. Numerous parties after me all sat down at the same seats and were told of their policy and had to get up soon after. Would slapping a reserve sign on the table be so hard? 

On to coffee, we had a cappuccino and long black, the milk wasn't frothed well, and the long black was just the darkest point of my life to say the least. 

Last but not least, everyone around was ordering the french toast, so maybe you might have better luck with that than the coffee?

First time here, we walked in and was greeted with the usual "for 3"? Was told to pick any table and order at the cashier without realizing it's a takeaway only place. Eric didn't explain either. 

When order arrived, I asked for an additional box realizing they likely don't have plates so my daughter could share the food without spilling all over but Eric was reluctant to give us an additional box. 

I wouldn't come back again to a place where customers are made to beg for an additional box which I doubt would be a difference in profit or loss. 

Setting expectations is key and the situations could've been dealt with much better.

text:
Had the lor mee (#116) and fried kway teow (#12) - which also both had long queues.  The lor mee was excellent and much better than it looked!  But the kway teow ($4 portion) was only ok and the portions were tiny!  

You can add cilantro and chilis and black vinegar to the lor mee, which I highly recommend.
Don't know who marked this as good for kids! They don't have a kids menu! And that's just the start....

Big chunks of ice that were in my milkshake, cradled by the large uneaten portion of the hard chocolate topping.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Big chunks of ice that were in my milkshake, cradled by the large uneaten portion of the hard chocolate topping.'}]
text:
Maybe I just have unreasonable expectations, but this seemed overpriced, overprocessed, and mediocre.

I asked what their most popular milkshake was and they recommended the 80's chocolate shake. It came with a scoop of not very good vanilla ice cream on top (instead of mixed in) with what looked/tasked like Smucker's hard shell chocolate topping on top - not something I would normally eat.

Then the milkshake hurt my teeth because there were big chucks of ice in it. Who puts ice in a milkshake? Especially an $11 milkshake? I feel like this is a case of paying more to get a worse product. I wish I had gone to Ben & Jerry's or Cold Stone.

Cheeses and desserts for Saturday brunch', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Cheeses and desserts for Saturday brunch'}]
text:
Been here a couple of times to unwind after work. They labelled themselves as the "world highest urban craft brewery" and man, actually the view up here is splendid! Take the inside seats facing outdoors, as it's really not that chill after all staying outdoors in this 365 summer Singapore.

I chanced upon a post by a friend on the Saturday brunch buffet and decided to give it a try for my big boy's birthday. It's a minimalist brunch compared to the hotels buffet we usually come across, which I like about it as the selection is small but great individually! We made reservation through a 3rd party app, and the staff called to confirm my reservation the day before. On Saturday itself, we were held up by some errands on the morning which we called to delay our reservations twice, and the staff responded positively to our request and I'm truly thankful for that!

The selection are very clear in 1 small confined area. Cold selection, hot selection, cheese, soup, desserts. That's all we've got. There's nothing international about the Saturday brunch. Cold selection includes salami, some seafood, salad. Hot selection includes foei gras, mini eggs ben, mini blue cheese quiche tartlets, roast beef, sausages, and 2 more dishes I couldn't recall. Desserts and cheeses are cluttered at one corner. Well, I'll pass the soup next time. Soup served on that day was a tomato relish sort of soup (well it's not labelled), and it tasted super salty which I stopped after 2 mouthfuls. There's also a selection of bread which you can choose to go with it. Apart from the soup, I love how all the rest are served so nicely.

The highlight of the brunch is definitely their craft beers, beer cocktails, and special beer cocktails of the month! It's your a hardcore beer drinker, you can opt to top it up for the "beer buffet" version from the normal buffet price of $58++. Alternatively, you can order the beer separately. For a brewery, buffet and beer combination is definitely the way to go!

One of the nays will probably go to the service. Staff do not give you much attention and you just gotta try your best to wave hard, or go up to them. My plates are not cleared promptly, neither was my water filled. I don't know if it's the privacy time which they are trying to give us, or they simply don't care. However, they are not rude la, still can make it.

Finally, the view up here is a true win! We enjoyed the lovely view over brunch, which makes our Saturday slow paced and relaxed. They also live up to their name as a brewery for the tasty draft they served! It was an enjoyable weekend brunch which I'll be back again.

After visiting the Botanic Gardens, we were looking for a place to sit and drink / eat something small. 
This place was just across the street and had still one small table left outside. 
Their was no menu, you had to go inside to look at the big board, order and afterwards they would bring your things to your table. 
It was 6pm and there was not a lot left anymore of the sweets (like we saw on the pictures here on Yelp), but there were still many pizza slices. We went for the vegi slice (7,5S$). It was served hot, with a wide variety of vegetables, but unfortunately the pizza was somewhat dry. Therefore only 3 stars, but it could have been more.

Unlike TCC, Nespresso Boutique is the place to go for coffee lovers. 

In this boutique they only do coffee, nothing else. And they do it with style. Hip Nespresso machines brew espresso from coffee capsules, a type of pre-apportioned single-use container of ground coffee and flavorings. They have a standard 10 flavors with every 2 months a Nespresso special, a good reason to visit the store again. 

The Nespresso Aeroccino Milk Frother is just amazing. Put your favorite milk in it, push the button and it creates a froth in half a minute, which is thick, dense and creamy and just perfect!

The ambiance of the store feels luxurious and modern. The staff is professional, attentive and kind. 10 capsules sell at S$ 9,90.

text:
This hawker center is a bit out of the way, but worth the stop if you have time! After visiting a couple of other hawker centers, this one was your typical place of various food stalls and such. Do note, that if you need to go to the restroom, it will cost you ten cents to do so.

For most of the food here, the options vary from porridge to pasta to the typical dishes you see at hawker centers. I didn't know what to get so I conducted a small experiment. Instead of ordering whatever looks good to me, I simply chatted with some of the locals and ordered food based on their recommendations. Result? Everything I got was DELICIOUS. One of my favorite items was the Thai style noodle dish with wonton soup. The stall was located in a dark ish looking corner of the place. The wonton soup = yummylicious. The broth was perfectly seasoned and the wontons itself were savory and filling. For only $4, you get both the wonton soup + the noodles. Noodle dish was quite tasty, with the fresh cut BBQ pork and the seasonings on the dish wasn't too overwhelming. For other small dishes I tried, I really enjoyed the curry flavored puff and the fried dumpling. For the puff, the outside was nice and flaky while the inside tasted legitimately like good Thai yellow curry with its potatoes and chicken. As for the fried dumpling, this was surprisingly filling! The inside was mostly chicken, potatoes and small veggies and it had a nice spicy kick to it.

Overall, I really like the vibe of this place. You don't see too many tourists and the locals are friendly and nice to talk to. Not sure if it was the time we went (late afternoon), but there was hardly a long wait (except for one stall in particular) for most of the food stalls. Definitely a relaxing eating experience at this hawker center.

text:
I'm not a fan of Hanis in the least. The prices are fairly cheap, but the "Western" food they propose has never appealed to me, and I'd much rather have a meal at the nearby Bras Basah coffee shop. 

A regular patron of the National Library, I have found myself desperate enough on several occasions to grab a quick bite at Hanis before going back in to continue with research. The coffee is pretty good and very cheap, so that's quite a draw, but the quick bites that you can just grab and go are pitiful. I've tried their tuna sandwich, and I'm certain I could make something better at home. 

I have certainly learnt my lesson after those first couple of experiences, and now avoid Hanis as far as possible.

Double: $7.50', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Double: $7.50'}]
text:
Over the course of several days in Singapore recently I was on a quest to get a hold of the best ice cream in town. After a bit of research, I narrowed my options down to:

Apiary
Creamier
Lickety

Time for a heads up review.

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

All three of these spots have comparable atmospheres, with Creamier coming out on top, Apiary being a great neutral iteration of a contemporary ice cream shop, and Lickety being maybe the weakest of the three just by a smidge in that they don't accept credit cards, which was frustrating. 

Apiary: Star (1)
Creamier: Star (1)
Lickety: Star (1)

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

Prices are comparable across the board at each of these shops. Apiary was the priciest at $7.50 for two smallish scoops, Lickety was $4.50 for a single scoop, and Creamier was $3.80 for a single scoop. Good pricing.

Apiary: Star (2)
Creamier: Star (2)
Lickety: Star (2)

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

When it came to flavor and consistency, there was a clear winner here in Creamier, which had a fantastically smooth, creamy, and flavorful Salted Caramel. Lickety and Apiary were both good, but Apiary, the weakest of the three, was over frozen whereas Apiary was good but not great. 

Apiary: Single Star (3)
Creamier: Two Stars (4)
Lickety: Single Star (3)

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

Maybe surprisingly, I wouldn't be excited to come back to any of these ice cream spots, but maybe that's because I'm simply so spoiled by the stacked Los Angeles ice cream scene. 

Apiary: No Star (3)
Creamier: No Star (4)
Lickety: No Star (3)

text:
The DC cafe has fantastic themed decor and menu items. There's a LOT of options to choose from and it's a cool place to look around if you're into the comics/movies, and they have a lot of neat replicas. 

I got a chocolate themed drink (don't remember the name) that was a chocolate OVERLOAD. It was chocolate ice cream with gobs of nuetella, chocolate syrup, toasted marshmallow and whipped cream topping. 

It sounds really good, but the chocolate they used tasted so artificial that it ruined the drink for me. I usually don't have high expectations for novelty drinks, but it was really hard to even drink the fake chocolate taste. 

The service was also very, very slow. There was no one in the cafe but we had to wait 20 mins at the cashier for someone to see to us. It seemed like the staff was avoiding us at one point. 

The concept of the store is cool, but I would suggest going for a simpler drink if you want to visit.

Had Saturday lunch here with a couple of friends. I had a beef burgers with rainbow fries. The fries were fantastic. The beef was hard and undercooked in some parts 

Service was ok. They seemed understaffed.  Aircon was terrible. It felt hot in the middle of the indoor eating area. It was noisy too.

text: Uber local, a bit grimy and pay for use toilets- Hong Lim came highly rated - however, found that the food at Maxwell seemed to be of higher quality and the hawker centre cleaner. We had the famous pork noodle and fried kway teo which wasn't really anything to write home about. We enjoyed the curry puff and the rice dumplings (nyonya rice dumpling was really different and yummy). But next time I will just give this one a miss and try the Chinatown one or go back to Maxwell to get my fill of local food.

text: My fav bagel place in Singapore! At this location, I like the spam bagel. I recommend adding a hash brown (usually I do that for my Husband cos he loves hash browns) but it's good enough on its own. I also like the avocado one (sofrito?) and add a slice of bacon if you feel like it. Otherwise I go for the blueberry bagel with fruits. My go to breakfast place in my hood.

Love the strawberry souffle and the berry berries cake. 
the cake is light, the cream was good too and it didn't leave any after taste :)
Ice cheese tart was good, but the cakes are far better.

text:
Venue 5/5 
great ambiance and atmosphere with clean and well-maintained venue, always appreciated. The place is spacious indoor as well as outdoor. 

Service 5/5 
attentive and helpful service throughout. 

Food 4.5/5
we ordered pork ribs that comes with grilled corn and mashed potato, and it is as good as it can get. You can slice through the meat with just the weight of the knife and it melts in the mouth. The mashed potato is very fresh and goes well with the meat, no additional sauce needed. Can't really comment about the corn aside it being fresh since I don't like corn. 

The next food is prawn risotto which is first class, although I am not a fan of el-dente rice, therefore it is not as enjoyable as it could, but I appreciate the food prep and quality itself. The sauce is perfect, flavorful but not too much, the prawns are fresh and prepped excellently. 

I give an overall score of 4.5/5 because I haven't tried other options that will make me a regular yet, but will try since it is a nice place to hang out and chill while enjoying a good food and wine. A bit pricey but reasonable with the food quality offered.

text:
I usually like the matcha latte and the shaved ice at Tsujiri. This is a new outlet across the road from 313@Somerset where it used be at. 

Somehow the shaved ice and matcha latte here are not as good as those I had at 313 and at 100 AM (also closed down now). I am not sure what is the issue but the taste is not there. 

The place is also quite tiny and the walkway just fits the width of a stroller.  So if you are going to bring your child with stroller, it will be better to sit near the entrance instead of all the way inside.

I am just glad that there is still an outlet in the Orchard Road area.
