Fish tacos', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Fish tacos'}]
text: We stay in the area. The food is great, I love it. One of the reasons I come here is their selection of "craft beer." The reason I'm marking Burp low on this rating is because they don't replenish their stock of actual craft beer. The past 2 times I've been, they have been out of stock on 2 out of 2 IPAs that they advertise on their menu. They deserve a 4 out of 5,  but will not get that to me until they up theirs craft beer game.

I live in the CBD and as such, Lau Pa Sat is my closest hawker center.  And although a zoo during the work week when at least 100,000 blue collar workers are looking for lunch all at the same time, I find this place really quite nice during off hours and evenings (on the weekends, some places are closed, thus why mid-week is better). 

Lots of seating, loads of cheap food options for any craving, and on the land of historically the first open air markets like this in Singapore countless years ago, Lau Pa Sat is a little chunk of history amongst the urban jungle growth of Singapore's financial district. 

In addition to the Satay Street experience that is available every night street side (See Yelp "Boon Tat Street Food Market"), I am addicted to Thunder Tea Rice served from the Thunder Tea Rice stahl at Lau Pa Sat.  A bowl of rice/quinoa, topped with green onions, peanuts, basil and dried anchovies, then you pour over a thick layer of green tea...it sounds awful, but such a healthy, hearty food discovery of mine I love.  A bit salty, unique flavors, fresh.  You can then get it as a set, with tofu and a fried egg all for like $8 SGD.  But from vegan options, to Chinese, Malay, Indian, fresh juices, bakery items, beer....there is a lot to be found here. 

Now a local would say that this is not the best hawker center in Singapore and I would not disagree (Tiong Bahru might be my favorite!). You will always find more authentic options the further out you go from the tourist areas for sure.  But if you are a tourist and looking for your closest option to MBS and the harbor area or you live downtown like me, Lau Pa Sat is your closest option and a relatively decent, clean one at that.

text:
We went for lunch to rider's cafe on a day when the weather was amazing - very pleasant, not too sunny. The ambiance is very laid back and nice. 
Food for us was ok, nothing spectacular. We did like our milkshakes and juices though.  
We had scrambled eggs, chicken blt, beef burger and pasta.

Quality was worth the money. However, taste was lacking the punch and resulted in unsatisfactory meal. Both types of pasta were soaked in sauce although the serving was very generous. Definitely recommend their nachos fries and pulled pork burger, they were SUPER DELICIOUS!! I love what they have done with the buns. Unlike the usual toasted, it's baked until shiny golden brown. I was sold for its' presentation. Thumb down for the chocolate tart though, it wasn't the ending I had hope to have. It's worth the first try, but not convinced to visit for the second time.

text: Excluded location tucked away in Fairway Drive near the Singapore Turf Club. Rocked up on a Saturday for brunch one weekend. I didn't have a booking, and Im not too sure if they take brunch bookings, though had to wait for a wee bit to get a table on the verandah. No air con in this place, though they have done well to make sure it quite comfortable and airy. Straight forward comforting food here, think shepherd's pie, beef burger, eggs ben etc etc. Well priced items, freshly squeezed orange juice always wins extra brownie points in my books. Had the shepherd's pie which was ok, would of gone down better if it was perhaps made in the classical way with mince lamb as opposed to braising diced lamb.  Service, at least the young girl who served or table had to be one of the cheeriest I've had in Singapore.

text:
Came here with two church mates as one of them wanted to try out burgers for dinner around 7.00 pm on a Saturday. Located walkable distance from Tanjong Pagar MRT and next to famous ramen chains. 

After exploring the menu, I decided to order Prime Beef with Streaky Bacon. Yes, I am a fan of bacons. And Gruyere cheese sounds unfamiliar. For the beverage, I asked one of the staffs whether the ice lemon tea was homemade and when she answered it was, I ordered that.

Price wise here was a bit steep. For the meal, you can either get the wedges for the price listed on the menu or add-on for other side dishes. I decided to try truffle fries with the burger.

For the home made ice lemon tea, it is highly recommended. But unfortunately they placed too much ice cubes inside the glass that lost its taste after 20 or so minutes. Could probably ask them for less ice. 

For the truffle fries, it was good if consumed before 10 minutes. Unfortunately I left them out in the air for long and they turned soggy even though the truffle fries were of thin cuts. 

For the beef patty, I ordered it medium rare as that is what I normally choose for burgers. Sadly it was not as juicy as other Yelpers had mentioned. The bacon was chewy to my liking and the buns were nicely baked. 

Store wise, it is not so spacious and could only contain maximum 15 customers. So to avoid the crowds, you might need to come earlier. Portion was reasonable and it did satisfy my hunger.

text:
It's a hawker centre, a paradise for food. Albeit this place is relatively small for a hawker centre and the whole thing is under construction (you have to walk the way around the building site), this place offers whatever you feel like. Meeting up with friends who have different taste in food from you? No problem. You can find anything.

I had noodle soup first time I was here, the second was fried cockles kway teow. They have also the famous chicken rice (blame my not-eating-poultry- policy) but I didn't taste any. It's a perfect walking distance to downtown Chinatown, so if you feel like you don't want to go where tourists go, go here instead.

text:
This was a very solid breakfast that felt very authentic.

While this was my first time having kaya toast, the down-to-earth staff and the other people reflected how this isn't a tourist trap type restaurant. Now about the actual food

Kaya Toast - kaya jam is made from eggs, coconut, and pandan. While eating the kaya toast, the flavor is primarily sweet with a hint of coconut richness and a whiff of floral pandan, but sweetness is really the primary impression here. Also, due to the generous spread of butter/margarine, kaya toast feels a lot heavier than you might expect. I thought that the soft and runny soft boiled eggs would be too much for me but I think the quality of the eggs are better here or they're just perfectly cooked. They didn't have any of that raw eggy aroma that can sometimes make me retch a bit.

Milk Tea - not quite as rich as hong kong milk tea. I think the UHT milk gives it a bit more of a cooked milk flavor which is quite nice. It's not too sweet, has some decent depth of tea flavor.

text: A cute little cafe tucked around Little India..you will easily miss this place if you are not attentive..the interior decor is simply amazing and you will feel you are in a Harry Potter set..the name of the drinks are also very interesting - definitely try the Elixirs potion! We tried the creamy carbonara with mushroom and it was delicious. The choco nana tella toast with the caramelized banana was also pretty good..

Wandered over on a rainy Friday after collecting prewedding shoot photos from our bridal studio nearby! :) Noodles were great, al-dente and with a yummy sauce, would've liked more chilli! Haha.

Ordered a plate of char siew/siew yoke/roast duck. And a small bowl of wontons (4 of them inside). That, with 2 plates of noodles, came up to $19! No idea how they counted.. I guess ordering normal noodle bowls each would've been cheaper. Ah well.

Anyway, roast duck was pretty gd, tender. Char siew was, as others have described, very caramelized (read: sweet) and fatty! My my... It reminded me of satay a little, actually. perhaps because of the caramelization. I don't like fat, but I could see how people would like this.
Siew yoke was crispy, I'm also not a fan because of the fat, and some parts of it were pretty salty. But fairly tender meat, where there was it.

Wontons had the crunch of water chestnut bits in it, pretty gd soup.

Guess I wasn't crazily wowed by it, but it was pretty good. Would like to try their soy sauce chicken next time!

This has now become my favorite sushi place in Singapore!  

what is there not to love?  they don't put tons of mayo on every roll they make, the fish tastes very fresh, everything is made right there in front of you (if you sit at the counter).  I also love the fact that you can get other Japanese dishes, like curry rice and udon.

i think my favorite little nuance is that they allow you to pick a unique sake class whenever you order a sake and will even let you try them before you buy them.

check this place out, but don't tell too many people as it is small and i still want to be able to get a seat!

I usually don't get to go out exploring during lunch so I never knew that there so much good food near my workplace! Luckily I've been able to have a more flexible schedule this month, hence the opporturnity to explore the Tiong Bahru hipster area thoroughly 

This is probably the most un-hipster place in the area but I LOVE IT because it has so many good stalls for cheap. You could come here everyday for a week and not get sick of it because there's just so much variety (tried and tested)

Heads up that most of the stalls are closed on monday (something to do with the slaughterhouses not being open).

So my favourites so far are the

- Zhong Yu Yuan Wei Wanton noodle for the ARMPIT CHARSIEW!
- Tau Kwa Pop store for the TAU KWA POP!
- Lee Hong Kee Roast for the ROASTED MEAT AND RICE! (chili was exceptionally awesome)
- Hu Ji Fishball Noodles for the FISHBALL NOODLES! (this stall only, there were 3-4 fishball noodle stalls in the area)
-Hwa Yuan Porridge for the FRIED PORK INTESTINES PORRIDGE!

Large, spacious, well-ventilated even in this awful haze and sheltered from the sun and rain. And you could have an entire meal for less than a main at any other place in the area. 5 stars for sure!

text: A very beautiful cafe, artistically decorated with great coffee choices! Highly recommend this place for a laid back afternoon or evening with a friend. There is brunch available too

We absolutely loved Lau Pa Sat... it's a hawker centre, so don't expect frills, and has been refurbed...

The food is simply amazing here - you can pretty much get whatever you want...  we opted for Indian Vegeterian, some fresh juices and some amazing pastries...

Three Ganga's Onion Rava Masala Dosa is absolutely delicious! :-)

All fabulous - highly recommended... ignore the drivel that people have posted saying it's a tourist trap - whilst it is becoming more touristy, we wouldn't go as far as to say to avoid it and it's a tourist trap... you will love it...
Best cupcakes in Singapore. Nuff said. The salted caramel and the earl grey lavendar ones are INSANELY good, and I'm not even a dessert person!

I had a massive craving one day for financiers and was really pleased to find a place that made them fresh. While they are pricey ($3.50 each), I still got two to try - the matcha and regular one.

They were still hot from the oven when I got them, and wow! Nothing beats soft insides, crisp exterior, and a rich decadent buttery taste altogether. So simple, so good.

Come and get a few for yourself, and eat it right away!

text: It's in the middle of nowhere but it's by the river and when you get there it is very pleasant. Do not count on public transport though. We came for brunch and the food was ok. Waffles were good. There will definitely be a part 2 to try out the other food. #maneklady #manekeats

Sunny lovin&#39; and coconut latte', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "Sunny lovin' and coconut latte"}]
text:
Went to Craftsmen Specialty Coffee at their new Novena location for brunch on a Sunday. We ordered 2 egg dishes (Sunny Lovin' and Craftsmen Breakfast) and 2 coffees (coconut latte and iced salted caramel latte). 

I asked about the difference between a regular and large sized coffee so I would know if they just pour in more milk for a large or if they add an extra shot of espresso. The answer I got from the barista was confusing as he said it had 4 shots of espresso. Coffees both came out after about 10 minutes and they both tasted great!

The Sunny Lovin' arrived after about 20 minutes. The Craftsmen Breakfast took 30 minutes. By the time the second plate of food arrived, the first meal was already finished being eaten.

Half an hour is too long to wait when all that needs to be cooked is bacon and eggs. Warm up some baked beans and toast, throw on some rocket and dressing and 2 pieces of smoked salmon and that was the rest of the dish.  Combined with the $20 price tag and meals coming out at staggered times; the great coffees just don't make up for the poor service and long wait times. 

The washroom lights are activated by a sensor, however it did not work consistently. As I was in there the light kept turning off and not turning on. Try as I might waving and flailing my arms, I sat there in darkness and went about my business. Even after standing to wash my hands, the lights did not turn on. 

After speaking to one of the staff they checked into it and the sensor is working. So maybe just bad luck for me. 

If you're looking for a good cup of coffee to go then you're in the right place. If you're expecting value for their food and quick service then I would not bother going here. 

Pros:
-great specialty coffees
-free water(?)

Cons:
-long wait time for food
-orders do not arrive at the same time
-slow service
-expensive for what you get (imho)
-washroom light sensor inconsistent
 
Overall: 3/5

This was there first weekend open so I'm sure they had difficulties. They had already run out of some of the items on the menu when we arrived at noon. 

Really hard to think of pros other than the coffee but will return to try brunch again in a few weeks and expecting a far better experience.

text:
this is one of the rare finds in singapore. you are immediately greeted upon arrival at TFBB with a warm smile and a quick check of the reservations list (note: do reserve on weekends. they are obviously fab). I was seated in a comfy corner and menu and order list are all there. 

the menu... simple and easy to understand. well designed and obviously fab. i wanted to approach the counter to order but was immediately attended to promptly and my bff's crispy requirement to her pancakes addressed. i was escorted to the cake/pies/desserts from heaven section (maybe I have that i-need-dessert-now face). all the specials were introduced in detail and I felt at home. like how you will introduce your prized collection to your guest.

our orders of extra crispy pancakes and croque monsieur was well done and served properly. granted they kinda forgot my extra cup of latte ordered but overall they were attentive to detail. me and my friend left the table to decide on the cakes we wanted and when we returned to the table, voila! our water was refilled and my friend's tea was topped up with more hot water! this was without us asking! i am impressed!

While they have a policy on weekends that the turnover per table is 1.5 hours from reservation, we were not rushed out of TFBB. However, I can see why they need the tables. everyone wants a taste and feel of home on a saturday!

the dessert was well done. i had the blueberry yoghurt cake while my friend had the raspberry cake. very well done and not too sweet. goes well with a cup of coffee. one gripe is that their latte art needs a bit more work (not consistent and a little sloppy).

Overall, this is not just another restaurant checked off the list. a very impressive service staff that makes you keep coming back because you feel welcomed and at home. of course the dessert junkie in me is prepping for the next visit to try ALL their cakes. 

TFBB, you live up to your name. continue to always serve fabulous food in a fabulous fashion. you have won me over with ur extensive range of cakes and sweets but most importantly, your hospitality. thank you for starting my saturday right.

A slice of the Elysium Fields in Singapore...the sun shines, children run through the sculpture garden, fresh herbs scent the air and even the cocktails are good for you!

We thoroughly enjoyed our Saturday lunch at Open Farm Community.  I have long been a fan of Tippling Club and Open Door Policy and we finally snagged a reservation at Open Farm Community (tip: indoor seating fills up fast!).

While the prices were hefty, when you keep in mind that the ingredients emphasize the freshest and most natural possible, somehow your wallet won't wail quite as loudly...

Food was good, service was extremely attentive and snappy and the ambiance was convivial.

The only thing we might not order again were the clams...after paying 2.50 / 100 grams of clams in decadent squid ink butter at Dancing Crab, it was very difficult to reconcile paying ~20 for a small bowl of clams.

PARTING THOUGHT: We lucked out as our visit coincided with the once a month farmer's market...everything from cocktails by bar stories to small batch gourmet goodies to purveyors of fresh seafood and meats were on feature, adding to the festive atmosphere!

Coffee bar', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Coffee bar'}]
text:
This isn't a regular Starbucks, but a Starbucks Reserve store, that means they have a different bar with a couple more coffees on offer. There are a couple more drink choices with a different menu. My favorites the Butterscotch Latte and the Shakerato affogato.

This store is constantly crowded ever since the PLQ mall opened, and it's hard to find a seat especially on weekends. 

Yes, I know it's a Starbucks, so it's not exactly batch roasted craft coffee. But when you need a consistent caffeine (and/or sugar) hit, Starbucks is fine.

(P.S. It's takeout only now during the circuit breaker, and the reserve bar closes early at 9pm)

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/THD_SpYZILd34ROIly5bBw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/chettynad-curry-palace-singapore?reviewid=k3-9MTaHM6KODa41Gs0YWw&select=THD_SpYZILd34ROIly5bBw', 'altText': 'Photo of Chettynad Curry Palace - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: This is a banana leaf oriented place. That means you go in and choose what type of thali you want. You can choose a mix of veggies with a meat of your choice. The quantity of rice given to you is a bit too much. You will fatten up if you eat here too much. It's a very south indian sort of a meal. They have some nice vadais as well and a really lovely coffee. It's a good 4 pm snack place for the coffee and vadai. The inside of this place looks like a school canteen. The service is pretty decent and the waiters always have a smile. Beware this is a heavy meal.

Looks great from the pics and menu online. We arrived and got a seat right away, however when we ordered, most things were sold out and the waitress stated that our food would take 50 min (Eggs and French toast) - why it would take so long boggles my mind. We decided to order drinks and leave. Bad business if they have such a problem w/cook times and turning tables.

The Assembly Ground used to be one of my haunts when I worked in the city area. The coffee was good, meals were a bit pricey and the portions were a little on the small side. 

 Revisiting this place after about a year, I was disappointed by how far the quality had fallen. I had their set meal - chicken skewers with aglio olio pasta which came with the soup of the day and a choice of drink. 

The soup of the day was pumpkin- way too sweet although the texture was nice. 

The main was... a joke. The pasta was barely enough for my 15 year old nephew and parts of the chicken were undercooked. 

On a more positive note, some of my friends who ordered the ala carte said their food was good. 

Avoid their set meals at all costs.

I'll admit I'm biased because I love anything book related.
Let me try to be objective though.

Came in on a Sunday for brunch (today, actually)

Had smoked salmon set sans the salmon, because vegetarian. 
Flat white. Long black. 

My friend had the smoked salmon set and vouched for the edibility of the salmon, hot cocoa, and we shared a French toast set. 

Food was great, waiting time was Long, even though the place was not crowded. Worth the wait though. Price is average for cafes. Decent portion size.

Music is old fashioned jazz-ish music. Not loud enough for me, but then again, to each their own. 

Service was great. Attentive, friendly, non-judgy even though my half-asleep brain asked weird questions about the menu. 

Bright enough for study/work/reading. 
They also have a great selection of books to read. 

If you're so inclined, it's a great place to transition from coffee to wine/beer. 

All in all, an experience I wouldn't mind repeating the next time I have an itch to be outside on a Sunday.

text: My go to coffee joint whenever i'm in the area. The ambiance is nothing fancy, but the coffee is probably the 2nd best I've had in Singapore (pm me if you want the first), and I drink a lot of coffee! Try the flat white, Melbourne style and with velvety microfoam. They also usually have at least 2 selections of beans to choose from.

text:
Ever since i moved to telok ayer for work, I notice there is always a lot of people enjoying their coffee outside Sarnies when I walk to work in the morning.  Putting aside the question of why so many people can have a sit-down breakfast during normal working hours on a weekday, I am curious about Sarnies' breakfast offerings. I have allowed my curiosity to build up until one morning last week when I found myself particularly free and decided to venture inside Sarnies.

As i pushed the door and stepped in, I seem to have walked from Telok Ayer to England, perhaps some cute little cafe in East London. I could not help notice that the overwhelming majority of the clientele is angmoh and just a second ago, I was surrounded by the laughter of uncles enjoying their kopi at the kopitiam next door so wow! that was a bit unexpected.

The set up is simple, there is a huge counter where you order and get your food and drinks and then a few tables and chairs against the wall and filling up the rest of the limited space.  A lot of people seem to opt for the outdoor seats which is a pretty good spot for people watching on the busy strip of telok ayer.  

Having quickly scanned the menu on the board, I decided to get the salmon cream cheese bagel since I have not had a bagel for a while (actually never in Singapore to be accurate).  I was a bit disappointed that I could not choose the type of bagel. It is definitely not cheap, my bagel came at a cost of almost S$10 and with a flat white that brings the total damage to 14. I mean, to be fair, the bagel is huge and if you are willing to pay 10 for a sandwich in the cbd this is acceptable but still, $14 for breakfast seems a bit on the high side.  I opted to bring my bagel back to the office since the place is too packed.  Delighted to find that they have taken the time to wrap my bagel up in foil so by the time I sat down at my desk and opened the wrapping, it's still nice and warm.  The bagel itself is pretty good, soft and smooth cream cheese that blends well with the salmon and the portion is quite generous.  I really enjoyed it so quality wise I cannot complain. I heard their brunch menu is pretty good so will come back and try.

I have to admit we didn't really know what we were eating. But a very friendly Singapore couple helped us eat it and then gave us good tips on the rest of our travel. We had the typical Singapore coffee, which has condensed milk in it. Too sweet for me, but the partner loved it.
An extremely busy cafe and pastry spot in Wisma Atria with no shortage of business

text:
It's a Sunday brunch ...... 

Upon arrival, the service crew show us to the seat ..... The ambience is good and cozy but it's alittle too noisy for me. Plates cluttering drives me crazy as the service counter just write behind the tables. Service crew was wiping th plates dry.

As for the food wise I ordered the Corn Beef Hash $17, Babi Pong Tay $20 and Roti Babi $14.

Corn Beef Hash the taste is nice and it's cook with the baby potato but I felt it's alittle dry. It would be alittle too much for 1 to consume as it can be alittle overdose.
My friend commented that the Babi Pong Tay is nice and the meat is so soft and tender. Lastly, the Roti Babi is overdose with oil and the topping is alittle dry. When I cut it the oil just ooze out. Oh Gosh, it's so fattening.

As for my brunch today, it's alittle different from usual as it has a the peranakan taste. Maybe it's the food I ordered and I felt it's a little oily for all the food.

Overall experience is good but maybe I have to try other food so I can give another review.

text:
Dimbulah is an Australian coffee franchise whose motto is "plantation to cup". It operates several locations across Singapore, including two in Raffles Place (with the other being located in Market Street). I prefer the Chevron House outlet as it's larger, more inviting and, because it's not out in the open, has more privacy.

 On the coffee front, Dimbulah is certainly very much Australian in that the staff is friendly and its coffees are brilliant. I've only had the flat whites here twice and they've been consistently delicious. Prices are reasonable for Singapore at $4.50. The only let-down though is that there's no latte art. I know it'll vanish the moment I drink my beverage, or, what's more likely, get destroyed by the time I get back to my office, but... still! Presentation does count, and for that, I'll take off half a star, only Qype doesn't do half stars, so I have to take off one whole star so as to distinguish Dimbulah from the other cafes with great coffee.

 For food, Dimbulah offers sandwiches, wraps and cakes. This particular outlets also sells soups from Saybons.

 Given its location, it can get a little crowded with office workers swinging by to get their morning /post-lunch fix, but the service is very fast, without quality being compromised.

text:
Thanks to Vanessa, I got to know this little place along Geylang Road, not far from Eunos MRT station. I have past by this place a few times and it seems like a normal cafe just the like others, but I was very wrong.

I met 2 other Yelpers at the cafe, we managed to get a place near the window. It was a small cafe so getting this table can be frustrating, depending on the time of the day. 

The boss is friendly and sociable and thanks to him we got to know a bit of history of this little cafe and sample some biscuits. We ordered the raspberry scone and for myself, a glass of cold coffee (cafe's speciality) and it is definitely worth it. Prices is pretty reasonable and I would definitely come back to try the others. 

About the Scone - absolutely delicious. Little bit sweet for my liking but this is certainly one to enjoy for every morning before your day starts. No wonder the duchess of this venue comes here so often! As for the coffee, I think it's worth trying it especially for the first timers. For $4.50, it's definitely value for money. 

Overall, I enjoyed my time there and would certainly recommend you to drop by there to try the scones. There are seats outside the cafe, but if the place is full, just take it away and enjoy it somewhere else. There are a couple of Malls nearby to enjoy the air con and the scone!

text:
Came here for dinner last sat night. Wasn't too difficult to get a seat for 4 at 7 so that was pretty good. We waited about 5 mins?

Food overall was disappointing. Looked/smelt better than it tasted.

Wagyu onsen bowl$14.90
Looked amazing in the pics and the first bite was heaven. I loved the mix of the sauce/egg/rice. Amazing; might almost pay just for that. However found the beef lacking, it was too chewy and also rubbery. Not sure if it was because it was too raw or that it was just like that. 

Chorizo sausage$6.90
Didn't like this at all. 

Truffle mash $2
Friend liked this but I found it extremely average. 

Creamy spinach $2
I quite liked this. Reminded me a little of panek paneer. Decent to share

Lamb
Friend ordered and said it was good. 

The Mexican store.
Friend tried it and thought it was average. I tried the hummus, it was ok but I wouldn't order next time.

Seafood store
Friend ordered the grilled fish. It took around an hour to arrive! So we pretty much weren't hungry by then and found it average. Sides of Chicken luncheon chips and sweet potato fries were very average too. 

Probably wouldn't go back unless someone really wanted me to
Bagel heaven. Need to try them plain for the real test but so far so good based on the 2 sandwiches I've tried. Shame there are no poppy seeds allowed here though.

text:
I honestly wished I have nicer things to say about Paul Bakery.

For starters, I loved most part of the service I got at Paul's. Had a delightful lady and gentleman serving and they looked like the genuinely loved what they're doing which -always- make for a nice touch. I just wished I got their names! 

Paul is constantly loaded with people so be prepared for a bit of a wait, try not to let that dent your mood. Also try not to go with too much of an expectation.

My friend got a breakfast set while I had the crepes. They were nothing to write home to and with the choices you get in SG now, I hardly think just doing the basic works. Also, I hardly feel that way, but the quality of the food made me feel that it was really overpriced.

I was genuinely looking forward to trying the desserts since Paul is famed for their bakes. Am a little disappointed to report that both options I picked - lemon meringue tart and another pastry - were lacklustre. 

Moral of the story - listen to your foodie friends when they tell you not to bother with a place.

text: The coffee is not bad but, unfortunately, the ethos of the place is not sufficiently customer centric. We had been waiting for our coffee for 20 minutes) which was okay as they were super busy. Then the owner arrived and was immediately given priority - they made him a coffee in less than a minute. When challenged they stated, "but he's the owner...". His fault, not theirs. We now go elsewhere!

Meng's has been my regular bar chor mee joint for years. While it used to make a seriously good bowl of noodles comparable to all the famous bak chor mee places out there, standards have sadly been dropping over the years. Sometimes, the noodles and sauce mix can be quite hit or miss. I have on a few occasions now, found my noodles a tad over cooked and under seasoned. However, I do think Meng's remains one of those reliable BCM places. While it's not mind blowing and yes, you can probably find better bowls of BCM out there, Meng's is open 24 hours, it's quick, and it's familiar.

text:
Do not be fooled by the "cuteness" and "charm" of this place. My coworkers and I ventured out to try this joint for lunch and not only was there a lack of any service, but our food was delivered one by one at a slow pace. While asking politely after 25 minutes of waiting, the "owner" or "manager" defended this piece of shit establishment by saying "we only have a staff of 4". I mean do you not have any common sense? It is the lunch rush and you have a staff of 4? Logistically, I am not in the F&B industry but I am pretty sure a moron can figure this out.

On top of all of this, one of the orders was left out- which is another logistically error by not having the server repeat everything.

Finally, the last straw- no remorse from the manager at all, then accusing us of ordering things that we never ordered, with no SORRY for the missed lunch for our co-worker, not even offered to knock off the pathetic 10% they call service.

In the words of you Singaporean people... "CHEAT MY MONEY!"

DO NOT EAT HERE.

text:
2nd time. I've been for dinner before, the food was freshly prepared and the portion huge. Not sure how authentically Swedish the food is. 

Today I had a latte - it was decent. The surroundings are nice but if I'm in the area better coffee can be found at Maison Ikkoku or other spots serving Toby's Esate.

Great choice for affordable healthy lunch. They aren't crowded during lunch either! I always go for the comfort fix (chicken thigh, onsen egg, broccoli and brown rice) and its filling enough that I ask for less rice.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/dNsc0LDAyTJ3OiobRVp-Vw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dimbulah-singapore?reviewid=Rs3aNroRDFsjo5NGvdz5Mw&select=dNsc0LDAyTJ3OiobRVp-Vw', 'altText': 'Photo of Dimbulah - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text:
This is a nice café with a very inviting décor located in Market Street. However, to be honest, it is a little hard to find this place even though it is right in the middle of Raffles Place. It's behind the M1 shop at Caltex House.
Dimbulah prides itself on bringing fine Australian coffee from the plantation straight to the consumer, and it shows: the coffee here is simply mindblowing. 
They have a breakfast menu as well as a lunch menu. They also have cakes, tarts and muffins on display. However, it seems that most people were there for the coffee.
My friend had a triple deck roast chicken sandwich and a chicken pie. The chicken sandwich was nothing special, just three slices of wholemeal sandwich bread with roast chicken and the usual garnishing. The chicken pie was not bad. I had a tuna baguette which was also very normal, so food-wise, it's really not impressive. As I've mentioned though, the  coffee was really good. It's not harsh and too acidic, and there is kind of an underlying richness which gives the coffee texture and body. Overall, this is a great place to chill. Recommended!

---- ICE CREAM ----

Coconut: 4.5 stars

Apiary:  4.5 stars

Blue Milk: 4.5 stars

Chocolate: 4.5 stars

Caramelised Strawberry: 4 stars

---- SIDES ----

Waffle with Brown Butter: 4.5 stars

Excellent coffee. Stopped by for a takeaway, hence I didn't get to try the food. From I saw seating is a little cramp and cakes are slightly higher than normal pricing. A red velvet is $6? Was eyeing the chocolate coffee tart which is $4.50. I ordered a 5oz flat white that came with one shot of espresso. Added one more shot for 50¢ which was decent. Think that cup sizes should be bigger. 5oz was slightly bigger than a vending machines Milo cup so I finished that in like 5mins. Sizes there only come in 3 or 5oz. Compared to Starbucks, 8oz (tall size) this was really tiny. Latte art is good. Service is really good too. They should ask though if you'd like sugar or something while ordering. Guess I'm used to that in the cbd area. Coffee was smooth and I find worth the money but like I said, bigger portions please.

text:
This place is so adorable. We arrived pretty late at night and I was surprised to see diners dressed up in what appeared to be Harry Potter cosplay - but no, the cafe has outfits that you can wear to get in the spirit of things! The decor is so cute and very appropriately Hogwarts-like. Had I come in the daytime, I think the natural lighting would have made for some amazing pictures. 

We got the butterscotch ale, and though I've never been to the Wizarding World of Harry Potter, my friend who has said it tasted JUST like the butterbeer you can find there. It was delicious. 

The food was surprisingly good for a theme cafe. We got the confit chicken with pesto spaghetti and the pesto mayo pork ribs. Both were really well cooked, not too much pesto on either but enough to give you a could flavor. The pork ribs were super tender and the sides that came with it were delicious, very American-style like mashed potatoes and sweet corn. I loved it and that's coming from an American mashed potato addict. 

The witch's brew, although I didn't try it, seems like it's something you can't miss here. I was excited to see another diner get it, and the flaming drink looks exactly like a potion from Harry Potter. If I have one regret it's not trying that!

text:
LOCATION & AMBIENCE 3/5
Located along Simon Road just off the junction of Simon Road, Upper Serangoon Road, and Tampines Road, opposite Stars of Kovan condominium. There are limited open car park lots (~10 lots) in front of Lola's. Else you'll have to drive further into Simon Road where there are additional open car park lots but you'll have to take a 5 minute walk over. Make sure you'll got valid parking or you might risk getting a parking fine from the parking wardens. 

There are limited seating also at the cafe (~20+) especially due to the covid19 restrictions. There are also 2 outdoor seating (al fresco style) tables (from refurbished/repurposed old Singer sewing tables) which seat 4 people each, you can request for the fans above to be switched off if you find it too strong. There is also a 1 hour dining duration so patrons will have to leave after their 1 hour is up.

It's relatively quiet from opening time at 10am on weekdays but they are busiest in the evenings when there is a queue just to get a seat.

SERVICE 3.5/5
Hard to get service during busy periods. Sometimes also hard to find staff on low peak periods. Could be better. 

FOOD & DRINKS 3.5/5
Can be a hit and miss, depending on what you order. The bangers and mash is good, with a nice snap to the sausages and goes well with the potato mash and sauteed onion gravy. Eggs benedict was so so.

OVERALL 3.5/5
Overall a nice place to drop by during off peak hours/days, unless you like to hang out with the crowd during their busy periods.

You know I would have never thought I would have such a fabulous time having tea in the middle of the mall, but I truly did! Despite it being in the center of a walkway, the shopping center wasn't that packed and it wasn't noisy, so I had a grand time.

It is indeed a special little place planted in the center of Ion Mall, and the airiness and surrounded by top designer shops gives it another posh feel--I never thought I could feel so posh having tea in the mall before. The service was pleasant and I felt like I was transported to some 5-star afternoon tea paradise (despite it being the middle of the night). I loved the huge tea selection, and the waiter made some nice suggestions after I asked for something flowery and light. I got the 1 tea + dessert combination (~20SGD) to share with my friend since we had just completed a delicious dinner earlier.

If I were back in Singapore, I could see this as a great hang-out spot to catch up with friends and drink some fancy tea + have cake at any hour of the day. It is pricey, but it's what do you expect for "the world's finest, luxury, tea brand." Indulge, and enjoy!

They also have a small shelf of tea you can purchase that smelled amazing.

text:
Chocolate and cheese buffet on top of MBS!

Skip dinner and come hungry. Skip lunch that day too if you can. Or go for a long swim before and after the meal. Or in my case, stuff yourself as much as you can while promising that you will start a juice cleanse the following day. 

Back to the experience, we came on a weekday without a reservation but didn't have any problem getting a table. You have to first reserve with the concierge on the lobby level, who will talk to the reception at Rise restaurant for some reasons. They will then give you a card that allows you to enter the pool area because this is located right in the middle Tower 2.

The most wonderful thing about this is of course the view. You can choose to sit inside the adorably decorated restaurant or outside with a view of the harbour and ocean. It was a little dark for us sitting outside but if you reserve you could ask for a table with better lighting.

Now on to the food, I was not blown away by one particular thing but generally the buffet was not too bad. There were around 10+ types of cheeses (mostly French I believe) and countless chocolaty desserts. I wonder if cheese is a new addition because none of the previous reviews mentioned it. Coffee or tea is complimentary but they also have a wine menu. 

Overall a must try experience especially if you have a sweet tooth :)

text:
You'll like this place if you are into tea. they have tea bags lining their counters and the drink i had a strong scent and taste of the oolong i ordered with a slight hint of peach.
i decided to  give it a try because they also offered cheese tea. sadly the cheese was lost in the tea and there was no hint of it other than the sight of it before i put my lips to the cup.

3 stars! 1 star each for FOOD, AMBIENCE and "WILL I COME BACK?". No stars for service and price.

Also, I apologise in advance for the epic length review.

The word 'hipster' is overused, really. This is a typical brunch restaurant. I don't see where it's 'hip' or 'ster'.

Food is average. Mushroom soup is not Campbell's. Or at least to my un-hipster taste buds. Buffalo wings were like sweet and sour chicken wings, not spicy. Pasta was meh. The only thing I would come back for are the pizzas, Super thin crust and light. Nice.

Ambience is homely. Lots of wood benches and tin pails for decoration. Seats are tightly packed and walk space is narrow. I might have seen a mason jar or two. /shudder

"Will I come back?" Yes, for the pizza and for the "buy 1 get one free" lunch special. Now the mechanics of this BOGO is dreadfully complicated and very sneaky if the customer is not careful. I will explain this in the next section. This would have been so easy to fix when asked, and would have won a life-long customer. But. hey, which restaurant manager would want to do that?

Service is non-existent. Poor guys are overworked and do not have time for pleasantries. 

Price. Ahhh, the only thing this place has going for it is the 1 for 1 lunch special. When you get seated, you will see from the menu that not all items qualify for this. Items that do, have a little label next to it.

So! Imagine the following scenario:

Ah Beng and Ah Lian decide to try this new 'simi-lai eh hipster' cafe near Ah Mah's flat in Tiong Bahru.

They order two muchroom soups ($11 for 2) This items is automatically 1 for 1. Don't know why they have to make life so confusing.

Then Ah Beng orders a Vogole pasta MAIN for $18. Ah Lian orders a Funghi Pizza for $18.

For appetisers, Ah Beng orders Buffalo Wings ($16) and Ah Lian orders Calamari Rings ($16).

So, quick recap: 2 soups, 2 mains, 2 appetisers.

QUESTION: How much was Ah Beng and Ah Lian charged for their lunch? (Assume no service charge.)

ANSWER: You would think, this is easy! 
1 for 1 mushroom soup + 1 for 1 MAIN + 1 for 1 appetiser = $11 + $18 + $16 = $45

Wrong. Because Chapter 55 is so scared that customers will 'take advantage' of the 1 for 1 deal, this is how they calculated the bill:

Mushroom soup is $11 for 2. (Written in the menu, don't argue.)
Higher cost items are charged, lower cost items are free. (Written in the fine print, don't argue.)

Actual bill is: $11 + $18 + $18 = $47

Ah Beng and Ah Lian pays up and leaves, vowing to never come back and also something about mothers and fathers.

Ok, ok, the story is a little dramatic for a difference of $2. But it is the principle of the whole thing. Even if it is not for principle, then it is about making a quick decision to make Ah Lian and Ah Beng happy customers. 

Long story short: After the trauma of mathematics and Chapter 55. Ah Beng and Ah Lian grew closer and lived happily ever after,

Nothing really special from my mind in terms of uniqueness: the view lacks quite a bit considering that i'm viewing a couple tankers just sitting there, ruining the view but guess in Asia, this is as good as it gets.

the sand's nice, peace and quiet when i was there, but their blue and white wooden 'lounge' chairs ---far from CSI Miami's comffy ones haha---means you better bring out yr own cushions unless you don't mind a sore bum after 15 minutes.

text: Elegant dining room with great service. The menu has interesting and unusual dishes, especially among street food and appetiser offerings, but the flavour is extremely mild, too tuned down for western palates.

Some days, I want something more fancy than a plate of "economy rice" for dinner, but am not willing to endure the crush of the Central Business District. So I hop on a bus and go to Great World City, where I spring for a fantastic Italian sausage and browned onions sandwich. Crusty bread, savoury meat, sweetly caramelised onions--how can one go wrong with that? If I don't feel like a sandwich (but I always do--it's the onions that do it), there are also more hearty options from the deli, such as risotto-stuffed chicken, that you can ask them to heat up while you pick your Tekoe tea. And for afters, go to the chiller to pick out some cake (they have one that is essentially a Snickers bar writ large--you may think 2 people can handle it; I suggest you share with more. in any case, more friends in the office is a good thing, is it not?) or pastry for afters. They also have thin-crust pizzas with a variety of toppings, as well as salads, for those of us who absolutely need something green in every meal. I enjoy Gastronomia for the range of foods they carry--eye candy and most of it delicious, so sometimes it gets really difficult to choose because my eyes are far far bigger than my stomach, though one cannot say it is not trying to keep up!

text: The matcha and the desserts are OK. But for some reason they don't take credit card??

Wow this place is NOT good. Ive been using Yelp since 2010 especially when I moved to a new continent to help eliminate trial and error. It's not often that I get disappointed by highly rated yelp and this is one of them rare instances.

We ordered the butterscotch & berries pancake and a Norwegian. The pancake was average and the Norwegian was a disappointment. For me salad (came w the Norwegian) isn't just a garnish, it's food. The cucumber was seeded (ok) and hard (not ok), the hollandaise sauce that came w the poached egg was not impressive (watery). The Hokkaido bread was quite ok. The smoked salmon was v average. The grilled asparagus on the other hand was really good. Unfortunately that's forms only 5-10% of the dish.

The service was pretty good and people are Super friendly. Alight I'll bump them up to 3.
I not what it is but the lady up front is super rude. It's like a bakery slash coffee shop. I don't even know why I ordered what I did because of her attitude.

One of the best in town. Great chicken rice stall a little down the row from the one with the huge queue that Bourdain and Ramsey have frequented. Super salad stall. Also try porridge, duck rice, fried dough and banana fritter stalls.

TWG is really one of those places that you see and the last thing you would think about it is that it is a Singapore Company. I love the atmosphere here, it feels fancy and service is great. However should you find yourself wanting to try what they have to offer you do need quote a bit of patience as service is rather slow from waiting in line to the serving of the food. Food is good however the menu is a little messy whereby I had to ask the waiters questions about the things I'm about to order. Taste wise is above average but price wise it's more on the pricey side.

text:
I have been doing myself a tremendous disservice by never checking this place out until now :( To think I spent three months interning across the road but never made Tom's Palette a priority....

The best part about Tom's are the inventive, delicious flavors. It may be easy to dump thimbles of yuzu syrup into the ice cream machine but it's difficult to produce ice cream of the right sweetness and texture. Flavors include grannys favorite, salted caramel cheesecake, berries and split, pi pa gao, and of course usuals like chocolate, strawberry. 

I highly recommend the yuzu flavor!! It's sweet, light and refreshing. We also tried a mix of chocolate and grannys favorite (a mix of chocolate, malt, marshmallows, i think?), and spent awhile chilling in the spacious interior. There're many tables and it reminds me of those student haunts at Upper Thomson. (also, ah loy thai right opposite is SUPERB- another excuse to visit Toms!)

I wish there were more independent creameries/ice cream shops like Toms, Daily Scoop, Creamier... I've gotta play my part in supporting and frequenting them ;)

text:
It's Hip to Be Square! Here, There & Everywhere!

TBC could be a 5-star hipstar hangout. It's got the trendy hipster location; it's got the style, swagger and streetcred. It's got the Singapore shophouse meets grandma's basement chillstar vibe.

Instead it wallows in the 2-to-2-and-a-halfy range with lackadaisical lacklustreness.

The service is the friendless math-olympics nerd who spent the weekend indoors doing times tables instead of outdoors chilling with chums.

The food is the cowardly four-eyed flusher you bullied in first grade using their spiked hair liked a scrubbing brush in the lads lavatory.

The brews are the too-cool-for-school kid who is trying too hard to be liked by everyone, and only marginally succeeding.

The views are the pretty princess that makes attending class worth the while, and worth your smile.

TBC coulda stood for The Best Club; Ten Beer ChillSpot; or To Be Continued (as in let's keep coming back). But instead it evokes Too Bland Chili; This Big Chode; or Tad Boring Chad.

Huey got it wrong. Take it from me. TBC is a square, despite the hip!

text:
As I was trying to find this cafe coming from Ann Shang Hill Park and walking down the stairs, making a left and then, being spit out into the busy street , expecting to find a normal looking cafe ... 

Well. I was wrong. 

Located on the second level inside a REALLY Cool bar, Dapper Coffee put me in a daze: a dimly lit space with a beautiful bronze bar and few seatings by the window. 

At first, I was like "hmm, is it wrong to drink at noon? I barely had lunch. To appease my inner Debbie Downer , I ordered a banana walnut muffin to cover the fruit and healthy fats group... Yay lunch! 

Since we're at a bar, I had to get an "Espresso + Tonic" -- an easy drink on a hot day. (When does Singapore ever had a cold day?!) and you know what? That's exactly what it is. The caffeine buzz after was exceptional, especially since I usually don't get espressos. 

I hung around for awhile so I was able to try their Campari Spritz as well. Served in an extra large wine goblet, this bevvy was bitter and refreshing to my taste. I highly miss good, low ABV cocktails and given the high prices of cocktails in Singapore, I wouldn't necessarily spend $$ on low ABV drinks! :p  so this was an exception. 

My first time here blew me away that whenever I get recommendations for a chill mid-afternoon hangout, Dapper Coffee is the first thing that comes to mind.

text:
I've finally tried this place and although it's not a NY bagel, this is the closest damn thing! I loved it. I should say I ordered breakfast from this place (avocado, egg, cheese, bacon) and the only downside was that I didn't get two!
The bagel sandwich was glorious as if I'd just gotten it from a bodega down the street. I didn't quite understand the weird white sauce (was it mayo? Was it cream?) but honestly who the hell cares? It was delicious and I'd happily stuff one in my pie hole again.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/J1AbqEvSsx9w00LucDofQA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/penny-university-singapore?reviewid=sAAlteHVlbgjDCUp7hdROQ&select=J1AbqEvSsx9w00LucDofQA', 'altText': 'Photo of Penny University - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
Discovered Penny Uni by chance when visiting my usual fried hokkien mee place - Geylang Lor 29 FHM, highly-recommended.

I love the decor here, especially the lighting. Not sure why they decided to waste some space on the "porch", resulting in less space inside.

My first visit, I opted for a flat white in the bigger cup (forgot what the size is called), felt it was too thin, like I was drinking milk instead of coffee. Subsequently opted for the smaller cup and the mix was just nice.

They're reasonably near where I stay, although not the nearest coffee shop (that'd be Loysel's Toy). But I'll definitely be back, as I'm regularly in the area.

Parking can be quite limited especially during lunch and dinner hours, be prepared to scout/camp for lots.

The little book nook where u can grab a book or leave a book', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'The little book nook where u can grab a book or leave a book'}]
text:
Great friendly staff who are polite, and gives good service too! Ambience is abit dim for reading but otherwise it's quite cosy. May be abit chilly for some people even on hot weather. 

For today, we used a credit card promotion and order the mains (1-for-1). 
- spicy crabmeat capellini
- bacon truffle Mac and cheese. 

*verdict to come soon* typing this as we are waiting for the food.

I'm kicking myself for not grabbing coffee from TBB right next door instead - it's truly daylight robbery to charge $4.50 for a Piccolo Latte that was both under extracted and washed out with burnt milk - I gave up after two mouthfuls.

This was my first try of Orange Thimble and sadly, it'll probably be my last. Of all the cafés in Tiong Bahru, I'd say that they lose out based on both quality and on decour. It's truly a shame; I wished this experience wasn't so disappointing!

One of the many hawker centers in SG. This one is right smack in the heart of Chinatown. Dining area upstairs and shopping downstairs. Plenty of stalls to choose from depends on your cravings.
Some has longer queue than the rest. Personally it's all the same for me.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Plk9spR84QiNcSC4x3d8SA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/tolidos-espresso-nook-singapore-3?reviewid=hutxF6CnCvFu7Togd_4F6Q&select=Plk9spR84QiNcSC4x3d8SA', 'altText': "Photo of Tolido's Espresso Nook - Singapore, Singapore", 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: This is going to be one of my new favourite brunch places. We found the recommendation online and in spite of the difficulty in finding good parking spots, this place is definitely worth thevisit. It reminds me of the cafes that you would find in Melbourne, Sydney. Locals and travellers seem to know of this place as it was packed on a Saturday morning. Their version of baked eggs brought us back to our favourite haunts in Sydney and their pandan pancake was delightful with its full pandas flavour and gula melaka on the side. They serve their coffee with a standard double shot. While the kinds of food is not revolutionary, they do it very well. One of the major plus points to this place is the lower price of food compared to other similar establishments. Most items are priced in the 13-18 dollar range. I'm going to keep this place in my rotating list of brunch places.

Coffee was great the first time I was there and then it became just Okay when I returned the second time. It is always crowded during weekend for brunch and a long queue... 

Will I be back? Unlikely unless there is no queue and the quality of coffee improved remarkably.

I've tried my fair share of salted egg yolk croissants, and flavor flings cafe has the best around in my opinion. It's not cheap but it's huge and the filling to crust ratio is pretty substantial. I would get one to share over a cup of coffee or tea! Recently the cafe has also expanded its hipster offerings to include raclette as well! Let me get a stab at it and report back :P

Still the best bagels in Singapore. This one alongside their other location in my old stomping grounds in Tanjong Pagar serve the only bagels in Singapore that I consistently come back to.

Highly recommend you come here for any bagel craving you have as you really won't find any better on the island.

The location is pretty cool, all outdoor or bar like seating. 

They don't take credit cards so be wary of that - only cash and NETS.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Qfbj9fSOD0_KZu9q2ayTVA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/ladur%C3%A9e-singapore?reviewid=5uozrbAiKvdKAY62z2VFlw&select=Qfbj9fSOD0_KZu9q2ayTVA', 'altText': 'Photo of Ladurée - Singapore, Singapore. Salted Caramel, Gold Chocolate, Lemon, Chocolate', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Salted Caramel, Gold Chocolate, Lemon, Chocolate'}]
text:
When I heard Laduree's opened in Singapore, I was like "YAYYYYY..." then I realised... Oh crap, that means the whole damn country is going to populate this place. True enough, the entire blogosphere started talking about the long queues and all that. 

And I thought "Meh... I already tried Laduree's in London anyway..." 

Then the boyfriend showed up one night after my dance class with a bag of macaroons. 

I squealed with joy, then I wondered what the hell he did that he felt he had to surprise me with a bag of macaroons. But that's besides the point, I got a bag of macaroons!

Four. To be exact. 

I ate the gold chocolate one first. Seriously, at $7 a piece.. it's like... just chocolate with gold dust. That's it. 

The salted caramel was how I remembered it when I ate it in the sweltering London Summer heat. So was the other chocolate one and the lemon one. 

I have tried Pierre Hermes's macaroons lovingly flown in from Paris by my stewardess bestie.. but it shrunk due to the air pressure, so I couldn't judge if it's the best in the world.. yet... 

So until I fulfill my dream of eating BOTH Pierre Hermes's and Laduree's macaroons both at the same time...... I'll say Laduree's macaroons will be the best 'authentic' Parisian macaroon in Singapore for now.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/kqWgc-d71AeAE0FWkKOQmA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/rabbit-owl-depot-singapore?reviewid=luOtBScxG-P8TqusLkf2Uw&select=kqWgc-d71AeAE0FWkKOQmA', 'altText': 'Photo of Rabbit Owl Depot - Singapore, Singapore. Pretty apt considering Bryan Adams&#39; Heaven just played.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "Pretty apt considering Bryan Adams' Heaven just played."}]
text:
Walked past this unassuming place and, quite typically, the mister with the keen eye took notice of it. Decided to give it a try and wow.

Let's start with the aesthetics - small cozy place with cute round tables scattered about. Love the "themed" furniture with the pipe details. I'm so over that array of mismatched furniture thing that seems to be all the rage. It's sloppy! There are little owl/rabbit knick knacks around the cafe that I find adorable. Again, that running theme which just shows careful thought. 

We shared a snowflake waffle with ice cream. Yum. Yknow how it is with "the basics". Anyone can make cakes, pancakes, toast etc. But the true test is to have it sans any "taste boosters". The waffle by itself is already tasty. Drizzled sparsely with icing sugar and syrup (overkill with the sweetness and it'd have been MEH) and the ice cream... Mm. Also appreciate how the waffles are a little on the crisp side, just the way I like them.

I'd say the star is the waffles, but hey, the coffee is pretty good too! The flat white would've been one of the better ones we've had if they were a liiiiiittle less generous with the milk.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/vXA38gEw0BgwApDwNSakCA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/craftsmen-specialty-coffee-singapore?reviewid=7lIHcZvF2P1rxrM7j9N_cw&select=vXA38gEw0BgwApDwNSakCA', 'altText': 'Photo of Craftsmen Specialty Coffee - Singapore, Singapore. A handy guide to the different types of coffees.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'A handy guide to the different types of coffees.'}]
text:
This is a good local neighborhood coffee shop, good coffee, good food, good service. I've been here a couple of time to get coffee and met friends for breakfast once as well. It's a bit small and can get crowded, but they tables to sit at and enjoy your breakfast with table service after ordering at the counter and they have high chairs as well. They don't have a kids menu, and their food portions are rather large. The coffee is good, the chalkboard showing all the different coffees is GREAT, you can get an coffeducation while waiting for your drink, maybe even change up your next order. The coffee price and portion seems a bit expensive, compared to Starbucks, but about on par for small neighborhood coffee shops. 
They have free filtered water at a self service station, which is always a major plus for me.
Convenient parking in the Siglap V garage down below as well.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=__Ksf1CCgaKdS3Gi5f6PcQ', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/eKDVIeYVKOG9ozxzu-hkmA/60s.jpg', 'srcSet': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/eKDVIeYVKOG9ozxzu-hkmA/ms.jpg 1.67x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/eKDVIeYVKOG9ozxzu-hkmA/120s.jpg 2.00x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/eKDVIeYVKOG9ozxzu-hkmA/90s.jpg 1.50x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/eKDVIeYVKOG9ozxzu-hkmA/168s.jpg 2.80x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/eKDVIeYVKOG9ozxzu-hkmA/180s.jpg 3.00x', 'markupDisplayName': 'Renuka V.', 'displayLocation': 'Los Angeles, CA', 'altText': 'Renuka V.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=__Ksf1CCgaKdS3Gi5f6PcQ', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 191, 'photoCount': 37, 'reviewCount': 744, 'eliteYear': None}
text:
5 of us + 3 year old boy went for brunch on the last Sunday of 2014. Had reservations so were seated promptly. 2 of us shared the following:-

EnglishBfast- Scrambled eggs, back bacon, Cumberland pork sausage, sautéed mushrooms, baked beans, breakfast potatoes, grilled tomato & brioche. Everything was delicious esp. the eggs which I usually find quite "heavy" after a while but found these to be "light" although still very tasty. 

Breakfast Hangover-Scrambled eggs, back bacon, roasted pearl tomatoes, Swiss cheese & spicy tomato chutney on grilled ciabatta with breakfast potatoes - tasty!

Also shared a starter which had fried "sticks" of goat cheese - very tasty.

My flat white was just perfect as well. We all also had a couple of glasses of sauvignon blanc each which went very well with our meal.

Extra star is for the good service and de rigueur bustling brunch vibe.

We came here to celebrate my father's birthday. We picked Bob's because he wanted live music, and I wasn't too sure about where to get live music in Singapore. Another plus was that it was outdoors.The Havana Night event only happens on Fridays, and it's still happening. We went last October, during the haze season, and lucked out because not many people wanted to be outdoors even though the weather was fine the day of. When you're at Bob's, you really want to be outdoors where the daybeds are. It was night, so we couldn't see much. But the sea breeze was really nice. There were no peacocks the night we went, and I think it's more sanitary that way.

While Bob's is mainly a bar, they serve food too. For Havana Night, they hire a chef to BBQ outdoors, so you smell your food as it is being prepared. We ordered a couple of the Havana Night platter for two, and it served everything on the BBQ menu. My dad particularly liked the lamb. The shrimp with mango salsa was really good too. We also ordered appetizers from the menu -- I particularly liked the pizza. I don't recommend their dessert though.

For drinks, we ordered and shared a selection of cocktails. If you're uncertain, they have a set of 3 glasses of any cocktail as a sampler. Some of the cocktails incorporate Singaporean flavors, like gula melaka. For the more traditional, you can just order a shot of whisky.

As for the live music, it was a trio of men, a singer with guitar, keyboards and drums. They sing in Spanish, and it was a mix of classic and contemporary songs. Definitely crowd pleasers. If you're into Latin dancing, they will play requests too, and the singer is happy to teach the basic steps. There is plenty of dancing space.

Now being situated in the Capella hotel, home to $1000-a-night rooms, you may be a little daunted by the idea of coming to Bob's. For our party of 7, we ended up spending about $400, which was decent. We had a drink each, but we didn't drink excessively.

Bob's is a little hard to reach, so you're going to have to cab in and out. But the whole experience was magical, kind of like being transported to a whole new world. My dad had a lot of fun, and he can't wait to go back again. Yes, it's surprisingly family friendly (we're all grown ups, but a couple of older people won't stand out, unlike at some other hipper joints.)

*Update*

Not sure how these updates work (it's my first) but I wanted to add that I went back to Choupinette and have confirmed that they now hold the title in Singapore as Best Eggs Benedict.  They have perfected the bread toasting and now offer more hollandaise sauce.  Well done!  You didn't earn another star rating, but you are on your way...

text: The ambiance is on point complimenting the great view. Very chic! Food is good but slightly overpriced for what it actually is. Service can be improved.

This hawker center has TWO levels! I went at lunchtime and this place was just packed with people. It is a really popular place to eat. I looked around and looked at the stalls on both floors. Noodles, fresh juices, hainan chicken rice, they have everything! I wanted to eat everything but the stall I really wanted to eat at was Noodle Story. Walking around you can tell by the lines which stalls are the best ones to go to. Noodle Story was one of them and it was totally worth the wait. There are tons of tables and seats but it's packed during lunch. I noticed people leaving a packet of tissues or a lighter or something to indicate that they've claimed that spot. So simple, but the system works. Hawker centers are great places to find cheap eats in Singapore, which is great because everything else is so expensive!

text:
Dining is limit to 2 hours. While I understand the rationale behind it, I was still a bit disappointed when we were asked to leave after 2 hours even when the space was not full. 

The all-day breakfast menu was pretty average and standard like other brunch cafes. I did enjoy their pastas (especially the Umami), but overall prices are pretty steep. They are on Burpple Beyond and Entertainer, so you can enjoy 1-for-1 deals. 

I would revisit only for the coffees as I really enjoyed those. Their signature coffees are really interesting, and I really enjoyed the Okinawa coffee.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/oBg9oWUXsTxRaytU3ZPh3w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/four-seasons-singapore-2?reviewid=eZz1Z2o8aUq_G8ixiUuOhw&select=oBg9oWUXsTxRaytU3ZPh3w', 'altText': 'Photo of Four Seasons - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
Simple consistent food. Sets are mostly $4.70 and come with 2 soft boiled eggs and a drink. Mains include kaya toast (4 square pieces), French toast, soft bun or egg baguette.

I've tried them all and they are worth the price. The kaya here is thick and I do ask for a little extra for my French toast sometimes.

You get a bigger cup of tea when it's takeaway but often less thick.

The eggs are always nicely done but.. They often take very long to be served!

Staff are pleasant.

text: Ordered kiam chai arg (salted pickles soup with duck) which supposed to be Chinese traditional dish, but most Chinese wouldn't deep fried the duck leg before cook it in the soup. 1 star  deducted. The portion is not really as big as described by the waiter, big for a lady, but barely enough for 2. The Roti babi was nice, minced meat deep fried with a toast. Gula melaka jelly so so, but the durian penyet paired with coconut ice cream was impressive. Advisable to make reservation to avoid disappointment, sometimes this place is fully booked.

text:
This Muslim-owned bistro has moved from its original location from Bali Lane to a spacier lot at Telok Ayer. Located right across the historic Thiam Hock Keng temple, along a cram street... you should be able to spot it.

Perhaps this place is just too new as it just opened for service mid last month; hence word of mouth is still not spread around much. It was lunch time and the place was still quite vacant. Only two tables were occupied; one was the owners and probably their acquaintances. Regretted being so paranoid of taking the trouble of reserving a table. It was only about 1pm++ did we notice more and more people coming in, but there were still a lot of tables available.

We were a group of 4 colleagues, lunching out together. Most of the food ordered were shared, just so we could have a bite of everything purchased. Opinions shared amongst us obviously varied. And oh! Do note that not all the photos posted here were taken by me. Haha! We shared our snaps. *giggles*

We got ourselves 'Nacho Lover', 'Fried Mushroom', 'Crispy Wings' and 'Signature Prawn & Crayfish Pasta'. For drinks and desserts, we ordered 'Mango Creme Brulee', 'Affogato', 'Iced Lemon Tea' and... 'Halal Champagne'. Yes, you read right. 'Halal Champagne': non-alcoholic. They even have 'Halal Red Wine'. Two of us have never touched alcohol before, so we asked one who had and she confirmed that the taste was exactly the same as a genuine champagne. It tasted like an extreme Apple Zapple to me. *shrugs* 

Nachos were served with 3 different dips: cheese sauce, salsa and guacamole. Okay! Not too overpowering. Fried truffle mushrooms were a bit too soft to our liking. Then again, I dislike mushrooms. The pasta was nice but those chicken wings... Wow! Loved them! We didn't share the Affogato though. But my colleague who got it did say it was good. 

Coming to the creme brulee though, I've tasted Chempedak and even Durian flavoured ones before, but this was the first time I had a Mango flavoured creme brulee. I absolutely loved it. My colleague however found it too sweet... Oh well! I have a sweet tooth. Hence the reason why I guess my Iced Lemon Tea was a bit too bland.

Oh! Getting here is best via public transport. We took a cab here. Parking is almost impossible in this area. Most did illegal parking. Even then, there were no more spots.

Aiyo Olio.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Aiyo Olio.'}]
text:
Beautiful, hip space in the little India. Definitely a nice to spot to have coffee, hangout and chat amongst friends. However, the food leaves a lot to be desired... 

I ordered the Aiyo Olio, spaghetti tossed in oil with garlic, chilli padi and a moderate serving of bacon. It was "ehh..." Nothing special. It was so simple, I could probably cook it. I tasted my fellow Elite's carbonara and unfortunately, it had the same unsatisfying taste. 

Overall, I would give the food two stars and the space four stars, which averages to a three star review. Fortunately, OMB's branding and design is quite impressive. The shop sells cute pillows and bags that reference everything bacon, which would definitely have some appeal to SG's hipster community.

text: Finally, a good American diner style breakfast place in Singapore! The food here is pretty good - I've tried the pancakes with warm maple butter + banana walnut, as well as chicken and waffles. Both were really good! The pancakes were extremely fluffy, and are in my opinion one of the best you can find in here.... and the warm maple butter they're served with was also heavenly!!

Sitting next to the post office on Nassim Hill is not the best spot for a restaurant, parking not great luckily I can walk from my office for lunch.  They have a decent selection of sandwiches and lunch fares service is ok.  Some of the options are tastier/more flavorful than others. Not my favorite place but good for change up from typical Tanglin food.

text:
The place is just beautiful so its nice to sit and just enjoy your tea.  The cutlery and plates are just so pretty!
When you go to this place, make sure you are not rushing.  Their tea menu is so extensive, that it will take you at least 15mins to select one.  The tea was great with the subtle flavors.
The let down was the dessert --- it looked very pretty but the flavors were not there -- felt like it was not good chocolate.  It was just sweet...
I went for afternoon tea so did not try any of the dishes.

text:
I've been to Garden Slug once and would love to go back again, but because of it's location, its pretty hard to travel there.

The staffs at Garden Slug are friendly and cheerful, the food there are really not bad and the ambiance of the place gives a casual dining experience. It's also a pretty good place for gatherings as they do cater to large group settings too. I think it's best if you called to reserve instead.

I would recommend their soups and desserts. It not only tastes good, it looks good too! I love how they will spend time and effort in plating their food before serving it to you. 

A good place to try out if you haven't.

text: Don't bother - customer satisfaction is not their priority. Ordered a salmon that comes with lemon butter and asked if instead of butter they could just give me some olive oil, so it wouldn't by as dry. I can't take dairy due to my disease. They refused to help me out and just kept saying 'cannot' - no alternatives other than no sauce were offered. The menu is not friendly to those, who have food allergies. Not coming back.

text:
Good things come in small packages. This hidden gem hosts beautiful decor, a small but solid menu, and a laid back vibe.  Yes, it has a hipster vibe, but is also very minimalist (think gray and beige) with succulents scattered throughout.

The food
The nam ban bao is the standout here.  A perfectly fried piece of tender chicken is nestled between the fluffy bao for a few perfect bites.  The salted egg yolk shrimp had a nice crunch, but could have used a little more seasoning.  The pork belly brings me back to traditional braised pork belly I loved as a kid.  It's served au jus style with a side of stock!  The truffle fries were wonderfully salty here too.

I'd definitely return for the good vibes, relaxed atmosphere and good food.

It's funny to squeeze in this tiny shop usually to a crowd of grandmas buying boxes or some guy with a video camera zooming in on the little pig pastries. The cashiers are really efficient and the space is small but clean and brightly lit, with all the pastries nicely displayed. I keep bringing friends here and really recommend their egg tarts. Tong Heng mastered the recipe with fresh flaky crust and soft custard filling. I actually love the COCONUT egg tart more than the original as you get more texture and sweetness from the shredded coconut. I'll always make Tong Heng a stop when I'm in town :)

text: Try the croissants too! Feels like I am back in Australia. A hidden gem with the coffee and the food. The price is not super expensive also. Typical cafe prices.

I tried the almond croissant but was not impressed, but Mum really likes the orange breads. Definitely prefer the version at Tiong Bahru Bakery. The coffee is alright though not mindblowing.

This place is always filled with tai tai types, not surprisingly given its location and type of stores. 

Service is friendly and helpful.

text: Their soft serve ice cream is delicious! My friends and I came on a Sunday night and they were out of cones, so we opted for the soft serve in a cup and it was great. I tried the chocolate flavor, while my friend had the white rabbit (milk) which tastes just like the white rabbit candy. Will return again!

Cute little bakery shop with a nicely decorated outdoor patio. We tried a couple different desserts there including cupcakes, raspberry cake, dark chocolate with filling, and a brownie. I thought the desserts were all ok, but not spectacular. The drinks were a bit expensive for what you get. 

There is limited seating which consists of just one huge communal table and one high top table. This isn't a good place for groups, but a perfect place to hang out and read if the place is not busy and you can find a place to sit.

text:
abc evenings =artisanal bites, craft beers and  in marketing is doing their job well. Question is, can they deliver?

Ordered their wagyu beef sliders, Serrano ham & arugula focaccia and truffle fries. All were labeled 'bites' And they were all pretty good. The one part of this meal I can't figure out is what type of dining establishment abc wants to be. The decor needs to look like a cafe /bakery during the day and an evening hangout afterwards. Neither is achieved. I get a bakery out front, wine cooler but not fully stocked, craft beers, also not extensive, coffee grinder and espresso at the counter area. Most places that attempt so much fail miserably. Here we get a 'high' pass. Their saving grace is their baked goods. The breads are very well done. And a lovely way to build goodwill with end of day complimentary eclairs. 

I will come back as the food is decent but price points are a tad higher than I would like. Now they just have to laser focus on what they want to be serving and more patrons will make this a regular place.

text:
I like coming here at sunset on a weekend because it's quiet and there's a great view without having to fight off the crowds that you'd get at One Altitude or on the MBS rooftop. The fact that there's a microbrewery on the 33rd floor of a building is pretty cool and I think some of their beers are quite nice despite not being a beer drinker at all.

The beers and drinks are on the pricey side, as are the food options. However, since it's a bar with a view, it's not bad. And at least they taste pretty decent. Service is pretty non-existent but it's nice to be left alone. If you go early, you won't need a reservation but might get kicked out by 6 or 7pm.

Patronized this cafe on a Sunday afternoon. Given that it was situated in a mall, it attracted a fair amount of people. It was difficult to get a seat at the beginning. 

A decent selection of sandwiches, pies and quiches. The dessert display was so tempting which made me fall prey to a chocolate eclair ($5ish), average tasting.

A convenient spot in the mall but if you're not pressed for time or undeterred by haze, perhaps check out Artistry or maison ikkoku in the vicinity.

Really a great hawker center. It's all about Tian Tian chicken and rice here though. Everything else is pretty good, but Tian Tian is next level my dudes. On the real, it's pretty much as next level as you can get when you're talking about poached chicken and white rice. Everything is delish, eat it all. Now.

text: Portions are decently sized but not exactly big enough for verocious eaters. Had the soba, which was aromatic. Pasta is so-so, feels like they used canned tomatoes to do the sauce and frozen prawns. Not really worth that amount of money I am paying for. Sambal risotto was served undercooked the first round. Taste was however refreshing and very interesting concoction I must say. Crowded at lunch time, recommended to get reservation before heading there. NO WIFI and there is bad reception. Not great for studying or doing work there despite a cosy ambience.
