text:
Nasi lemak is the way to go. Yes, you should end your meal with some chendol, but you are missing out if you don't enjoy the nasi lemak.

When you walk in, the open and bright interior welcomes you. The menu is simple and classic. The establishment is modern and trendy. The combination of the two creates this fun, casual, and nostalgic dining experience. 

Overall, this is a great place to unwind after a long day, catch up with some friends, or as the first stop of your incredible night.

text:
[1] Portobello Fritters $12.90

- We all knew good food coming before it reaches our table. All thanks to the fragrance from the truffle oil. Portobello fritters were so crispy, drizzled with truffle oil on the outside and best of all, it wasn't soaked with oil when we bite our way through it!! So good I think I could have a few servings on my own.

[2] Sambal Sotong $16.90

- These 2 sea creatures were presented to us in a nice char. "Almost" grilled to perfection but I thought cooking time could be a little shorter to keep the tenderness of the flesh. The flesh itself tasted slight garlicky and goes really well together with the sambal chilli.

[3] Salted Egg Yolk Calamari $13.90

- Salted Egg Yolk food items wasn't new to any one of us here, it has been trending for more than a year already. What made LHOD's dish stood out? Their version of salted egg yolk sauce was thick, grainy with salted egg bits and not salty. The proportions of salted egg, curry leaves and chilli were perfect where each individual ingredients did not overshine each other. Great on these breaded calamari! LHOD could consider using this sauce to create new dishes too.

[4] Prawn Paste Chicken Wings (4pcs) $15.90

- Look at these wings!! Chicken wings were huge and juicy within. Skin deep fried till super crispy, lightly marinated with prawn paste and a dash of herbs. A pity the marinade did not penetrate into the meat completely otherwise they would have tasted even better.

[5] Drinks:
[a] Iced Chocolate $7.90
- My kind of drink but it wasn't chocolatey enough for me. I preferred thicker sinful ones.

[b] Green Garden Fruit Fizzies $8.90
[c] Pink Passion Fruit Fizzies $8.90
[d] Lavender Blue Fruit Fizzies $8.90
[e] Sunny Day Fruit Fizzies $8.90

- These non-alcoholic thirst quenchers were more interesting. Pretty colors and interesting flavours made us couldnt make up our mind which to try first. We ordered the 4 most popular ones to try out. My favorite was the Pink Passion Fruit Fizzies. I love slight sourish drinks as it gave me more appetite to eat more!

Mains:
[6] Big Breakfast $16.90

- For this price we paying, portion served was really generous. Scrambled egg was done pretty well, just the way I love my eggs to be. The spinach and mushrooms were a little salty but they definitely complement the bread well. Served all day!

[7] Seabass wif Salad $34.90

- Fish meat was firm and succulent. Pretty to my eyes and tasty on my palate. The chef made the pan-fried potato balls looked like scallops, Genius! My 2nd most loved mains for the night.

[8] Pork Ribs wif Salad $32.90

- Whenever I order pork ribs, I'm most concerned with the tenderness of the meat and the sweetness level of the marinates. Lucky this plate didn't disappoint me. The marinates wasn't overly sweet and carried off a smokey aftertaste. The meat fell off bones easily, tender and nice.

[9] Spaghetti Laksa Prawns $26.90

- Tadahhhh.. My vote goes to this spaghetti laksa prawns for best dish tonight. Look at the huge prawns we were given! Very fresh and crunchy. The spaghetti texture was al dente and every mouthful you could taste the spiciness of the sauce. I love the fiery kick from the laksa sauce, but I could take something spicier. If only the sourish from the tomato base could reduce, I believe the laksa taste would outstand more. Nevertheless, this was still my top choice :)

[10] Chilli Crab Bun $19.90

- Who don't love crabs? Everyone on this table loved them! Chunks and chunks of generous crabmeat were made into patties and served to us in a delicious bun made in-house. Look at the Chilli crab drizzle, so generous and everything overflows! We almost licked up the plate *haha*

[11] Pulled Pork Sandwich $17.90

- If we compared this pulled pork sandwich with the chilli crab bun, the former crabby was so much better. Pulled pork was too dry and tough for my liking. Overall lacked the juiciness of meat which I found it a pity. 

Desserts:
[12] Sticky Date Pudding wif Vanilla Ice Cream $13.90

- Sticky date pudding was so good, we wiped it out in seconds. Every mouthful you can taste the fragrance of dates. Beware: It could get very sweet if you pair with the bananas given but we gals dun care! Whack!!

[13] Creme Brulee $10.90

- Tofu-liked vanilla custard base was smooth and slippery, eventually disappeared after touching our tongues. The torched sugar crust gave it more flavour. I would say it's a common item which can do with or without.

[14] Vanilla Bloom Pot $6.90
[15] Pandan Rose Bloom Pot $6.90
- These mini pots piped so beautifully with flower petals attracted us at first sight! Almost too pretty to eat them. Vanilla bloom pot tasted less sweet with a very nice milky flavour and fluffy sponge cake below. As for Pandan Rose, the frosting was too sweet although it smells good. But I couldn't finish the first mouthful. The Pandan cake below was slightly dense too. This flavour definitely for the sweet toothies only.

text:
The long awaited indie coffee chain serves great coffee even coffee snobs love albeit at a rather steep price. Try the Spanish latte ($7.80 for short, hot) which is sweetened with condensed milk for something special, or go for the classic Cafe Latte ($7 for short, hot).

Despite the cafe being rather crowded even on a weekday afternoon, the waiting time for the coffee was a short five minutes. Service was good. While some benches and tables are available outside the cafe, seating inside is limited.

Overall, a good coffee to try if you're at the nearby Haji lane but a bit pricey and inconvenient to get as it's not near the MRT

Grungy hole in the Wall Cafe (bright red rain awning at front door is how you know it's this cafe). Coffee offerings include oat or soy milk. I had former but it wasn't that great (quite sour) -- should use Oatly! Avocado toastie was amazingly yummy but way overpriced for three slices for $10 including a bunch of undressed salad leaves (!!)

Weekday morning and sufficiently empty and calm to find tables. Tad dark at some spots making reading difficult.

text: Dapper coffee is located on the second floor of a shophouse. It's a bit of a climb up, but once you enter, you feel like you've stepped into a secret world where people talk about all things indie and where you'll find out who's the next hottest underground artist. I ordered their latte, along with a Salted Egg Earl Grey chiffon cake. Their coffee was pretty nice, and I decided not to get their famous 'unicorn tears' or 'Merlion's blood', both of which APPARENTLY are basically nicely presented lemonade and ribena respectively, but I'll have a taste myself next time I drop by. In any case, it's not a very big space, with a bit of a narrow walkway between the bar and the rest of the seating (sat at the bar). I really liked my cake though, because even though salted egg has been done to death, the chiffon cake was very soft and melded well with the salted egg sauce, making for a light but satisfying snack. I'd come back, but pity they only open during work hours on the weekdays!

text:
I was staying at Marina Bay Sands and decided to do tea time before dinner!

In America we don't have TWG so I was excited to try it out!

As soon as you walk in you'll feel like you got transported to a Parisian cafe! The ambience, decorations even music was on point!
I loved how they were playing Andrea Bocelli the entire time!

We ordered macaroons and champagne! The macaroons were sensational!

Also! 

Big thank you to the staff for never letting my glass get empty! 

Can't wait to come back!!

text:
It has been a while since I last visited Okada Coffee and I finally got to try its signature Mont Blanc ($9), made with the premium chestnuts from its hometown Kumamoto. The patterned layers of Mont Blanc set it apart from the usual "noodle strand" chestnut cakes, with a meringue heart that gave a good measure of crunch. 

The Creme de marron was full of chestnut goodness but the Creme Chantily was in short supply and I wished it could be significantly less sweet. 

Fortunately, it's another chestnut sweet, the Okada Roll ($8), was rational on sugar. The core was pumped up with light chestnut cream and one could inhale whiffs of eggy aroma in the pillowy sponge. 

The Matcha Cake is a simple construction of green tea mousse, azuki beans and sponge. Nothing much fanciful.

Standard has dropped a lot over the years. 

Ordered the pancakes during a not so busy time of 4pm and they were pretty obviously microwaved and not freshly made. How do I know? Arrived almost instantly, with steam blazing hot coming out of the pancakes and a horrible texture that can only be achieved with microwaved-old-food. 

Tasted pretty horrible and the garnish of half a sliced banana was just sad. Was served with what tasted like cheap syrup rather than a maple sauce or anything remotely nice. 

Had the rosti as well. Did not add salt at all and the "poached" eggs were kinda hard boiled. Nothing was seasoned properly. Kinda disappointing because this was in my memory a great place to eat at. 

Prices are still high. Ordering system was good and efficient but poorly planned on some tables. The iPad was placed in the middle of 2 diners eating which to me was pretty poor thinking. The floor around me was wet and had food all around telling me that the servers were pretty oblivious to things going on around the restaurant. 

Pretty sure this does not happen that often here but this particular experience was exceptionally poor. For their prices & the amount of people that were there while I was there at 4pm, they really should have some sort of consistency towards their cooking with a full team of chefs in the kitchen.

I can't stop eating! And yet my attempts to put on weight and keep it on have been futile. I think I have worms in my tummy. 

A little birdie raved about this place to me. She went on and on about their breads, especially the Épi de Blé, Orange Cream Tart and Almond Croissant. She adviced me to go early - regulars just come and swipe the items off their shelves! So earlier this week, I hurried to this bakery before noon on Tuesday to get my breakfast before reporting for my afternoon shift in town.

Hungry, I bought whatever my buddy recommended.  I was surprised to discover that the base of the Orange Cream Tart is not the crusty kind but is actually soft bread. I found it a little too sweet though. The Almond Croissant and Épi de Blé were winners! The latter may appear alien, but it makes eating bread less messy - you won't grumble about crumbs falling on your clothes anymore! 

The bakery is too far for me to visit more often though. I don't go to Joo Chiat that frequently, so I'll just try out other offerings at the cafes they supply.

I came here one late Sunday morning for brunch. And sure enough, the crowd was thick. The problem with a popular place on a Sunday morning is getting seats and I believe they do not do reservations. So the troop of us, about 6 managed to squeeze ourselves on to a single small table in an odd corner of the place. 

The menu is a replicate of the one found in the other branch at Queen St. Nonetheless, the space and ambience fortunately makes up for the lack of a waiting staff. I would imagine that need to hire a lot more if they were to get people seated by waiters, the dining space is sprawling, indoors and out. 

The food, I had the works. And a beer on the side. Yes, Sunday morning beers. Heh. We had to line up at a counter to place our orders and pay for them at the same time. They advised that the food would be served in 30 minutes or less but in actual fact they came in about 10. Very fast and efficient I thought! The food was as expected, good. 

All in, a rather enjoyable Sunday morning for all us.

text:
Dunkin' Donuts @ FUNAN Mall...

Thank you for offering that Mochi version of Donut.  Thank you for not making it overly too sweet, for my sweet tooth.  Just a booth near to one of the entrances of Funan Mall.

For now the Berry MochiMochi and Chocolate MochiMochi received 3.25 stars in my books...

Too bad I did not get the chance to have the Dunkin' Donuts while I was at Massachusetts.  Did you know Dunkin' Donuts originate from Quincy Massachusetts in 1950??
They are very good for breakfast. Also love the friendly staff who always remember what I order.

text: Of the 5 hawker centres that I was able to go to, this one is my favorite. The food here is cheap, the portions are a good size to sample everything, but most importantly, the food is just amazing. Make sure to stop by Zhong Guo La Mian Xiao Long Bao for XLB and On Tap to wash down all the heavenly delicacies.

text:
We went to NOM for brunch on a Saturday. It wasn't too crowded, there was just another family there with us. My first impression of the place was that it was bare and clinical, with the stark white walls, cement floor and white tables and chairs. It felt.. cold. The mandopop music played through the speakers made me feel even more like an outsider.

I would say the food was average. We had the atlanta eggs benedict, blackstone eggs benedict, truffle fries and chocolate rainbow cake. 

Let's start with the best part- the cake. We got it only because it's supposedly the thing you must try if you're there. I've never been a fan of rainbow cake because they don't really taste like rainbows (cheat my feelings, you know?), but I'm glad I tried this one. The sponge was moist, fluffy and full of flavour, even without the chocolate icing. The icing was decadent - rich, creamy chocolatey goodness that melts in your mouth (and in your hands, I checked). 

The truffle fries were amazing as fries, not so much as truffle fries. They were actually cut potatoes and I believe they were air-fried or baked, so they were not greasy. The fries were crispy on the surface and hot on the inside. Unfortunately, we could barely taste the truffles. In terms of taste, the shaved parmesan on top had more impact.

The poached eggs were not that great, to be honest. They were almost cold by the time they were served, and one out the 4 was not runny in the middle. Toasting the english muffins and grilling the tomatoes would have improved the dishes, i think.

In summary, as NOM is quite out of the way for those who don't live in Macpherson, I think I'd need a stronger reason to go back. The cakes are definitely tempting, so i'd stop by for those if i'm nearby.

text:
It is super loud inside. The coffee preparation process is the noisiest ever. The staff keep hitting the coffee hopper - it's like they're taking out their frustrations on it. Luckily, in the outdoor seating area there are fans & the area is shaded from trees so it's OK to sit there. 

They use sugarcane straws which are of awful quality. I took one out and it had already broken. The second broke after a short while too so I just drank directly from the cup.

Had a sparkling lemonade. It was ok, though really an Italian soda  so I had to stir. It wasn't cheap but that's normal for cafe prices.

text:
Great great views of the Marina! The beer was top notch - excellent variety and very smooth. Definitely worth getting the beer paddle / flight. Service was also very good.

The food was decent - perhaps price outweighed the quality which is why I am knocking down a star. Pork chop was good, as were the fries. Brussel sprouts not my fave. My coworkers had the sirloin and didn't think it was worth it.

I would still 100% come back here and I definitely will!!!

text: Because there is always space for dessert! went on a Tuesday evening at around 7:30 and there was still a line. It was quick though, took us 10 minutes of waiting before  we got sested. Order and pay at the counter, and they will serve you your food. Food wise - the lavender earl grey soft serve ice cream is THE BEST and their waffles are great. My only complaint is the loudness inside the store. By virtue of it being so popular, the tables are packed such that I was back to back with another person and it was hard to move around at all in the store. I would say the soft serve and cakes are definitely worth it only if there's a short wait.

text:
Very reasonably priced European style bakery. Grab a tray and your own set of tongs and help yourself. Focus is on croissants, breads and rolls, no cream tortes here. The goods are as fresh as it gets- you can actually see the staff bake through a giant glass window. 
Credit cards accepted.

text:
- Cute, modern style cafe. 
- A few items on the menu weren't seasonal, but weren't available. 
- The Staff seemed like they didn't care, we had to go to the front desk to ask any time wanted something. And the whole staff was eating while we were eating. This should have been done prior to opening. 
- 2nd floor didn't open up until 2nd floor was full. 
- 1 bathroom available. 
- Don't sit below the flowers where the fan blows. We were constantly getting flowers blown in our drinks.

text:
Food was probably the only redeeming quality about the cafe. Their soufflé pancakes were nice and fluffy; if I ever do come back, it'll probably be only for that. Their garlic mushrooms and eggs were literally just assorted mushrooms and eggs; Would not recommend you order that. 

Service was pretty much dismal; one of the hostesses basically waved us off and let her colleague (who was super nice) sit us. 
The cashier buzzed us to indicated that our drinks were ready for collection, but he tried to give us the wrong one. (The layout doesn't make it easy to move around so I was a bit ticked when that happened because I knew I had to come back again)

Other than that, if you're into IG, this is the cafe for you! Because aesthetics wise, it was very pretty

text:
Neither my kouign amann nor my green tea croissant were as up to snuff as snob carb moi expected. The expectations were much too high. Certainly the ones I have had in other places had better buttery lamination with gooD flavor.

The KA simply wasn't buttery or fluffy enough ( sounds funny that a KA could actually NOT be buttery enuf)-- And the caramel-y bit was amiss. Not cheap prices, just expected more. Places like B and arcisault and Tartine are my benchmark comparisons.

Meh, not impressed by this place. There's no waiting area. It was a Sunday afternoon and seats are all taken. So my group of 4 awkwardly waited at the space near the entrance. 

When we finally got a table, it was by the window. It wouldn't be so bad if the sun didn't shine through and heating up our area. On the bright side, my friend(nearest to the window)'s coffee remained warm throughout.

I ordered scrambled eggs on toasted brioche, $10, with Harrisa sausage, +$4.50. The eggs were tad overdone to my liking instead of runny and creamy. For a moment, I thought I was at McD for Big Breakfast. Very plain and ordinary.

Not going back anytime soon since its just another cafe serving plain pricey eggs. But hey, at least they have free wifi. ;)

Beans sourced from Liberty Coffee Roasters.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Beans sourced from Liberty Coffee Roasters.'}]
text:
Flock Café is one of the more unassuming players in the thriving Tiong Bahru cafe scene. Somehow it feels genuine and laid-back, which can hardly be said for nearby establishments like Forty Hands and Open Door Policy, both of which have amassed loyal cult followings (quite deservedly) and lost their chill factor in the process. Well I suppose crowds are a good thing for cafes to have, though it would be nice to be able to have a meal without feeling like I'm in someone else's way all the time.

These crowds were absent from Flock when we visited one Saturday afternoon for tea. Bit of a welcome change from having to wait in the sweltering heat for a table. It wasn't that the eatery was devoid of people - there was a steady trickle of customers, and the staff looked hard at work.

Portobello, mozzarella & rocket sandwich, $13.50 - Since this was supposed to be tea we ordered one of their sandwiches to share. T'was a pricey sandwich, but I liked that the juicy portobello shroom was so big it occupied the entire pocket of ciabatta. This was quite delicious and would have made a substantial lunch for one, though y'know, the pig in me wishes they had fries on the side.

They have other interesting offerings on their sandwich list like prawn and avocado, as well as pork cheek and gruyere.

Orange bundt cake, $5.00 - Having had a disappointing encounter with a bundt cake the week before, we decided to give the orange bundt cake here a shot. I thought it had a nice citrusy fragrance and crumbled quite satisfactorily, but the others found it to be a little too dry.

Mocha, $6.00 - Flock sources its beans from the ever-reliable Liberty Coffee, which pretty much ensures quality coffee brews. The mocha we had was frothy, chocolatey and every sip was laced with a pleasant hint of bitterness.

In line with their philosophy of providing a "deliberately relaxed" ambiance conducive for weekend catch up sessions between friends, Flock was modestly, yet comfortably furnished and I loved the warm lighting. The food here is above average, and it's a lovely place to spend a lazy day, as all my weekends tend to be. Wouldn't mind coming back at all.

Rafee's Corner claims that they sell the best teh halia in Singapore. While the claim might be a little bit OTT, their teh halia tarik and teh tarik really hits the spot for me. For lovers of Mr Tea's teh tarik, the ones brewed by Mr Rafee (I assume that's the name of the boss who does the brewing) might not be what they are looking for. But what I love about the tah halia from Rafee's Corner is the generous amount of ginger they put inside the tea - making the tea tangy and soothing at the same time. For those who prefer not to have ginger, their teh tarik is also very good - smooth and creamy with a very strong, wholesome taste of tea leaves in every sip.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/ioKUT48R0lKkmdqKJxXGAQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/coffee-break-singapore?reviewid=HulugAMMcEhhaP9DRwEeqQ&select=ioKUT48R0lKkmdqKJxXGAQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Coffee Break - Singapore, Singapore. Earl grey and black sesame kaya toast, and caramel latte', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Earl grey and black sesame kaya toast, and caramel latte'}]
text:
The line was really long, but there is a lady that walks down the line with an ipad to take orders. I recommend taking a picture of the menu before getting on the line so you can decide your order as you wait instead of deciding when she reaches you.

We ordered 2 kaya toasts - the black sesame and the earl grey, as well as one of their most popular drinks, the caramel latte. The black sesame kaya toast was stronger, whereas the early grey had a lighter flavor. The caramel latte was sweet, but not overly sugary. It's a great place to pick up snacks for a coffee break in between sampling all the hawker stands, a nice modern twist on the traditional kaya toast spread.

text:
Tooo much good places to choose from but all so so so amazing.
The hianan chicken, congee, and all the fruit stands where what I went straight too. I also loved the dumpling too.

Set upon a lush, peaceful backdrop of the reservoir, this place as a sleeper vibe. Staff was super attentive. The fish tacos and waffles are good. Decently prized and portions are not measly for Singapore's standard. Get your face into their fish tacos and ice cream waffles, they're good! The rendang burger is average.

Positive vibes and them treating customers like friends won me over. Definitely supporting this small business!

A nice big hawker center in the heart of the trendy Tiong Bahru district. Big selection of stalls, though most are Chinese or seafood, not many Halal options. The shark nugget soup is a must try. I don't know what exactly was in the syrupy stuff, but super good. The pork rice is also very good. Prices are of course super low too.

I never tried the food at Prive so I am in no position to comment but visually the food at Prive's fine dining restaurant looks a lot more appetizing as opposed to the food served up at Prive's cafe/bistro. 

The Prive Bar has a great setting with outdoor couches facing the yachting docks. For a moment it actually feels like you're not in Singapore. 

Back to reality, I had a  mixed berries mojito which was honestly terrible. The ice was not crushed nor blended properly leaving behind mini ice cubes. The mojito was quite sweet as well which made me wonder if fresh or canned berries were used. Lastly, it came in a really huge tall glass which just further emphasized quantity and not quality. I would definitely return but only for the location and comfortable seating!

text:
I like Coffee & Toast when I have a craving for a Singaporean breakfast. Their prices are reasonable at $4 for a Kopi (of your choice), 2 eggs, and kaya toast set.

Brought a colleague to this one for his first ever SG brekkie experience and he also enjoyed.

It took a few tries but I finally understand the appeal of the runny eggs with soy sauce and kaya toast topped off with some strong kopi. Delicious combo!
Tried many different brunch places in Singapore, quite a few I would like to have another visit. This is on my favorite list, which I could even go everyday, right after the first try.

Brews for the day', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Brews for the day'}]
text:
After only 2 visits, tiong hoe has commandeered a place in my heart and quickly taken the top spot for a cuppa. 

On my first visit, we went during a weekday and was relatively quiet. It allowed us to peruse the descriptions of the different single origin beans. 

The cappuccinos are excellent as is the brew. I can't remember which beans I chose but the flavours were bright and robust. Payment is on a tip basis, it's so refreshing to see businesses place trust in their customers and not purely for profit. 

The owner was present at the store and you could see his passion just bubbling over. He was regaling the customers with tales of his experiences purchasing beans and being in the coffee business. You just can't help but want to sit down for that bit longer to learn from such a knowledge uncle! The neighborhood feel has been fantastic and won the top spot in my books.

text:
I ordered the scrambled eggs on croissant which came with bacon and I asked to not have feta on top. For drinks, I ordered the cold drip iced coffee and an elderflower soda. 

It's rather a sticker shock to eat in cafes and restaurants in Singapore. Mostly the price of "artisanal" coffee is ridiculous. But I understand that Singapore's rent is ridiculously unaffordable so guests have to pay a premium to come to bricks and mortar cafes, bars, restaurants. 

My cold drip coffee which was served in a tiny glass with ice was $6.  
I was suffering from major jetlag and needed extra caffeine so this obviously made me incredibly sad. 

The food made up for it. My friend ordered a curry chicken and truffle fries to share. I tried a bit of her chicken and it was good. Not too spicy. I can't stand when curries burn a hole in your mouth. (Insert fake Asian joke here!) it was creamy and hearty but lacking in a depth of lemongrass, galangal, and tamarind. The truffle fries were salty, just enough Parmesan for umami, and addicting! 

My dish was better though. 

The dish came out looking HUGE! I gave some to my friend. The fluffy eggs were cooked beautifully and the croissant was buttery, flaky, and soft! My only complaint would be the bacon but that's a personal preference (which many people share) of having super crispy bacon. I like my bacon crispy and these were just mediocre. 

Would I come back here? Sure but I'll try something else.

text:
A hidden gem (can I still say this? It's getting less and less hidden by the week!) in the currently low traffic Galaxis. Prices are very reasonable, and the coffee, breads, pancakes and dessert are fantastic. The sandwiches are decent but not outstanding.

The flat white in particular is executed skillfully, with a roast that isn't too acidic, topped off with smooth, creamy microfoam.

The wife enjoyed the sweet pepper vegetarian sandwich while my toddler who's been having a bad week cheerily gobbled down the classic scrambled eggs on toast (rye bread).

The butterscotch & berries pancakes were soft and fluffy (get this!), and we couldn't get enough of the banana coconut bread pudding with gula melaka caramel and vanilla ice cream (get this too!)

Give the cookies a miss though - they were dry (we prefer soft and gooey) and were a tad too sweet.

Another great coffee shop in Bukit Timah. Great selection of brewed and espresso coffee. Hot and cold. They also have two selections of nitro brewed coffee. 
What is obvious is how much passion has gone into this shop. Take a look at the hardware that they have installed for roasting and brewing. They are very serious about their Joe.

A small, very local mom and pop cafe next to Goldbell and inside the Prudential Center that mostly served as a lunch spot for me when I was short on time.

A small tip to venture in quickly before noon to avoid the typical lunch crowd and long lines- after 1pm and chances of anything being left or catering to your palette was slim. 

Nothing prepared fresh at the time- everything is prepacked in styrofoam or plastic containers. My go to was the fried rice with chicken. They also have noodle options that were a little on the bland/hard side, but the rice was always a safe bet. The iced coffee is also delicious.

Again, nothing to write home about, this was always a last minute resort kind of place for me, but on the plus side it's relatively inexpensive.

4.5!

Love this healthy and authentic Scandinavian eatery in Raffles Place! Wish I had tried this place sooner when I worked at the area.  It takes a bit long for the order to come out, but it serves one of the freshest and healthiest dishes in Sing. I tried the smoked salmon sandwich and immediately regretted that I only ordered one, and the thick and hearty avocado soup was one of the best I've tried.  

They have combo lunches such as meatballs and chicken that come with pasta, broccoli, and roasted cauliflower, and salads that are simple yet unique in taste. D takes away dinners for me randomly as I crave this place on a time to time basis. The owner is usually always on site and he's been helpful in choosing the meals I want. highly recommended!

text:
Privé @ Paragon is my go to lunch venue. 

Love their salads! I like Mediterranean Salad best. The other salads are good too.

I also like their satay. A bit stingy on the sauce but you can ask for more.

I like their English muffin with plant-based meat (was told they make it themselves), potato wedges & small salad as well as their vegan roll too.

Hazelnut cappuccino is lovely.

Service from a staff named Bey is excellent!

text:
Younger sibling of The Flying Squrriel (Telok Ayer Street). Workshop brings the jap fusion menus, all day happy hour and a good cup of coffee to the heartland. 

Bento sets are from $10 and comes with 2 generous portion of sides. Good value.

I had the Wagyu beef bowl, minced beef topped with a cold poached egg. The grainy, slightly dry beef mixed with cold mushy egg white. Interesting combo.

text:
I have lost count how many times I passed next to this store and the wonderful smell was always there!

I entered this store and I felt that I was in Disney, at least, my kind of Disney! with so many different tea flavors, teapots and cup of all sizes and forms.

I wish I could take them all.

The service was on point and their macaroons were extremely delicious, they practically melted in my mouth. All the flavors were screaming my name and the price was great; only $2.00 per piece.

Thank you!

text:
Hidden in a little back corner at bustling Far East Plaza is this branch of this lesser known chain. Perfect for those like me who wants to enjoy a quiet traditional breakfast of a cup of kopi, soft boiled eggs and kaya bread but dont want the noise and crowds at the popular Ya Kun. 
Though not so traditional is their wonderful take on the traditional toast. Here, you have the option of ciabatta toast which is fluffier and less dry than normal kaya toast. Even better is the orange ciabatta where the tinge of orange zest complements perfectly with the smooth pandan kaya. 
As with most kopi toast places, they also serve an array of local asian fare for a more filling meal. These include curry chicken, laksa and mee siam.

There are so many great food stalls in this Hawker.
My favorite would be the Lao Ban, the Fried Kway Teow, the claypot chicken rice and the little stall that does Popiah.
But no matter what local craving you have, this is the place to go to satisfy it!

Rum and raisin', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Rum and raisin'}]
text:
I love ice cream, gelato, sorbets, sherbets, milk shakes, and all the other brethren and cousins twice removed in the icy family tree. Imagine my pleasant surprise when it's closing time, and my sad puppy eyes yield the last scoops of gelato for the day. Score! I get hit up with a decadent scoop of rum and raisin - heady rum, boozy raisins, and that airy, almost fluffy poofy chewy texture of gelato that I haven't experienced in years. I'm a texture person, and most places don't do it right. Either it's too creamy, too milky, too hard, too dense, too icy, or too pedestrian. This, my friends, was revelatory. 

Price point is fair, throw in good conversation over which flavour to pick, and a toss up between strawberry cheesecake or Baileys Irish Cream. I'll be back, and next time.. I'll be getting a tub of each, and one more scoop of that rum and raisin for the road.

So far the best hawker centre ever with great food and hospitable vendors. I'm just so glad that some of my favourite stall are not pushed aside after the renovation. 

If you're coming here, I'd recommend you to try out the following 

- Beef noodle. It's quite obvious there as it is the only one, just walk towards the ban chang kueh stall deep inside the hawker centre

- Ban chang kueh beside beef noodle. It's really good and they are still doing it old-fashioned style which I personally prefer over Mr Bean's

- Nonya cake shop, located beside the kway chap stall. Near to beef noodle shop, try to spot the bright white neon sign. 

- Tiong Bahru Pau. You would spot this easily as they're the only store to occupy two stalls at the left of the escalator. Queue early in the morning as they're usually sold out by 11 am. 

- Prawn Noodle. It's located somewhat near the toilet, you'd definitely spot it since it has a long queue

- Oyster Omelette beside the famous pork rice. The stall is manned by a very nice and chatty uncle. Although I couldn't really speak chinese, he still tries to relate to me, something I don't really experience in Singapore anymore. The food itself is really good too! Large, fresh oyster was used and the sambal was very fragrant. 

- Char Kway Teow. This is the legendary stall, located to on the left when you come up from the escalator. Try to spot the orange store sign and long queue and voila you arrive at the correct stall. While it is very oily (by very I really do mean it), it has that wok hei that no food court has managed to replicate. It is truly a definitive mark of an experienced cook. 

I'm pretty sure there are many others stall that are just as good but I may not spot it yet. The above are just a snippet of my suggestion if you're crunched for time yet want to experience Tiong Bahru Market.

text:
So delish.  After admiring their sleek new shop at the Jewel, my cousin surprised me with a durian swiss roll during my stay in Singapore...and it was incredible.  Fresh durian with lots of flavor, the fluffiest cake, and plenty of whipped cream.  Since then, I've been to their old school (original) Kompong Glam shop twice to buy a number more rolls for family and gifts for others.  I've still only tasted durian since I'm durian obsessed but have heard very good things about kaya as well.  

Cash only, and the nearest ATM is at the Raffles hospital.

A very nice interior drew us there for brunch.

Alas it does not make up for eye watering prices and practices such as not offering ice water (instead, you have to pay for your water) and a 2 hour then return the table policy.

Portion size was small, which was expected, but the food was average, which was unexpected given the popularity and look of the place. The avocado chunks were literally black in half the cases - not just lightly oxidised but thoroughly black throughout - no self respecting chef would have served that. The hummus lacked salt. The $10 grapefruit juice they call a "no-tail" was not really worth it. The cocktails looked better. We walked on to Common Man to top up the calories despite spending over $100++, rather than try the desserts.

I recognised a few people from the hip crowd (including a Vogue cover). For some reason this place is "cool" right now, perhaps the great interior which beats the usual drab school chairs and tables with raw concrete, perhaps the fans which make the heat bearable, perhaps the lack of options nearby. Tables are very close together and the one next to us was quite interested in our conversation.

The Good:
  :: a local business!
  :: service is you get seated, then you order food from the counter. when it's ready they deliver it to you at your table. very straightforward!
  :: delicious, healthy fare. go for brunch! i had the eggs with mushrooms and bacon, and it was so yummy
  :: they also serve coffee, tea, and pastries
  :: they take credit cards

The Bad:
  :: can get really really crowded during peak times
  :: not ideal for large groups. small groups are fine, but if you want to come here with a group larger than 2-4 people, you are going to struggle to find a place for you all

The Ugly:
  :: none

Would I go back? For certain! This place is a really great, charming, casual dining experience that makes me feel like I'm back in the States. 

This place is IN.

The brunch here is one of the better ones I've had in Singapore for the longest time. 

The ambience here is great and you can spot many other like minded individuals and families here having coffee and enjoying the food.

It's shaded from the sun, thanks to a large awning and there's ample smoking area. the fans provide just the right amount of breeze should you choose to sit outside, or you can sit in air-conditioned comfort inside and watch the chefs prepare your meal, thanks to an open kitchen concept.

text:
This stall is a cupcake bakery that sells gourmet and heavenly cupcakes in different sizes and even in pop sticks. They have a wide variety of flavours and all taste yummy. The service is also extraordinary as it is a small stall after all and they make customers feel at home. 

My favourite cupcake flavour has got to be the strawberry burst as it has fresh strawberries and it is topped with strawberry cream cheese frosting! Simply divine. Price wise it was quite reasonable as well. A good option for parties or gatherings as it brings people closer when you talk about the flavours and textures of the cake.

Overall a good place to have your cupcakes and one of the few cupcake stores in Singapore that actually sell nice cupcakes with so many varieties.

text:
Since this Starbucks opened, students have been flocking here like flies to honey. Seriously, unless you're incredibly lucky to enter just when someone's leaving, it's unlikely you'll find a seat.

Same goes for the iMacs in the middle of the coffee shop: I've never seen them unoccupied. And hey, iMacs in a Starbucks! Is anything cooler than that?!?!

That said, if you're not fussy about air-conditioning, you can always get takeaways and sit at the much bigger study area just outside the coffee shop. It stays relatively cool no matter how hot the whether gets thanks to the huge fan spinning above.

text:
Really love the interior of this place, the row of good-looking bakery goodies really make the best backdrop of a nice quaint cafe.

Came here for brunch on a weekend and it wasn't as crowded as we thought it'd be, or perhaps we were really early.

Had the poached eggs with salmon, my usual. It was great but I felt they were a little too heavy handed on the vinegar. Also had the creme brulee for dessert, not the best one I've had. The almond croissant was delicious though, crisp and creamy flavourful.

The service here is satisfactory - was rudely acknowledged with a snooty head nod when I called for service.

Not sure I'd come back here again for the food, but maybe only if I'm in the area and craving for some good pastries.

This place was such a let down. It may look pretty on the outside but the food was wayy overpriced in my opinion and it honestly wasn't anything spectacular. 

I had the scrambled eggs with sausages and mushroom breakfast thingy for $9.80 and a cup of hot chocolate. Hot chocolate was bitter and disappointing. The eggs were alright. They didn't have any sandwiches when I was there (11am ish) and I was pretty disappointed by that. Furthermore, the staff were really unfriendly.

text:
Honey ginger tea- they use real ginger and the tea is strong and soothing. For $3 it's a pretty good deal
It's cash only

text:
Came here on July 3rd, the same day as their re-opening day after renovation. I had waffle with bacon and scrambled egg (S$18), which is not bad overall- taste wise. The texture of the scramble egg is pretty good- it was fluffy, but I just wished they give some herb or whatever into it to enhance the flavor cos it turned out pretty plain to me. For the Bacon & Waffle, we all know how easy to prepare them.. but even the waffle was just mediocre. Honestly for that price range for such a simple dish, I expected much more. 

The same thing with the seafood pasta (S$23). It was just ok only. I've had better. The texture of the pasta is a bit wrong - like it was over cooked. Pasta is the easiest dish to make with high margin. I'm sure that I don't ask to much if at least I want my pasta to be al dente. I could name some cafe that offers brunch places at a lower price and higher standard of food. 

On the plus side, this place offers free wifi, comfortable seatings with elegant & relaxing ambiance.

This place is cute and well air conditioned, but super pricey!!

I had their aloe vera addiction tea for $8.  It was just ok...my boo had their coffee.  Not much else to say except it's a good place to take a break, since we were dying from the heat and walking around lots :P

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/poj8YyqZIeTu-fAWH1vY1w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/spinelli-coffee-company-singapore-3?reviewid=g2rTV1Ua4Z-8t9nsJxF0FA&select=poj8YyqZIeTu-fAWH1vY1w', 'altText': 'Photo of Spinelli Coffee Company - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: The food and the coffee here are just OK. You can get better coffee and pastries at any number of places within a block or two. That said, Spinelli's has a great area to just sit and relax, work, read...whatever. They have air-conditioned indoor seating for hot days and outside seating to take advantage of great weather. There is almost always room as well, which is sometimes a scarce commodity in this area!

Bad, Inattentive service in a restaurant that had only 5 other patrons on a sleepy Saturday afternoon. 
Average food. 
Higher than expected prices. 
In a land of amazing eats, this is an easy pass.

text: Not a big fan of CBTL anymore as they often don't have my favorite drinks: Chai Latte.  And even when they do, sometimes it's a tea bag which tastes very different than if it were an extract or brewed.  Not sure what they are thinking but they make it anyway without informing and I often have to cancel and get my money back.  A complete waste of my time.

Pork hash', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pork hash'}]
text: I've been here a few times since I discovered Jimmy Monkey. Each time for breakfast on the weekend. Grab a menu and order at the counter, then the wait staff will bring out the food. The coffee is excellent, and I love the vibe of the place. The staff is friendly and attentive. Yes, the food is a little price-y, but not too far out of range for this kind of place. My favorite so far is the hash. Just a little bit of spice and just satisfying enough for brunch.
Wonderful breakfast experience! Loved the chicken peanut curry and the speciality coffees. Staff was attentive and polite. Will definite be back again to check out their dinner scene.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/jnSBwh4H2g2XzcKMG-GVQw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/clinton-street-baking-company-and-restaurant-singapore?reviewid=RhVXYYsYZ4DtCnbrpwX_8Q&select=jnSBwh4H2g2XzcKMG-GVQw', 'altText': 'Photo of Clinton Street Baking Company & Restaurant - Singapore, Singapore. Mangled upside down pineapple cake', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Mangled upside down pineapple cake'}]
text:
My first time here. Ever. Didn't know about the New York branch so there is no basis for comparison. I've heard lots of excited rumblings of course, and friends who used to live in New York were thrilled about its opening. Fair enough. From all accounts, I hear that this place largely works. The food is comparable and all. I'll have to take their word for it. 

I only came here for some cake and I got the upside down pineapple cake. I don't know why but seeing a badly sliced and sloppily presented cake annoyed me. It shows a lack of care in the attentive-level of staff.

When I went to pay, I noticed that other cakes (of other flavors) were similarly badly sliced. Woah. 

I really did think Clinton St Bakery was better than this. 

Taste-wise, the cake was fine. Not great, not terrible. The staff was sufficiently polite. But I think the devil's in the details and they need to teach their staff how to slice cakes properly, lift the slices and place them on plates.

Jewel&#39;s Red Velvet latte - not to be missed', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "Jewel's Red Velvet latte - not to be missed"}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/U9Bmgh4YXSMycxgRa2chtg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/jewel-coffee-singapore-8?reviewid=5eqMoKKWLZCPGDsenJmGvQ&select=U9Bmgh4YXSMycxgRa2chtg', 'altText': 'Photo of Jewel Coffee - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
My daily coffee fix - I cannot believe that I waited so long to tell the world about their amazing coffee and service :)

Thanks to Jewel, I became an absolute coffee snob. Their baristas are true experts, their coffee beans carefully selected - and you can pick from two coffee bean choices every day - with the coffee itself being pure velvety, strong goodness.

Ask for the stamp card if it is not automatically given to you, as you'll get a free coffee once your card is full.

The staff is cheerful and seems to love what they're doing. Food is quite good - I've had pasta, bacon & egg muffin and a ham & cheese melt before.

My current crush is their Red Velvet latte, which is an absolute revelation that I don't know how to live without anymore. Good for them, tricky for me ;)

Super crowded (as usual). We went at 3pm and managed to find a sweet spot! 

Love the vibe of the place! A hipster joint right smack in the middle of the good ole' heartland :) 

We had the hoky pokey ice-cream (vanilla and honey comb) with waffles and a mocha (strong). 

Price-wise, it's definitely on par with other cafes at more prominent locations. I've notice the trend of new cafe/creameries moving to the heartlands because of the lower rent. YAY for convenience but sadly I don't see any decline in prices despite this.

text: I was really looking forward to an amazing experience but it really fell short. The food is terrible and the service is even worse. But hey, where else can you go to grab a nibble or a drink and sit in a place that looks like the scene at FRIENDS and watch FRIENDS episodes? The menu is entertaining and witty, but they really need to improve their service and food. My Thanksgiving sandwich didn't even have a moist maker! Huge disappointment. The cheesecake wasn't even good enough to eat off of the floor! They really could do better.

text:
Pro tip: 
- This place is a classic case of hit or miss. If it's a hit, probably one of the best Hainese Chicken. 
- Expect to wait in line anywhere between 5 to 30 mins. 

Having visited Tiong Bahru market a lot,  I've typically had made by way  over to The Tiong Bahru Boneless Chicken stall for their Chicken and rice. But I must say this  place is a hit or miss for me. It's either super tender or dry and overly chewy pieces. 

Since the portion sizes are small 
I ordered the double meat portion steam/baked and bean sprouts. Total price 8 dollars.

Regarding lines, expect to waiting anywhere between 5 to 30 mins

text:
My boyfriend loved this place. Hands down, of all the places we went to, we went to this place TWICE because he liked it that much (the pasta). Our first dining experience here was amazing---service was spot on and spectacular. Second time, we had to flag down our server several times and it left us feeling a certain way we didn't care for. 

The place is situated right in the middle of mall which certainly gives  great opportunity to people watch. Definitely worth the trip depending on what server you get!

text: So visiting my brother here in Singapore and we wanted some bagels for breakfast. Now we're from NYC so we know how a bagel should taste. For some reason this bagel was flat it was missing some of that cushion. Now I'm sure it's really hard to get bagels here in Singapore. But 101 before in baking dough is, dough needs to rise. This gives it that consistency of that doughy taste. Unfortunately there was no rise. They have great combinations of putting a sandwich together but their main focus should be making that bagel taste great. Try it out and you can see what I mean.

text: Ok so I've walked by these many times, finally went in the one at great world city.  Had the pasta that wasn't bad, nothing special though.  This seems to be more suited for coffee or some 10, 000 calorie beverage and desert, so I believe the food receives less attention.  Don't order the chicken wings.  Being from the south I'm not known to walk away from fried yard bird (chicken) but I did this time.  It seem that it had re fried a couple of times.

Soy Flat White', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Soy Flat White'}]
text:
Cute hipster cafe hidden behind a roller door on Horne. Inside is very minimalistic and slick. Menu is short and sweet, but offering something for everyone. 

Coffee is perfectly presented and tastes amazing. Very smooth, strong but not bitter and tasty. Small selection of Italian blend fruit drinks and plenty of tea options too.

Ordered the bagel plate - a generous serving of creamy scrambled eggs, fresh smoked salmon and a currant bagel with fresh cream cheese. So much food, and it was divine. E ordered the Guac & Scrambled Egg combo - beautifully presented and she loved it. Wish this place was closer to home, I'd visit weekly!

Nice place to hang out for those who enjoy instagram worthy food. But the taste and the price doesn't really quite measure up as much to the presentation. 

Generally wouldn't be my natural choice to visit but it's nice to hang out if you are willing to splurge a little and take some nice photos with your food to boost some social media likes. 

They do come up with new items regularly so for those who likes gimmicky food, do consider them!

Free Maison jars with cold coffee drinks', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Free Maison jars with cold coffee drinks'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/zZhUPogimdoNWopbgGMv3A/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/hot-singapore-2?reviewid=aHaIMY6eXQ6mqbixVWOGeQ&select=zZhUPogimdoNWopbgGMv3A', 'altText': 'Photo of HOT - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}]
text: HOT stands for House of Taste.  Coffee by day, after work watering hole by night. The space is uniquely shaped, and small, but they have done a good job of maximizing the seating area.   The interior design is industrial modern and very cool.  They are known for their single origin specialty coffee.  There will always be something new to taste or smell here as they change their coffee bean selection regularly.  They always have 3 options of beans to choose from.  Depending on how you want your coffee - espresso style, or V60 pour-over.  All their coffees are served double shot.   There is also a selection of tees, cold-pressed juices, and aloe vera drinks.  They also had a selection of deserts, in house made sandwiches, and yoghurt-granola jars. The menu can be overwhelming for a first timer like me, but the staff were extremely friendly and helped walk me through my options.  They suggested that I try an iced coffee latte.  It was refreshing, flavorful,  and served in a mason jar that is yours to keep (included in the price). Quality coffee at decent Singaporean prices.  I wish my hotel was near this spot as I would have come back here several times during my trip if I could.

Nice place to get breakfast and watch American baseball, or even NFL football. They always also have a rugby game going.  All of the usual suspects are offered for breakfast, mostly served with grilled tomato or baked beans, a very English/Australian breakfast.  They do serve a Texas size toast for those that like alot of bread in the AM. 

Be careful of ordering a alcoholic beverage for breakfast as its pricey. Stick with a coffee or orange juice without the kick.

This is the only place in Boat Quay that is open for breakfast, not as glamerous as brunch at The Fullerton, but still a sold choice if you are looking to eat breakfast in the area.

They are one of the few speciality coffee shops in the area.  Very fresh and all beans have dates.  They don't have full body kind, but that's alright other beans are also good.
Thanks for opening here.  You are awesome!
こちらでは少ないスペシャリティコーヒーのお店です。ここで焼いているわけではありませんが、ストレートコーヒーをちゃんと焼いた日付を記して販売しています。日本のように苦めの焼き方はしてませんが、十分美味しいです。
お値段もお手頃で、いいお店ですね。2015/11

text: Beautiful Victorian ironwork lace building housing dozens of food vendors.  Aesthetically, perhaps my favorite Hawker Center.

Great ambience with wide spaces - something hard-pressed to find in Singapore. Food range is surprising wide. Love the food choices we made although the poached egg is still far from world standards. The coffee is good. A glance at the drinks list reveals another surprisingly wide range of whiskeys, cocktails and beers. A bit hidden from the main road but a definite gem if you are looking to chill in a unique and cool environment amidst good beverages and decent food

text:
A solid hawker centre if you're looking for a legit Singapore eating experience.

My current faves include:

#01-02: Hua Kee Hougang Famous Wan Ton Mee
The $5 portion of the dumpling noodle fed this hungry preggo lady well! I could've shied away from the chilli but I figured it wouldn't do the dish justice if I skipped it. The dumplings were stuffed to the brim and delicious. Throw in the copious amount of al dente noodles in a bowl and it is BEST.

#01-12: Lao Fu Zi Fried Kway Teow
I love Char Kway Teow and am not very particular with my stalls. Just know this one does the dish justice.

#01-51: Waan Waan
This is a Thai dessert spot that does coconut ice cream. Their dishes are quite refreshing in this Singapore heat; however they do try to upsell me sometimes even though I tell them straight up that I'm not interested... not a fan of that.

Next time I want to try some of the curry puff stalls and the banana fritter stall in the back!

A dead ant on the lettuce', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'A dead ant on the lettuce'}]
text:
Flock or Flop?

Had wanted to have lunch Hua Bee Restaurant but had unfortunately got there too late. 

Deciding that it was way too hot and we were way too hungry to look elsewhere, we decided to give Flock Cafe a try, seeing how popular it was. 

Flock's Scrambled Eggs and Toast($7.50 + $2.50 for a side of baked beans) 
I have to admit, the scrambled eggs were pretty decent. Good texture, not over cooked. The sautéed mushrooms were forgettable, baked beans were.... well.... tasted canned and the sourdough was unfortunately pretty hard and crunchy (almost like a crouton). 

Scrambled Eggs & Croissant w/ Crispy Bacon ($15.90)

Scrambled Eggs, consistent with mine so that's a good sign. The croissant was pretty buttery and was nice and flakey. Bacons were fried nice and crispy (although I'm more of the juicy tender bacon person than the crispy sort).
The salad was an after though and came looking a bit limp and old. The most disappointing? The salad wasn't washed clean. The wife was just about to take a bit and suddenly noticed a dead ant on one of the lettuce leaves. Tsk tsk. Big disappointment. 

Overall, while the Eggs were pretty good but everything else seemed like an after though. Definitely not a place we're chose to come back to.
Salmon Rosti and French toast were delish! I will be back to try the dirty burger and the beers on tap!

My new favorite neighborhood spot. I love places that just make a few things but do them well. The Nanban Chicken bao was my favorite. The chicken is juicy, and the skin perfectly crispy and light, and the Japanese tartar sauce is just right. 

My wife had the classic pork belly and salted egg shrimp bao, which were also both excellent but not quite as good as the chicken for my taste. Lastly, their truffle fries were a bit on the salty side, but full of cheesy truffley goodness. 

Besides the food, the decor is right up my alley. Clean and modern, wide open spaces and gray and brown accents. 

Service was super fast, which is another big plus with places that have small menus. We had our bao in less than five minutes after ordering, which is great for a case of mid-afternoon munchies.

text: Cozy and quiet place in the middle of Orchard Road to indulge in all things matcha. I chose an order which had a bit of everything- soft serve, crepe cake and fruits. Would have appreciated a bit more fruits but otherwise the portion is just nice and not too overwhelming. Can definitely taste the matcha flavour and it's not too sweet. Would drop by again in future.

This is a difficult place to find because it is located in the basement level.  It's actually next door to the McDonald's behind Shiraz on Orchard.

Like all Killiney's, this place located off Orchard was a regular place for me to go to get coffee.   Very good cheap breakfasts eats here.  For $S4.50 (about $US4), you can purchase a coffee, soft boiled egg, and French Toast.  They offer a take out as well.  The French Toast is similar to French Toast back at home (toast battered in egg) but unique in the kind of bread used and served with kaya, a coconut flavored jam that's pretty good.

I do not know how they do it, but their coffee, served with sweet condensed milk is always perfect.  I seldom drink coffee with milk or sugar, but when I come here, I have it the way they serve it and it's always the best.

text:
Cute dessert spot nestled in the Gillman Barracks, perfect for escaping the heat after visiting the surrounding art exhibits. It's also conveniently located along the Southern Ridges trail, making it ideal for a quick dessert detour!

Got to try the Sea Salt Gula Melaka and the premium Richest Dark Chocolate Ferrero flavors. Both were super satisfying, but must admit the richness of the dark chocolate overpowered the gula melaka. The waffles were really crispy and great for soaking up the ice cream. 

Overall: Definitely one of the top ice cream spots in town (can see why people order pints to bring home!). Also love the chill, natural ambience of the outdoor seating area.

Sorry... I've had to dock a star. I enjoyed this place for coffee and went back to try a brunch on a Saturday. It was crowded, and the staff weren't very on the ball when it came to seating waiting customers. Tables were cleared but waiting customers were still left waiting... Tried the Big Brekkie and it was OK. The eggs were purportedly 60 degree eggs but I'm pretty sure mine were over cooked and too firm.

text: As 3 peter a good menu. The food didn't let down either. Service was decent. The greatest thing about this place, though,it's the ambiance.  It looks like a converted warehouse of sorts but can't be. I liked it.

This place salvages a three star rating because of the atmosphere. The desserts are way over-hyped in my opinion and priced far beyond what they're worth. The churros and hot chocolate were the best dish we had but were nevertheless underwhelming and exceedingly bitter. The chocolate forest dessert was such an odd selection of flavours it was impossible to discern what the goal was. It is almost as if so much is attention to distinguishing the look of the dishes that the flavour profile is just sort of thrown together. I am sad to say this feels like a place seeming high-class by making its dishes rather obscure just for the sake of appearance.

text:
Hipster cafe in a rustic neighborhood. Main attraction: waffles

A friend brought me here, she can't stop raving about this place's waffles. We alighted at Braddell Station and walked in between the HDB block to get to this cafe. Approx 5mins.

It's an old neighborhood, so it is fairly easy to find a parking lot if you plan to drive. 

Typical cutesy, cosy hipster cafe. Nothing over the top, generally well decorated. 

We ordered a Waffles with chocolate ice cream, cafe latte, citron tea and Mexican wings. Approx $22

They arrived fairly quickly. Waffles was good, and clearly they take pride in it - there is a dedicated chalk board to justify and tell people just why their waffles is so good and how they made them. In addition, the wifi password is "crispywaffles".

The coffee was below average, citron tea was ok. The Mexican wings were terrible. They all had a weird smell to them, felt like it was dunked in some detergent or cleaning solution. It was so bad, we had to stop eating them. Informed the staff when she cleared our plates, claims she will look it up but did not come back with a response. Instead, she sat down and watch her drama series.

I would have given them more stars probably 3/5. If not for them - disregarding customers feedback and the horrible wings. The one and only thing (maybe two) that you would visit this place for would be the waffles and maybe the ice cream.

text:
Decided that we need to go local so I went on a Sunday morning quest for coffee beans while Aga studied. We've been bringing them back from trips to Australia. Would never ever have stumbled across this place without the recommendation. They roast their own beans and serve nothing but coffee. 
Super happy with the Four Chairs espresso blend and 2 iced coffees I've had there. On both visits the staff were friendly and knowledgeable. Last night I snuck in just before closing and the whole team were cupping different roasts that someone had brought back from Scandinavia.

Robot is a good, solid, comfortable place.

Many items at Robot are made in-house.  This includes their light, buttery brioche, their flavoursome meatballs, and even their pesto, redolent of basil.  The food is one manifestation of the pride and effort the folks behind Robot put into all they provide; the warm hospitality is another which you won't fail to notice.  Attentive yet unobtrusive, always eager to share more on the provenance of their edibles - these guys are wonderful hosts.  This, despite its low prices for the area.  

I wouldn't necessarily speak in hyperbole about Robot*; it's more a "consistent, high batting average" kind of place.  It doesn't have "the absolute best salad!" I'd head to Salad Shop with its dozens of customisable options, though then I'd have to deal with massive lines and sometimes surly staff.  Nor does it have "the absolute best coffee!" For which I'd trek to Nylon at Everton, where the excellent folks do beautiful coffee, and only coffee.  But whatever does Robot serves they do do well, and I'm always very pleased to get my salad and coffee from them. 

Also, take note of the quirky, hand-painted murals. There's so much to spot!  Visiting Robot is like hanging out in the home of your cool, arty, ultra-foodie friends.

*Actually, Robot has the best cafe ambassador in the form of four-legged Baileys

Located at the ground flour of heartland mall. Hidden in this mall lies a small gem called the double spout café. Been here twice because it had good food. 
Both times I had the beef lasagne and the mixed fruit tea in a jug. 
The beef lasagne was quite small but it had a generous serving of cheese, tomato sauce and ground beef to make your mouth crave for more. The lasagne had potato wedges and a small serving of garden salad with it. The potato wedges is pretty average but the garden salad is very fresh!
The mixed fruit tea is delightfully sweet and has loads of fresh fruits like lychee, apples, oranges and strawberries in it!!!
Beef lasagne- 8/10
Mixed fruit tea- 9/10

To a late night party goer, this is paradise. The most extensive range of late night food you could probably ever find, and when you're tipsy, or tired, or happy, the food will still taste great no matter what. Even sober, the food here doesn't disappoint, and while it's no Tony Roma's or Chilis, but they do offer a great variety of Western and local wares to keep you satisfied.

I am a big fan of the fact that they server truffle fries here. Truffle fries! At 3 am in the morning, truffle fries are a godsend. Haha jokes aside, I have seasoned truffle fries connoisseurs tell me that the ones served here aren't half bad at all. Their food options cover the whole spectrum, from your fish'n chips, to prata, they have almost anything you could think of whilst inebriated. Or sober.

Here are a couple of the dishes I have tried which are mention worthy and some you should definitely try when visiting Spize. Their roti john chicken special - cheese, mushroom, chicken goodness on bread. Their maggi goreng seafood pattaya - maggi, with seafood and a tinge of orange spicyness wrapped in a hot omelette, nuff said. Their truffle fries - as mentioned above. Their fish and chips - fried crispy goodness with tonnes of fries. Their bangers and mash - good ol' sausages with creamy mashed potatoes and an equally tasty gravy to match. Their nasi goreng - they've got multiple variations of fried rice, be sure to give them all a try. There's a reason why there's more than one type. 

I could go on but you get the jist. I think the magic in this place is that it comes alive late at night, and is always full of sights and sounds way past midnight. Fantastic for eating those post party blues away. Also fantastic for drunk people watching at 4 am in the morning when you are hungry and cannot go to bed. 

Their only downside, when it gets crowded, be sure to expect that orders will slip through the cracks, and you may end up waiting for some time before those truffle fries finally arrive at your table.

Iced Doi Chaang', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Iced Doi Chaang'}]
text:
Hipsters, this cafe is not for you. You would feel uncomfortable here as there are no racks of reading materials, glowing filament bulbs, or shaggy bearded baristas with man buns. But what you will find at Doi Chaang is a friendly welcome and a helpful attitude. Searching for a late lunch, I came across Doi Chaang and was greeted by Joseph working the front of the house. He told me about their cafe's special organic coffee, which is ranked in the top 1% worldwide by Kenneth Davids, but you be the judge. With some help from Canadian backers, the beans are cultivated & exported by the Akha hill tribe in Northern Thailand.

For lunch, I decided on the recommended green curry rice which was tasty but typical, though the side of chili and baked egg & cheese was a nice touch. Permanently listed on the menu board are sandwich and waffle options. I spied also some cakes that looked pretty moist and fresh. The curry was likely a daily special. 

Ordering the iced Doi Chaang was perhaps not the best choice to enjoy the characteristics of the single-estate brew, but it was still quite enjoyable. Reminds me a bit like dark chocolate. Will need to return to try and try a naked cup next time. United Square Mall wifi is freely available.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/UCB0PL9OJDJKsYR-uDrvVg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/common-man-coffee-roasters-singapore?reviewid=5jYUQDvJUMzprH095kIqYw&select=UCB0PL9OJDJKsYR-uDrvVg', 'altText': 'Photo of Common Man Coffee Roasters - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
What a space. The "WOW" effect hits you even before you enter. If you grew up in a neighbourhood with white lions outside the house, then this is nothing new. It's quite the same. It has two huge birds placed by the entrance. 

The bar is spectacularly decorated with aeropress, drip filters and a dark horse like synesso. Everyone is sleek and well mannered. The staffs are extremely friendly and take the initiative to understand you and your dining experience. Spa Esprit persona score! 

Food is very flavourful, fresh, and delicious. A friend and I came here for lunch. Our food came quickly but it was served separately. So we had to wait for each other's food to arrive. Both of us ordered salads which were very refreshing. 

Coffee is good but I can't help to admit the ceramic cups are not meant for coffee drinkers like me. It is most preferredwith tea, but this is just personal. Nevertheless, the clay plates are amazingly beautiful which adds a whole new level to the dining experience. Have yet to return for desserts. But first, I need to save up. 

This place is pricey for their food. Definitely setting a different scene and drawing the coffee crowd to a wider approach to appreciating caffeine and food.

Jimmy Monkey came highly recommended for its coffee and that was the main reason behind my visit to this off location. The space sort of screams hipster in name, design and look of the staff. That is not necessarily a bad thing as it often can deliver some good food and beverages.

The coffee was pretty good and clearly better than any random place but still not really impressive wither. If it would have been around the corner I could have visited again but not at all worth traveling this far for. Also had a decent brekkie muffin and a pasta with mushrooms. Not bad but also a bit overpriced.

What was however a pleasant surprise was that the staff were friendly and helpful. Service was also smooth and fast despite the place being packed.

text:
Little House of Dreams is a homegrown bakery and one-stop party decorations specialist that offers bespoke cakes, cookies, cake-in-a-jar, freshly baked goods, party supplies, party decorations and even party props rentals.

They have experienced party stylists to create bespoke dessert tables to suit any theme and occasions such as weddings, baby showers, parties, corporate functions and photo shoots.

Little House of Dreams also conduct baking workshops at their baking studios or at a location convenient for the customers. Their sister shop, Dreams and Confetti, offers a specially curated selection of party supplies, imported tableware, pretty cake stands from USA, candies, trinkets, gifts and much more.

Little House of Dreams has recently launched a new savoury food menu in December 2015 which features burgers, pastas, pizzas, salads, sides and sweet treats. One noteworthy point is that the dough for the burgers, pizzas and pasta are all hand made in-house at the Little House of Dreams.

REVIEW

The hot foods here are all prepared by their talented pastry chefs. As the Little House of Dreams' forte is in baking and bespoke dessert creations, we find that their savoury food items would require a little more fine tuning.

Being a fairly new establishment, the Little House of Dreams has great potential for growth, with their great desserts, cosy ambience and friendly service with a personal touch, and I will be happy to return to try their new offerings.

text:
We visited on a Friday afternoon, one of the few restaurants on Dempsey that could accommodate us without reservations. I got the set lunch, consisting of a salad/soup, main and dessert, for $38++. It was decent though not fantastic, main gripe though, was that the service was achingly slow. 

- Roasted pumpkin salad with Roquefort cheese: more pumpkin than rocket, and it was slathered in a heavy glaze. It was a bit heavy tasting, though the pumpkin went well with the cheese. 

- Grilled Norwegian salmon, chorizo and shaved fennel: presentation was good and the diced chorizo in beans was tasty. While the salmon skin was nice and crispy, the fish was slightly overcooked, tough and bland. 

- Sweet corn panna cotta, popcorn and truffle oil: slightly too firm but went nicely with the popcorn. The truffle undertone definitely added an interesting twist to the dish. 

I also heard good things about the hangar steak and prawn linguine that my friends opted for. 

Seems like the dinner items seem better than the lunch. Would love to return to try!

Went to eat there with a group of friends and they had ran out of bagels...
Annoying, especially having travelled there specifically from seeing good reviews.
if you are a tourist , try different shops. if you are unlucky you wont get your money worth.

text:
Quite quiet on a Thursday evening. Staff are not really attentive but otherwise friendly and warm when you get their attention. 

Let's talk about the food!
Aglio Olio - I like their version with sun-dried tomatoes thrown in. The pasta by itself is not very tasty but if you put some bits of sun-dried tomato and garlic slices into it, each bite can be quite delightful. This came with 6 juicy plump prawns that went great with the pasta. 

Beef Burger - They asked for the level of "done-ness" and added they only do medium and up. So I clarified that medium rare is no no and waitress repeated "medium and up". So we opted for medium and when the Burger arrived, we were surprised that the patty is very thick and when we cut into it, it was fairly pink. Strange for a 'medium'. 

Smoked Salmon Pizza - Fairly generous with the salmon slices. The pizza was toped with a drizzle of avocado mayo. Interesting combo. My girl liked it enough. 

Pepperoni Pizza - This pizza was really covered with pepperoni slices! With such a generous coverage of meat, how not to be nice? 

Tiramisu - Quite a decent bowl of "yummy"! Really quite a good serving of tiramisu, not too dry nor wet, with loads of cheese. 

Can come back again!

text:
Not a bad place!

I've been here almost every time I'm doing some work on my laptop, and at the same time waiting for my boyfriend to finish his workout at a nearby crossfit box from here.

This place is like a hipsterized old warehouse.. I enjoy staying here for long hours Infront of my laptop. It gets really crowded during lunch hours, but at 4 onwards it gets super empty. Oh, and it's not that easy to spot this place from outside as it has no signage which is cool. It's not like the usual in-your-face type of place. It's a hidden gem with yummy food!

I've always ordered Brave Begedil - which is very yummy. The portion for this one is not very big, so if you are that hungry this meal wouldn't be that filling for you. I looove the turkey bacon! 

I've also ordered lavender latte. Iove love love.

Came here looking for Cafe Tiffany's (I even paced around the entire library to double check that it hadn't moved to another corner), and I found this underwhelming shell of what Tiffany's used to be. Got a latte ($4.80) that was way too overpriced, the power sockets were all taken (and when I tried to use the ones that were next to my sofa, the staff told me they weren't for 'customer usage'). 

There wasn't anyway the people using the sockets were going to vacate anytime soon, so, peeved and pissed, I left for the Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf at Tanjong Pagar which yielded much more promise. It's a sad, sad shame when a chain café brings more comfort than a supposedly 'comfortable' setup.

text:
Seen this place numerous times and finally step in here today. Does not help that they only open at 11am... Usually go looking for food before that on a weekend... 

Came here after a heavy breakfast, looking for coffee. Ordered a Long black and it is good. Generally don't like the sourness in black coffee that some cafes tends to do. 

Pastries, tarts and cakes looks absolutely delicious! Can't wait to come back next time to try them. They do have savoury and breakfast menu too. 

At this time of the day, things are quiet, two tables (besides myself) occupied. There are sofa seating are and tables and chairs, big enough of a setting. 

Going to come back for the food next time around 

Update : quiche and salad meal is nice :) price tag at $8.30, plus a coffee with that nice light meal for under $14.

And now the tarts/cake ...

text: Good amount of food options (like really tons of food options) and lots of seating. It's easy to find (only a few steps away from the MRT). There's also lots of variety. There are essential Singaporean foods like bee hoon and also Cantonese foods like chopped meat. I would definitely come back.
