Ugly Salmon Cakes', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Ugly Salmon Cakes'}]
text:
The ambience and decor of the place isn't great, doesn't have a very welcoming feel nor is it stylish - the concrete walls are painted in terracotta and left plain with wooden tables and chairs being the main decorative item - resulting in the noise bouncing off the walls and echo-ing around the cafe.  

The food however is pretty decent - the burger and wedges were good, moist and tasty although the burger could have been a slightly bigger portion for its price especially when you compare it to the big breakfast your neighbour is having next to you :P  

I had the ugly salmon cakes which were pretty good - the mash they used in the cakes were very buttery and tasty, but it could have done with some batter and extra time in the pan - and also some cheese I think.  Although simplicity in cooking is the key, these salmon cakes lacked a little depth in its flavour.  Otherwise no complaints, great portion size, and the salad that came with it was fresh.

What I found slightly strange was the iced mocha that I ordered - it really wasn't milky enough, as you could tell instantly from the colour. It didn't taste bad, just not what an iced mocha is really! There was an overpowering taste of chocolate / cocoa powder - bit too much for my liking.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=tieQ1FQ3BdXO7PjShPE28g', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Bern T.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Bern T.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=tieQ1FQ3BdXO7PjShPE28g', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 1, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 80, 'eliteYear': None}
text:
The fare at Open Farm Community was wholesome, soulful, exquisite, and quite simply, sustainable clean-eating at its most delicious.

Be sure to make reservations: we didn't think reservations were necessary on a Thursday evening, but boy were we wrong; the restaurant was a full-house, so we were "banished" to the counter seats at the bar.

We had:

1) 'Hail Caesar' ($25): a novel deconstruction of the classic green salad, with romaine lettuce cups cradling tender slabs of smoked chicken, layered with 5J jamon, the thickest ever parmesan crackers, slicked with a light horseradish caesar dressing, and finished with soft-boiled egg confit and garlic croutons. This was well-executed, elegant, incredibly balanced, and the best caesar salad I've ever had. A must-try.

2) Sweet Corn & Basil Soup ($19) chunked up with charred baby corn, caramelised onion strips, and mopped up by fluffy hunks of pita bread - velvety smooth and nuanced.

3) Mud Crab Pappardelle ($29): the sweet flecks of shredded crabmeat complemented the mild Thai curry gravy swirled with coconut milk, dotted with yellow squash, and topped with fried Thai basil leaves. Despite the spice, this was very restrained.

4) 48 Hour Barolo Braised Oxtail Strozzapreti ($26): unabashed and bold, the smoky sweet of the wine highlighted by the heft of the meat, and cut through by fresh thyme and parmesan crisps.

5) Coconut Laksa Barramundi ($29): outstanding as well, the skin of the fish seared to a tantalising crackling, yielding luscious moist flesh underneath. This was sided by an otah-potato cake blend, blanched bok choy and garnished with chilli oil beads that looked like ikura

Downgrading a star. We ventured off our menu go-tos and were very disappointed. We left half of our I Love NY and Mexican burrito dishes on the table. Just wasn't very edible. 

Stick to the Spanish and the Tunisian.

Salted egg pork rib rice', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Salted egg pork rib rice'}]
text: head to the 5th floor at far east plaza at lunchtime and you'll probably notice a long line forming outside this place. most people are queuing for the zi char dishes, but there's a separate line for the salted egg yolk pork ribs. you probably can't go wrong with any of the other dishes (i hear the popcorn chicken is great) but definitely try out the pork ribs. for $6, you'll get a plate of rice and these delectable pieces of fried pork smothered in a slightly sweet yet savory salted egg yolk sauce. you can even add on stuff - i paid $1.50 more for some greens. it's not the cheapest (nor healthiest) hawker center dish but it's really good. lines can get really long, so be prepared to wait.

Itty bitty breakfast. So little avo. Very disappointing.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Itty bitty breakfast. So little avo. Very disappointing.'}]
text:
Came for breakfast two days in a row. 

First visit: Sunday breakfast/ brunch, ordered eggs royal and was pleased. Happy to return the next day as I was going to be in the same area. 

Second visit: Monday morning at around 9am. Ordered one of the breakfast sets, toast with avocado and coffee. This was incredibly disappointing. The toast, while good quality, was tiny. And the worst bit, the portion of avocado was unacceptably small. Not even 1/8 of an avocado was provided - just three and a half (barely) Super thin tiny slivers of avo which I had to strategically spread out in order to get some in each bite. After eating I felt like I hadn't even had breakfast. Really a shame they scrimp on this and ruin an otherwise great potential breakfast option. 

Would have been 5 stars but after my breakfast I cannot rate this cafe so highly.

text: You can't take photos in the store but you can whatever you want if you're having tea!  Service was outstanding and the truffle sandwiches were so good.  The Parisian tea set with two teas and snacks for two was $70.  So worth it.  And you can drink from the $200+ teapots and admire all the TWG branded swag like the linens, all porcelain, etc.  They have so many teas - it's ridiculous.  I'd recommend coming here at least once!

text:
Had high expectation for a delicious affogato since I was heading to THE affogato bar. But seriously, my least favorite affogato I've ever had. 

La opera is not my thing. The espresso was so bitter, the overly sweet chocolate ganache, almond sponge is all too much. The best part? Dark espresso ice cream but more like just normal coffee ice cream. And you can get away with $4.50 for one scoop. My buddy Lippy and I paid $15.90 for a bunch of Bla. ya.... should have just gotten a Milo Dino McFlurry.  yup, nice ambience, nice service but the affogato not so nice. 

#latergram #affogato #drklingeats

Having tried the famous and amazing Paul patisserie in Paris, I was elated about the news of the opening of Paul Bakery at Ngee Ann City. Sipping a hot cup of coffee and biting into a warm butter croissant on a chilly winter day in Paris was the most memorable experience and I thought I could relive it here in Singapore at Paul Bakery.
 
Although the seating was really cramped, the interior of Paul did remind me of Parisian patisseries. The chandeliers, French paintings and even the waitresses in white chef hats really simulate the setting of French restaurants.
 
Food-wise, there were a few hits and misses. The highly recommended Chocolate Mellefeuille was a let down because the pastry was not crispy but limp instead. The chocolate flavor was good though, rich and not overly-sweet. The Praline Macaron was great, crusty on the outside and filled with creamy rich praline. The Caneles have a really good texture as well.
 
The service was slow, probably because they were short of staff. It was difficult getting the attention of the waitstaff and the food took pretty long to arrive.

My friend and I ordered The Italian and Mexican Hot Dark Chocolate drinks. 

The Italian drink was a bit too thick to drink and didn't taste unique.

If you like to spice up your hot chocolate, I'd recommend the Mexican drink. I could taste the spice from the cinnamon and nutmeg. However, the spice tapered after a couple of sips. 

Though it was good, it wasn't worth $7.50 for the drinks, especially since the drinks got cold really quickly.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/1rzSXUGVNhiaNNX2gS5_oA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/spize-singapore-2?reviewid=pev7dXmJr1JHv-NcBMT-iw&select=1rzSXUGVNhiaNNX2gS5_oA', 'altText': 'Photo of Spize - Singapore, Singapore. Pre- and post-party place to be.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pre- and post-party place to be.'}]
text:
You can love it or hate it but Spize is a necessary establishment in every party-goers life. If you're done at Zouk and need food, and you probably will, skip the amazingly overpriced food stand outside zouk that serves no purpose but to rip drunk people off. 
Instead, head straight to Spize which is so nearby, will still be open and has food that tastes good whether or not you're intoxicated. 

The menu is really extensive, as is the seating. As a vegetarian, there are plenty of options - the usual nasi goreng and mee goreng (both about $4, as there are a few kinds) can all be done veggie style, though you might want to repeat your order a few times to make sure they get it right (this goes for anywhere, really). 

More favourites are the drinks like ice limau (lime) and longan. The Blue Longan drink is awesome as well. It's basically just processed fruit and colouring, but it's exciting. Because it's blue. Who needs cocktails, right?

HOW DO YOU MAKE SO MANY FLAVOURS WHEN YOU ARE A SHOP ALONG A STREET WITH NO PARKING AND THEN YOU STAY OPEN SO LATE AND -- okay so the caps exclamation is to express how impressed I am at the commitment this business has. This isn't their first store in Singapore, but is certainly a pretty big one (two stories counts as pretty big, yes). They're on East Coast Road, and they're open till 11pm most nights, which I think is an amazingly smart move, since I only popped by when I got done with a late dinner and was looking for dessert. 

As the story goes, the founder is a French guy who started this business in Vietnam, before deciding it was a viably exportable brand. I realise at this point that I'm not telling you much about my experience here, so let's change that.

I had a great experience here. The staff member at the counter was lovely - she patiently (and pretty cheerfully) let me try half a dozen flavours, and even gave me suggestions. I settled on the Young Rice flavour, which reminded me of rice pudding, in a very good way.

She answered all my inane comments and questions, and I remembered being impressed by how she handled herself and the shop alone. She helped make this walk in customer a fan. Yes, I'm a fan. Of Fanny.

They started the hype and it's probably here to stay. Still one of my favourite go to spots for a healthier lunch option offering a good selection of restaurant level selections for you to mix and match. With the likes of Daily Cut right around the corner though, I would only wish they could lower their price just a bit to contend with the almost negligible difference in quality.

Very cool old school coffee bean store on Balestier open since 1959 (since 1960 in current location).  They actually have a very cool website, but everything else is old school, from the way they will pack up the beans to how the old couple will wrote down your purchases for inventory in a notebook.  As the other review noted, the owner has two types of beans here: blends for local coffee and single-origin beans.  I purchased 250g of Guatemala beans for half the price of other places (only $10 SGD!), and the quality is much better than places like SBUX.  I don't know why I didn't come here earlier, as I drink a lot of coffee at home.  Will also have to try some of the other  single origin beans from South America, Africa and Asia as well, and perhaps one day, I might even try to learn how to make a proper kopi as well :).

Had the portobello mushroom salad, a macadamia nuts cookie and an iced cafe latte. The mushrooms were really huge and juicy. Its really different from portobello that I had at many other cafes which is usually dry. The salad dressing was a little gooey but it tasted fine. The cookie was bad - hard, dry and pretty tasteless.

Whenever I am at Mohd Sultan, I will usually end up at Laurent Bernard Chocolatier for desserts. Love to end my night with the souffle.  The soufflé is delicious. Just the right fluff with rich Valhorna chocolate oozing out and paired nicely with the ice cream.  When you are looking for a nice presents, you can also buy their pralines.  It makes great gifts.

Be prepared to wait especially on friday and weekdays as they can get very crowded.

text: Service was friendly and the quality of food was laudable. The environment was comfortable and feels at home. I had a pleasant experience and every vegetarian restaurant visit will throw me some surprises. Even though I love exploring new places, I do not mind making a return for vegetarian food at Warung Ijo.

text: A pretty awesome view, in fact one of my favorites in Singapore without requiring a cover charge. While a dinner here is pricy and I have only tried it once (was delicious). The drinks are very reasonably priced and their own craft beer and craft beer cocktails are well worth the visit. Sometimes the balcony gets rather crowded but usually you can get a table after 20-30 minute wait or can always enjoy the view and come back inside for drinks. Overall I highly recommend to visit here. In terms of food - I had the steak + shrimp combo dish and it was well prepared and presented though expensive!

text:
Bought more cheese tarts today and I have to say, after trying the long queue cheese tarts from across the hall, I much prefer the original lava cheese tarts from Bread Society! They raised the price to $2.40 per tart or buy 5 get 1 free, which works out to be $12 for 6, which is a great deal.  

The lava cheese filling is velvety smooth, very creamy and rich.  I think they tweaked the cookie crust recipe a little, because the cookie tart shells are still crunchy two hours later from when we got home.  My eldest son loves to eat them semi frozen with a firmer center.  

No queue, reasonably priced and delicious!

text:
Food is so so only.

The long black I had is very bitter and acidic. Same for the cappuccino.

The poached eggs on the Portobello are over-cooked. The yolk is more or less solid and not gooey.

Music is too loud, not able to hold a decent conversation at all.

Spize is another one of those post party supper places people flock to in the middle of the night. This place is open till late, and can get crowded over the weekend. There's a HUGE variety of dishes to pick from, so you'd be spoilt for choice. 

They have all kinds of pratas, both sweet and savoury, as well as murtabaks to choose from. I like the mutton and cheese murtabak. It's huge and stuffed with ingredients.

Rice or noodles? Take your pick. Most of the fried rice or noodle dishes here are pretty standard. Satay here is decent, but pricier than most other hawker centres. In fact, all the local dishes here cost a little more than average.

There's also a western menu available, but I've never tried any of those dishes. Neither have my friends, so I can't really comment on that.

The toilets here are usually filthy, and the floor is really oily. Tread carefully, especially if you are inebriated. They set up rows of tables and chairs on the walkway outside their shop, and the next 3 shops on either side.

Parking around here is a real pain when you've got the post-party crowd in. Most people park on the streets illegally. Watch out for drunk people crossing the road as well, as some of them park on the little streets across the road from Spize.

Chocolate eclair', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Chocolate eclair'}]
text:
Love the pastries here. The chocolate sea salt cookies are an exact match to the Pierre Herme chocolate sea salt cookies - decadently chocolatey with the zing of salt to keep things happening. 
They also do a lovely crumbly buttery salted egg yolk cookie for Chinese New Year. 
The chocolate eclair is also very decent - some places have their eclairs sitting in the display cases slowly drying into cardboard crumbliness. But Patisserie G's eclair is fresh enough that the choux has a crisp shell and light interior. Helps too that the cream filling is usually richly flavoured. 
They've done well enough over the years to expand to additional seating outside the shop. I love their morning breakfast offerings - croque monsieur, buttery croissants and lightly brewed coffee.  
Good place to hang out, chill over a cuppa and a nicely made sweet.

The perfect lunch', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The perfect lunch'}]
text:
My newfound love! 
Healthy slow-cooked meal made fast in the form of westernized mixed rice with price fixed at $16 nett for each bowl. Add-ons are available with prices from $1.5-$3.
Choose your grains, meats, veggies, sauce and toppings! My fave combo is brown rice, salmon, mushroom, beans, pumpkins and cucumbers with miso caramel sauce and furikake as toppings. Really delicious meal for lunch & dinner. Generous portion and extremely filling!!!! The place is so spacious as well. You can have your coffee too supplied by Papa Palheta what a nice collab!
This branch operates on weekend too!

I've been back 3 times in 2 days. :D

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/STiwtTJ1VjUBUWPc0wSFFA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/the-assembly-ground-singapore?reviewid=Nkh-4-fu-mX0_p0O0D8KqQ&select=STiwtTJ1VjUBUWPc0wSFFA', 'altText': 'Photo of The Assembly Ground - Singapore, Singapore. Beef rendang Mac and cheese.. the combination is pure genius!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Beef rendang Mac and cheese.. the combination is pure genius!'}]
text: My new favorite brunch place in the city area. Spacious location, well spaced tables, friendly staff are just a start. The real magic is in their food. Great ingredients and excellent combinations. We got the assembly brunch and the rendang Mac and cheese and we were beyond delighted with the food. It was timely, hot when served and the portions were generous. Pair it with one of their smoothies and you may be set for a wonderful day ahead.

Love this place for getting some work done! There's an array of seating from stools to couches to tables with pillows. There's also outlets by some of the couches to give you enough juice to keep going for hours. The wifi was no fuss (no re-logging in and very speedy). 

Amazing coffee, including the drip coffee. I tried the Indonesian drip, which had a slightly more bitter flavor and tinge of sour. Lattes and signature coffees can be pretty pricey at S$7-9, but the drip is affordable at S$3.20.

Gets busy around lunch hour around 11-2pm, but quiets down during the mid-afternoon. Highly recommend for a place to chat with others, chill on your own, or hunker down and get some work done.

text:
A nice place in the botanic gardens; nice ambience great for brunch and a quiet gathering 
Very spacious space; great for events 
The food was passable ; not extremely fantastic but still pretty good. 

Had the pulled pork pasta - pork was a little too salty; wasn't spicy enough and slightly too oily : however it was okay 

Latte was Normal as well; so was the carbonara - nothing too memorable. 

Wouldn't go back especially for the food but is a good chill and nice hang out place after a run in the botanic gardens or for brunch out of the city

2 Blur Guys is a relatively new burger shop set up in Orchid Hotel. Its concept is simple - a stripped down quick meal place which serves quality food at reasonable prices. The menu is simple - there's a list of less than 10 burgers to choose from, and each burger comes with a side of potato salad and greens. Portions aren't massive, but they're pretty filling. 2 Blur Guys also serves desserts such as brownies and ice cream. The restaurant is nothing fancy, but it serves as a functional place to grab dinner at with friends.

We had the mushrooms, fries, bouillabaisse, shepherd pie, carbonara, cream of mussels and gula melaka cake this time. 

The mushrooms were delicious, consistent with my previous visit. The carbonara was decent but not a must have. The bouillabaisse and shepherd pie were a little disappointing, considering they were the chef's special. The portions were small and did not taste what I expected of a bouillabaisse and shepherd pie. The gula melaka cake is what made this review a 4 instead of 3 - it was a little sweet but would have been perfect with a coffee. 

I would still recommend coming if you need a halal restaurant and am in the area.

Coffee is good though thank goodness but not good when cold

text:
This branch is located in Bugis Junction near the Hotel Intercontinental. I've tried to patronize this place for the pass 3 occasions but always has to wait. Today I was there with my son and a friend. Perhaps they brought me luck. Even though the place is air conditioned it can be quite warm because of the glass ceiling letting the sun in. On a cooler day this place is great. Seats are comfy and the dessert looks good. 

My son had the Caramella Mixed Fruit Crepes and Raspberry milk shake. I had the cold brew 
coffee and my friend ordered the Dome Surprise. All these taste good! I liked the coffee and the Dome Surprise. The milkshake is a bit too sweet for me and my boy. 

The staff is available when you summoned them. They have 3 to tend to the whole place on a Sunday afternoon and yes they forgot my cold brew and milkshake. Had to remind them. 

Other than that it's been good to escape the crowd of the shopping area. Will try again when it's not so warm, maybe at night.

text:
I wish they had a broader food menu and a greater ability to alter dishes that are non-veg. Specifically, I would have been very happy to try the Raunchy Eggs, if only they left out the anchovies. Alas, it seems to be pre-mixed, and a violent head shake from the kitchen staff (that I saw from afar) told me customization was a no-go. Too bad, they are missing out on the revenue. I always order toast, poached egg, and avocado. 

I also always order the lavender latte, which is amazing. No problems with the spare decor as there is plenty of clear table space, which is what I need more than tchotchkes all over the place.

text: As with any other toastbox, they serve very nice local coffee. This outlet however is slightly pricier. They do have a two tier pricing I realize, $2.20 for kopi o at premium outlets like this (another example would be MBS) and $1.70 for heartland outlets. I am fine with this since they probably have higher rental to pay and the price is still cheaper than your western coffee. Will leave this review as a short and sharp one.

text: I think if you are lost or duno where to go even if you are not hungry you can find a suitable haunt in this place. Any type of food is found here. delicious array of dishes. thanks.

Kinda cool vibe indoor outdoor and not too hot. Not familiar with the vibe which I guess is like an old timey coffee shop or harkens back to colonial times. Am always uncomfortable with that bc yeah it might've seemed cool but was not cool for the majority of those not in the elite. Anyhow it was cool enough in the evening inside and they had mixed chairs and cool wood floor etc. just be careful if ur inside and then you moved your chair back and one leg falls off the elevated floor and u could fall and hit ur head. The food was actually pretty good - the Indian food only. We had chicken not the spicy one and it was juicy and citrusy and delicious. Also had the Dahl and the baigan bartha and naan and plain rice and one more thing. But it was all tasty and very spicy but good. The service was meh. I asked for ginger ale and they said no we don't have it. I pointed out on the menu where it was listed. Was advised they don't have it anymore. Asked what on this list they had. They have juice and coke. There were five more things listed. Ok I'll just have water. Have to flag them down if you want anything so they don't check back. But at least they don't bother you and let u stay to chat. They're not clearing ur plates as soon as ur done which was my experience in most other restaurants in Singapore.

text:
decent-alright japanese-styled-french cakes at this tiny cafe in duxton hill. flor patisserie is pretty well-known for its light, japanese cream-type cakes, but I hadn't gotten to it previously on my dessert circuit precisely because of those characteristics: I like my cakes hefty and substantial, and these fluffy, creamy things do little for me.

but for its class, the desserts are good - certainly worth a visit if you're into this sort of thing. there's no way to get around this - this place is pretty much fantastic for women (and persons inclined toward the delicate and feminine). it's a small white-walled space with a large window that lets in plenty of light at brunchtime, and the counter is laid full with colorful, dainty little cakes with all sorts of fancy frosting and glazes.

we had five cakes from the selection on offer that day - mango (the unanimously-declared winner of the day), strawberry, yam, chocolate and blueberry - and whilst there was a mix of textures from millefeuille and the sponges, all the cakes felt the same.

everything's certainly gorgeous - but all a little too light and substantial. of course, this opinion speaks more of my preferences than the skill of the kitchen; if you're into this sort of thing, it does well enough (and you might also want to try its famous ex-chef's new venture: his eponymously-named chef yamashita).

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/PPAzWMTAwQOcceowrXrsDg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/two-blur-guys-singapore?reviewid=vBzjaQkZYgY_fugtcJqmyQ&select=PPAzWMTAwQOcceowrXrsDg', 'altText': 'Photo of Two Blur Guys - Singapore, Singapore. delicious burger and a very nice beer', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'delicious burger and a very nice beer'}]
text: The best burger in Singapore... where is the six star rating? When I asked for a medium rare burger, I finally got what I had never gotten in this city-state, a medium rare burger. The finishing was perfect, from the bread to the meat to the greens served with it. The fries were amazing too, and the mayo with the fries and the burger was to die for. I'm not one to like mayo very much, but this one, this one is something different. Had a pecan pie for dessert which is quite nice, and the beer selection is quite affordable and varied. I honestly wish I could write more, but I don't want to waste any of your time while you read this review instead of going and having the best burger here. You'll thank me for it!

text: I knew I had to at least try a traditional Singaporean breakfast before leaving.  The menu is stripped back and simple - choose from coffee/tea kaya/kaya french toast all for the equivalent of about 5 quid.  This is a stripped back (as others have mentioned) cafe and if you're in a rush it's probably best to order at the counter and take it to go - once you seat yourself it's all about getting the attention of the staff, so you definitely need to make your presence known by a few waves and constant eye contact. My food came out piecemeal - coffee, then 10 minutes later eggs, and another 15 later the toast but luckily I had the whole morning to hang around so enjoyed people watching in the interim.  This was clearly a super popular spot, and you can see why. If you like a breakfast on the sweeter side, you'll likely enjoy this runny egg/jam and french toast like concoction with sweet Singapore coffee. Be prepared for the sugar rush that follows and don't forget to bring your own wet wipes/napkins (probably an obvious for most of you used to Singapore but I was constantly walking around with sticky hands!)

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/hZ6dI19dvGm1E73kmL27Hg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/sinpopo-brand-singapore?reviewid=gFw7VqaTvd4m0PoBeQdbjw&select=hZ6dI19dvGm1E73kmL27Hg', 'altText': 'Photo of Sinpopo Brand - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
This restaurant is really a hidden gem in Katong!

I don't usually start my reviews like that so that's how good an impression it made on me. We stumbled upon it completely by accident and thought it was going to be overpriced and modified local food not done well. Boy were we wrong.

The ambience was nice with a touch of local culture such as the old fashioned shutters in the corner. We tried the sng muay pop and the milo dinosaur for drinks and both were impeccable. Especially the milo dinosaur (I confess my love for milo now but there is nothing more heavenly than a milo dinosaur done right)

The har jeong Kai wings for starters turned out great as well, juicy with a slight crisp. The mains were good too. The crab bee hoon was hearty and tasty and the nonya kiam chye arg tasting relatively authentic.

Didn't have space for dessert but I guess that means an excuse to visit again. And that's nothing to complain about.
